nato leaders are looking toward better relations with the soviet union, encouraged by mikhail s. gorbachev's new policy of openness but demanding that he back up his words with deeds
we are looking beyond pronouncements,'' the western alliance said in a final communique that called on the soviets to respect human rights and make a ``speedy and complete withdrawal'' of red army troops from afghanistan
the 16 nato leaders on thursday wound up their two-day summit, the first in six years, in a show of solidarity that glossed over differences on arms issues and applauded superpower efforts to reduce long-range nuclear weapons
president reagan claimed a mandate for his planned spring summit in moscow and said nato was ``ready to get down to business'' on strategic arms talks
he said the medium-range nuclear weapons treaty signed by the united states and the soviet union last december was ``a direct result'' of alliance unity
the alliance, troubled by a dispute over the modernization of short-range nuclear missiles in west germany, sidestepped a direct confrontation on that issue and produced an upbeat proclamation of unity
the leaders pledged to maintain a nuclear presence in europe to deter a soviet attack, and called for a reduction in soviet bloc conventional forces. the west says the soviet bloc has a substantial edge in five major ground categories
nato said ``the search for improved and more stable relations with the soviet union and the other countries of eastern europe is among our principal concerns'' and called for efforts to reduce east-west tensions
the statement noted ``encouraging signs of change'' in the policies of the soviet union'' that create ``the prospect for greater openness in their relations with their own people and with other nations.''
but we look beyond pronouncements for tangible and lasting policy changes addressing directly the issues dividing east and west,'' the communique said
we agree that the speedy and complete withdrawal of soviet troops from afghanistan and effective restoration of that country's sovereignty would be of major significance. it is against these criteria that we shall assess general secretary gorbachev's recent statements,'' the statement said
the nato leaders were united in their assessment of the alliance and its goals
we're strong, we're united, we're prosperous and we're free,'' said reagan
underscoring nato's commitment to keep nuclear weapons in europe, he said, ``all of us understand the absolute necessity of maintaining the credibility of our deterrent.''
there is no doubt whatsoever that the agenda we have set now is the right one for nato,'' said british prime minister margaret thatcher
french president francois mitterand said ``this is one more step toward disarmament, with all the necessary precautions.''
the harmony of the meeting had been threatened by west germany's reluctance to replace older short-range nuclear weapons with newer, more effective ones
most of these weapons, if fired, would hit german soil, east or west, and the modernization campaign has inflamed disarmament passions in west germany
in a compromise, the communique avoided use of the word modernization, to which west germany objects. instead, the document said nato will maintain ``an appropriate mix of adequate and effective nuclear and conventional forces which will continue to be kept up to date where necessary.''
nato secretary general lord carrington said the word modernization _ perhaps because of translation problems _ ``means in the minds of a number of people in different countries in europe the introduction of new and more terrible and more destructive weapons.''
however, he said it was more likely that the new weapons would be ``more accurate and may very well be of less destructive power.''
malaysia plans to ban people under 21 years old from nightclubs, bars and pool halls in kuala lumpur, prime minister suleiman mohamad said today
suleiman told reporters the age limit was being raised from 18 to maintain a good social image for the capital
legislation was being proposed to impose the ban, he said
suleiman said entertainment centers would be fined about $200 if they allow in underage customers, and the youths would be fined a similar amount if caught
here are excerpts from the official text of the final communique agreed to thursday at the conclusion of the nato summit
we, the representatives of the 16 members of the north atlantic alliance, have come together to re-emphasize our unity, to assess the current state of east-west relations, to review the opportunities and challenges which lie ahead, and in so doing:
_to reaffirm the common ideals and purposes which are the foundation of our partnership;
_to rededicate ourselves to the principles and provisions of the washington treaty of 1949;
_to reassert the vital importance of the alliance for our security, and the validity of our strategy for peace. ..
the security in freedom and the prosperity of the european and north american allies are inextricably linked. the long-standing commitment of the north american democracies to the preservation of peace and security in europe is vital
the presence in europe of conventional and nuclear forces of the united states provides the essential linkage with the united states strategic deterrent, and, together with the forces of canada, is a tangible expression of that commitment. this presence must and will be maintained
likewise, a free, independent and increasingly united europe is vital to north america's security. the credibility of allied defense cannot be maintained without a major european contribution. we therefore welcome recent efforts to reinforce the european pillar of the alliance, intended to strengthen the transatlantic partnership and alliance security as a whole
the atlantic alliance cannot be strong if europe is weak
our aim will continue to be to prevent any kind of war or intimidation. by maintaining credible deterrence the alliance has secured peace in europe for nearly 40 years
conventional defenses alone cannot ensure this; therefore, for the foreseeable future there is no alternative to the alliance strategy for the prevention of war. this is a strategy of deterrence based upon an appropriate mix of adequate and effective nuclear and conventional forces which will continue to be kept up to date where necessary
while seeking security and stability at lower levels of armaments, we are determined to sustain the requisite efforts to ensure the continued viability, credibility and effectiveness of our conventional and nuclear forces, including the nuclear forces in europe, which together provide the guarantee of our common security
taking into account the structure of the alliance, each of us undertakes to play his part in this joint endeavor in a spirit of solidarity, reaffirming our willingness to share fairly the risks, burdens and responsibilities as well as the benefits of our common efforts. ..
we want gradually to overcome the unnatural division of the european continent, which affects most directly the german people. we will continue to uphold the freedom and viability of berlin and to support efforts to improve the situation there
the search for improved and more stable relations with the soviet union and the other countries of eastern europe is among our principal concerns. we call upon these countries to work with us for a further relaxation of tensions, greater security at lower levels of arms, more extensive human contacts and increased access to information. we will continue the effort to expand cooperation with the east wherever and whenever this is of mutual benefit
we have noted encouraging signs of change in the policies of the soviet union and some of its allies. this creates the prospect for greater openness in their relations with their own people and with other nations. ... but we look beyond pronouncements for tangible and lasting policy changes addressing directly the issues dividing east and west
however, we have to date witnessed no relaxation of the military effort pursued for years by the soviet union. the soviet union persists in deploying far greater military forces than are required for its defence. this massive force, which the soviet union has not refrained from using outside its borders, as is still the case in afghanistan, constitutes a fundamental source of tension between east and west. ..
arms control is an integral part of our security policy. we seek negotiations not for their own sake but to reach agreements which can significantly reduce the ris of conflict and make a genuine contribution to stability and peace. ..
the recently concluded inf agreement between the u.s. and the soviet union is a milestone in our efforts to achieve a more secure peace and lower levels of arms. ..
consistent with their security requirements, the 15 allies concerned will make use of all possibilities for effectively verifiable arms control agreements which lead to a stable and secure balance of forces at a lower level. for them, the comprehensive concept of arms control and disarmament includes:
_a 50 percent reduction in the strategic offensive nuclear weapons of the u.s. and the soviet union to be achieved during current geneva negotiations
_the global elimination of chemical weapons
_the establishment of a stable and secure level of conventional forces, by the elimination of disparities, in the whole of europe
_in conjunction with the establishment of a conventional balance and the global elimination of chemical weapons, tangible and verifiable reductions of american and soviet land-based nuclear missile systems of shorter range, leading to equal ceilings. ..
genuine peace in europe cannot be established solely by arms control. it must be firmly based on full respect for fundamental human rights. as we continue our efforts to reduce armaments, we shall press for implementation on the part of the governments of the soviet union and of other eastern countries of all of the principles and provisions of the helsinki final act and of the madrid concluding document. ..
we agree that the speedy and complete withdrawal of soviet troops from afghanistan and effective restoration of that country's sovereignty would be of major significance. it is against these criteria that we shall assess general secretary gorbachev's recent statements
we hope that at their forthcoming summit in moscow president reagan and general secretary gorbachev will be able to build upon the progress achieved at their washington meeting last december. we strongly support the efforts of the united states
here are the house members who switched sides on the two contra aid votes thursday. the first vote was on adopting the democratic plan for $30 million in aid. the second vote was on passage of the entire bill

switching from yes on the first vote to no on final passage:
democrats: bates, california; boxer, california; roybal, california; schroeder, colorado; durbin, illinois; jacobs, indiana; smith, iowa; early, massachusetts; kennedy, massachusetts; wheat, missouri; applegate, ohio; gonzalez, texas; boucher, virginia; kastenmeier, wisconsin; moody, wisconsin
republicans: leach, iowa

switching from yes to not voting:
democrats: wright, texas

switching from no on the first vote to yes on final passage:
democrats: bennett, florida; fascell, florida; nelson, florida; pepper, florida; ray, georgia; lipinski, illinois; sisisky, virginia
republicans: meyers, kansas; miller, washington; morrison, washington
advocates of using lie detectors to screen job applicants and test employees' honesty have given up hope that president reagan will veto legislation outlawing the practice
the senate, by a 69-27 vote, on thursday joined the house in approving a bill effectively prohibiting about 85 percent of the some 2 million polygraph examinations now conducted each year in the united states
remaining now is only for the house and senate sponsors of the ban to iron out minor differences in the two versions, submit the compromise for passage again and send it to the white house for reagan's signature
throughout his first term and even into last year, reagan had vowed to veto any legislation to restrict private employers in their growing use of lie detectors, allegedly to ferret out thieves and other wrongdoers
labor unions and civil liberties groups argue that the devices are used just as often to intimidate workers or weed out those with pro-union sympathies
with increasing evidence that the tests in most circumstances are poorly administered and produce faulty results between 15 and 50 percent of the time, advocates of the ban have worn down much of the administration's opposition
after two days of extended debate this week stalling the senate action, opponents of the ban gave up their fight when the administration released a statement objecting only to portions of the legislation and avoiding any mention of a veto for the first time
the administration does not have the backbone at this time to veto this bill,'' complained sen. dan quayle, r-ind. ``they have folded up shop, caving like a house of cards.''
crafted by sens. edward m. kennedy, d-mass., and orrin hatch, r-utah _ normally adversaries on labor-management issues _ the senate bill would allow some private use of polygraphs to investigate specific incidents of theft or sabotage
but even then, the tests would have to be conducted by licensed examiners under regulations to be developed by the labor department, and employers would first have to file a police report or insurance claim and detail in writing the basis for suspecting the employee to be questioned
employees who failed the test or refused to take it under such circumstances could not be fired absent other evidence. if they were, the bill allows civil suits against offending employers, and provides for up to a $10,000 federal fine for each violation
kennedy and hatch, respectively the chairman and ranking republican on the senate's labor and human resources committee, complained that an estimated 320,000 ``honest workers'' are branded as liars each year, often losing their jobs or being denied one because of the machines' inaccuracy
conversely, it is a regrettable fact that employees steal,'' hatch said. ``this bill addresses both concerns by barring use of polygraphs where they are most likely to make a false identification but permitting the use of these tests where they are likely to be most accurate.''
both house and senate versions exempt private security guards and kennedy said thursday that senate negotiators are likely to go along with the house in extending the exemption to employees of pharmaceutical companies as well
he said he expects to meet with rep. pat williams, d-mont, the primary author of the house version passed by a 254-158 vote last november, within the next two weeks to begin hammering out a compromise
they ban about 90 percent and we ban about 85 percent,'' kennedy said, predicting the new prohibition will become law before the end of the year ``with or without the president's support.''
hatch credited the united food and commercial workers union and its president, william wynn, for crafting the language that allows use of lie detectors to investigate specific instances of ``economic loss.''
with that provision, absent in the house bill, several business groups representing railroads, bankers, restaurants, brokerage houses, grocers and other retail merchants dropped their opposition
the only major opponents that remained were the polygraph industry itself, the american trucking associations and the u.s. chamber of commerce
we've found them to be reliable and cost-effective, particularly in pre-employment screening,'' said roger middleton, chief counsel for corporate policy at the chamber of commerce. ``this is just an inconsistent attempt by the federal government to address a state problem.''
however, the ufcw's wynn said the large margin by which the senate passed the bill reflects a recognition that the devices are little more than ``the 20th century's equivalent of the dunking stool.''
the commerce department turns 75 today, just four years older than the man who runs it, c. william verity. and verity claims to be ``a late bloomer'' just like the once-staid agency he heads
even as a late bloomer, you can come into the scene and be a player,'' verity said in an interview in his ballroom-size office built in the late 1920s to the specifications of one of the early commerce secretaries, herbert hoover
the oldest cabinet member at 71, the retired chairman of armco steel is still five years younger than his boss in the white house. verity arrived on the scene in october, about the time top-echelon members of the administration plan their returns to the private sector
still, verity's brief tenure has been marked by activism and some measure of controversy
there have been trade skirmishes with japan, turf squabbles with other agencies and resignations of several top officials. verity's outspoken advocacy of closer economic ties with the soviet union has drawn criticism from both conservatives in congress and from some jewish organizations
the agency has come a long way from its creation in 1913 when its main functions included counting the population, inspecting steamboats and maintaining lighthouses
today, the department enforces u.s. trade policy, probably its most vital role in a day of $170 billion trade deficits. it also collects and analyzes economic data and serves as home for the census bureau, the national weather service, the bureau of standards and a host of other agencies
it serves, now as in the past, as the business community's advocate within the halls of government
verity had retired in 1982 as chairman and chief executive officer of armco, then based in ohio. the retirement ended when he was picked by president reagan to head the sprawling agency after the death last summer of malcolm baldrige, who had been commerce secretary since 1981
baldrige, who was extremely popular with the agency's 38,000 employes and members of congress, died in a freak rodeo accident
although under baldrige the commerce department had been the lead federal agency on dealing with congress on trade legislation, verity has moved into other areas and pressed ahead with his own pet projects
one has been more fully automating the department's many activities. another was pressing for commercializaton of space _ an effort verity said gave him a quick lesson in heading a government agency since it brought him into conflict with the national aeronautics and space administration
nasa doesn't want anybody else out there,'' he said
i think you find out you're not in charge,'' he said. ``there are a lot of people who have a piece of the action who have to get on board. the mission in private business is to get something done. in government, it's to move toward solving a problem, but to get everybody on board with you as you try to solve it.''
and that just requires a lot of time and a lot of massaging of people's feelings and testing this and testing that.''
he said his present priority is a program to help smaller companies export more
i think our economy is going to be export-driven this year,'' he said. ``our department feels we should do whatever we can to encourage small and medium sized companies to get into the export game.''
his no-nonsense approach, particularly his tough stance toward japan, has won him a lot of fans in the business community. just a few days on the job, verity threatened japan with retaliation if it didn't do more to open its markets or adjust its prices to match the lower dollar
while japanese officials protested, the tough talk from a man who speaks softly and slowly won him fans among u.s. industries battered by japanese imports
other secretaries and other u.s. spokesmen have not been urging the government to start speaking in plain language to these guys (the japanese),'' said richard muller, a washington representative for chrysler corp
verity also delighted conservationists by recommending sanctions against japan last month for the killing of minke whales in violation of international whaling regulations
but, sighed verity: ``i never had any idea i would be in charge of whales some day. and i had no idea it would take so much of my time.'' campus; picks up 5th graf pvs, `tillard will ...'; subs 11th graf pvs, `on monday ...' with two grafs to update with ban.</note>
a black student activist at the university of pennsylvania was under 24-hour protection thursday after receiving a death threat, and an all-white fraternity was banned from campus for hiring two black strippers for a party
earlier thursday, about 300 people rallied at dartmouth college in a protest against bigotry
the threat was made against conrad tillard, director of the organization of black consciousness, which had called for the ouster of the primarily jewish fraternity zeta beta tau from the ivy league school in philadelphia
the university had charged that black strippers at a zbt party in september danced naked with a prospective freshman pledge before a jeering audience shouting racial epithets
the threatening letter was sent to a reporter at the school newspaper, the daily pennsylvanian. the writer claimed to be a student member of the jewish defense league
however, school officials said they do not believe the writer is a student, and the jdl denied any connection with the threat
tillard will receive round-the-clock protection by campus police ``as long as it necessary,'' said security spokeswoman sylvia canada
police said they were investigating the letter. the fbi also said they have received the letter but declined comment
the main thing it said was that i was a target on their hit list,'' tillard said. ``it also said that in general they're trying to stop the rise of this black power group that i'm helping bring about.''
in hanover, n.h., the rally was sparked by a conservative off-campus student newspaper's criticism of a black professor's teaching ability and his music course. the night before, about 200 people held a candlelight march
members of dartmouth's afro-american organized the protests aimed at the dartmouth review. four review staff members are charged by the school with harassing the professor, william cole, after confronting him in his classroom over the article
at the rally, music professor john appleton defended his colleague, saying, ``we must find a away to put an end to jim crow, to jingoism, to sexism and to just plain ignorance that the review seeks to foster on this campus.''
on monday, demonstrators at a penn rally sponsored by the organization of black consciousness had called for the ouster from campus of a zbt, which was charge by the university with lewdness, indecent exposure and hazing
late thursday, the 112-member fraternity announced that it had been banned from campus until at least the fall of 1989
the threatening letter did not mention the fraternity incident, tillard said
the racial tension on the campus has been very, very high for a long time,'' said jacqueline wade, director of penn's afro-american studies department. ``this is just one indicator of the level. it's part of a larger whole of racism on this campus.''
penn spokesman bill epstein said university officials believe the death threat was written by a penn student. ``we've checked around,'' said epstein. ``there's no sign of the jdl.''
mordechai levey, international director of the new york-based jdl, said that several jews on campus were affilitated with the organization but that the jdl played no role in the threat
rabbi howard alperg, director of the jewish campus activities board, called the zbt incident deplorable but added: ``to claim that it is now a jewish-black issue is also deplorable.''
there are black radicals who are trying to turn it into a black-jewish issue,'' alperg said. ``that is perceived by jewish students as being anti-semitic.''
relationships between black and jewish students were strained in 1986 during a confrontation over attempts by the black student unity conference to have nation of islam leader louis farrakhan give a speech
farrakhan did not speak; his organization said it was not satisfied with the security arrangements
on wednesday, minority students at hampshire college in amherst, mass., ended their nine-day occupation of a dormitory office after administrators signed a 16-point agreement aimed at encouraging racial harmony
two large holes opened up in a road in eastern england, swallowing a double-decker bus and prompting the evacuation of a small hotel and nearby homes, police said
authorities believe the road near the city of norwich was built above an abandoned 19th century chalk mine
one hole opened under the rear of the bus thursday and the driver ordered the 20 passengers off the vehicle immediately, the british broadcasting corp. reported. but as the driver tried to pull away, the hole grew into a 26-foot-wide gap and another hole appeared nearby
the television report showed the bus with its rear in the hole and its front wheels in the air
chief inspector david cushing of norwich police said city authorities ordered the evacuation of the hotel and nearby homes as the holes grew larger. underground gas, electricitry and domestic water supplies were disrupted
the evacuated people spent the night at a school as workmen attempted repairs
south korea plans to send a buying mission to the united states in may as part of its effort to ease growing trade frictions with washington, government and industry officials said today
the mission, to be headed by nam duck-woo, president of the korea foreign trade association, will tour various u.s. cities for 15 days to purchase machinery and other industrial products, the officials said
officials did not give details of the mission's itinerary or shopping list
the united states has pressured south korea to open its markets wider to american products to cut its growing trade surplus. the united states ran a trade deficit of $9.5 billion with south korea last year
the house has killed its democratic leadership's proposal for a package of ``humanitarian'' aid for the nicaraguan contras, leaving the vacillating u.s. policy toward central america once again in limbo and the rebels without support
the lawmakers voted 216-208 thursday to reject the democrats' $30.5 million proposal that would have provided four months' worth of food, clothing and medical supplies to the rebels and created a new $14 million program to aid children who are victims of the nicaraguan civil war
forty-five democrats, mostly liberals who oppose any aid to the contras, joined with republicans, who thought the aid proposal too weak, to deal it a fatal blow. only five of 176 gop members present voted for the measure on the final ballot
the vote showed the difficulty of coming up with any kind of agreement on the contentious issue. it was a particular setback for house speaker jim wright, d-texas, who had sought to keep the contras in place in nicaragua to pressure the leftist sandinista government into concessions as part of a regional peace process. democrats had hoped, too, that their milder aid package would relieve pressure to give the rebels more weapons later this year
but the surprise outcome also appeared to dim any administration hopes of speedy action to keep supplies flowing to the rebels, who by some accounts are in dire need of food and other non-lethal materiel. previous u.s. aid, and the authority to deliver it by airdrops inside nicaragua, expired tuesday
wright, d-texas, said the vote may prove ``a somewhat pyrrhic victory'' for republicans, adding that he had no immediate plans to revive a contra aid plan
we have thus far done our best,'' wright said. ``it was as good an effort as could be made. i don't know how you would find a better consensus among those who have a sincere effort to help the peace process.''
other democrats vowed to make any new try for aid difficult
as far as i'm concerned, it ought to be a damned lengthy process,'' said rep. david obey, d-wis., a contra opponent who is chairman of the house appropriations subcommittee with jurisdiction over the matter. ``the republicans sandbagged us.''
the vote came exactly one month after the house rejected a $36 million reagan plan to aid the rebels, one which included money for weapons and other military supplies. wright won that showdown partly on the strength of a promise that he would give moderate members of his party a later chance to vote for a purely ``humanitarian'' aid package
we fulfilled our commitment to them,'' wright said after the vote
with no aid plans left before congress, u.s. policy toward the contras _ who were organized seven years ago with u.s. backing _ was in limbo
the confusion was illustrated by conflicting reactions to the vote from president reagan, the contras' most prominent supporter, and a rebel spokeswoman in miami
as he flew back to the united states from a nato meeting in brussels, belgium, reagan said: ``i'm very happy.'' his spokesman, marlin fitzwater, later explained that the president meant he was glad to be able to work on an improved aid package
but contra spokeswoman marta sacasa said the rebels had wanted the aid to pass, and said the united states was turning its back
every time the united states turns its back on the contras, it puts us in a less favorable position,'' sacasa said. ``we are fighting against an enemy that doesn't have these kinds of problems. the aid from the soviet union has not stopped flowing to the sandinistas.''
in drawing up their aid proposal, democrats led by rep. david bonior, d-mich., were faced with the challenge of attracting support from moderate members, many of them southerners, while not alienating the party's liberal wing _ most of whom never have backed the rebels
to gain every possible advantage, democratic leaders had set up an unusual procedure under which their package would come before the house as an amendment to a competing but similar republican bill. the democratic version was adopted on a vote of 215 to 210, thus wiping out the gop version and replacing it with the democratic plan
but minutes later, voting on final passage for the same bill, 26 members switched their votes and the entire package was defeated. the largest group of those abandoning the bill comprised liberal democrats who had been uncomfortable voting for it in the first place
rep. mickey edwards, r-okla., who led the republican debate, said supporters of contra aid were never given an option they could support
this plan didn't do anything,'' he said. ``it was just a lousy, lousy bill. we were saying we weren't going to vote for it, and they didn't believe it.''
one democratic liberal who said he grudgingly voted for the package, rep. george miller of california, said it would have helped encourage the peace process in central america because it sent ``a renewed message to the contras that congress is not willing to provide lethal aid.''
but a contra supporter, rep. dan burton, r-calif., said the bill was ``like throwing a bone to the freedom fighters without any meat on it.''
rep. henry hyde, r-ill., said the democratic package represented ``an invitation to a funeral _ a funeral for freedom.'' and if it passed, hyde told democrats, ``you'll have the guilt you deserve: being accessories to the murder of freedom and democracy in this hemisphere.''
police said they arrested two men late thursday in the slaying of a rookie police officer shot at point-blank range in his patrol car feb. 26 outside the home of a drug witness he was guarding
the men, whose names were not released, had been picked up thursday for questioning along with two women who were later released, said officer peter o'donnell, a police spokesman
details of the arrests in the slaying of 22-year-old officer edward byrne will be released friday, he said
police commissioner benjamin ward had described the slaying as an ``assassination'' meant to intimidate drug witnesses. byrne was killed by shots from a car that had apparently coasted up to his early in the morning
since the slaying, detectives have flooded the queens neighborhood, arresting 256 street-level crack dealers in hopes of extracting information about the killing
shooting at cops, it's just bad for business. i think experienced criminals know that; perhaps these inexperienced ones will learn it,'' ward said
the reward for information leading to the conviction of the killer grew to $130,000 thursday with a $25,000 contribution from members of the new york stock exchange. more than 10,000 officers attended byrne's funeral
wnbc-tv reported wednesday night that investigators identified two men _ including the gunman _ and two women believed to have been in the car from which the shots were fired
a police spokesman, capt. tom fahey, asked earlier about the wnbc report, said, ``the case has not been solved. the reward is still in effect, we still need the cooperation of the community to help us solve this case.''
the broadcast report also said police believed the killing was ordered by lorenzo ``fat cat'' nichols, 29, a reputed drug kingpin sentenced feb. 25 to 25 years to life in prison for narcotics and weapons possession
he is also awaiting trial on charges he had his parole officer killed for revenge
nearly every night for the past week and a half, sen. albert gore jr. has delivered himself by satellite to television stations in super tuesday states for interviews on local newscasts
the tennessee democrat also appeared via satellite for a campaign pep rally with supporters assembled in more than 50 locations and for a question-and-answer session with students on more than 100 college campuses
everybody is having to do things like this in view of campaigning in 20 states at the same time,'' said arlie schardt, a spokesman for gore. ``it's economical and it's the best method of reaching large numbers of voters.''
as the approaching super tuesday primaries strain campaign warchests and candidate schedules, satellite ``uplinking'' is being used by presidential hopefuls to increase their exposure to voters in the cheapest way possible
though many stations refuse these brief interview opportunities, the chance for ``live'' time with the candidates has become attractive to smaller stations in areas where the contenders are not likely to appear in person
but some media experts say the new high-tech tool of the 1988 campaign does not serve the public well
it plays on the vanity of the local media because everyone wants to be seen interviewing a presidential candidate, but the tough questions aren't being asked'' by the local interviewers, said kathleen hall jamieson, a communications professor at the university of texas at austin
the candidates won't run into any sam donaldsons in the 132nd market,'' said stephen hess, senior fellow at the washington, d.c.-based brookings institution, referring to abc's tough, sometimes abrasive white house correspondent
costs for transmitting via satellite vary depending on location and equipment used, but generally it is far less expensive than producing and airing an advertisement
airing a 30-second ad on a boston television station during the popular cosby show program can cost $30,000, while buying 90 minutes of satellite time that can be used for five-minute interviews by 18 stations costs about $2,000, said gary galanis, a spokesman for democrat paul simon's campaign
we at this point don't have the resources to buy even a minimum amount of paid advertising, which would probably be about a million dollars to hit all the super tuesday states,'' galanis said
you can't mold your message as well with satellite interviews, but you can get two to three minutes on a local newscast,'' he said. ``paid advertising ... is the best thing, but the next best thing is satellite uplinks.''
tim archie, a spokesman for republican bob dole, said large stations in major markets are less likely to accept a satellite interview because they are in cities where the candidates are appearing anyway. these stations also often have a reporter on the road with the campaigns
but for other stations, satellite interviews ``give the stations a sense of an exclusive,'' he said
a number of democratic congressmen want the final totals of the 1990 national census adjusted to make up for the many minority group members and city dwellers they say will be overlooked
commerce department and census officials, who have refused to agree to such changes, were criticized thursday at a hearing for making ``shameful'' and ``political'' decisions
every census since 1790 has seen at least some criticism for the so-called ``undercount,'' and the complaints have grown in recent years despite improvements in census taking
officials estimate that in 1980 only about 1 percent of americans were missed in the national head count. but they admit the problem was much greater among minorities and in cities than it was for other groups
studies were launched to try and determine if adjustments could be made to compensate for this problem, but last october the decision was announced that there would be no adjustment in 1990
pointing out that the people usually missed are most often minorities and city residents, where the democratic party predominates, rep. charles schumer of new york termed the decision not to adjust ``shameful'' and ``political.''
he said the action was not based ``on fair-minded concern about accurate statistics; it's a raw exercise of partisan politics.''
schumer's remarks came thursday at a hearing of the house post office and civil service census subcommittee. reps. mervyn m. dymally of california and robert garcia of new york also raised concerns about the decision not to adjust. all three are democrats
commerce undersecretary robert ortner denied that politics were involved in the decision, contending that statisticians disagree on whether there is an accurate method of making adjustments
i don't think it would make the problem any better if we were to devise an elaborate mathematical system to make up new numbers,'' ortner said
the focus of the problem is the fact that all 435 seats in the house of representatives and billions of dollars in state and federal money are distributed on the basis of the figures collected every 10 years by the census bureau
kansas republicans convene saturday to elect the last 14 of the state's 34 delegates to the republican national convention, and it's expected to be a good day for bob dole
all will be pledged to support the kansas senator on the first ballot in new orleans, since dole claimed all but 16 of the 1,249 county delegates elected five weeks ago in the kansas gop caucuses
the convention also will ratify the election of five delegates recommended from congressional district conventions held feb. 20. the other 15 national delegates were elected at the district level
no contests are expected for the 14 slots still to be filled, but some challenges are expected for the final 14 alternate delegates to be elected. kansas also has 34 alternates
gov. mike hayden, sen. nancy kassebaum and other elected officials, party leaders and prominent republicans will claim the 14 open delegate positions, sources said. their election is not automatic, but nobody is expected to challenge them for the slots out of respect for their prestige and position
the 1,249 delegates elected at county conventions feb. 1-7 are all eligible to attend the state convention and vote on the national delegates, but some are not likely to show up
hayden, who is expected to be elected chairman of the delegation going to new orleans in support of dole, and kassebaum will address the convention
state gop chairman fred logan jr. said dole also may talk to the convention by telephone but the senator will not come to topeka
the main order of business is to elect the rest of our 34 delegates for bob dole,'' logan said
the national convention is aug. 15-18 in new orleans
for the first time in canadian history, a member of parliament has revealed that he is homosexual, surprising the public, delighting gay rights activists and provoking right-wing ridicule
svend robinson, of the socialist new democratic party, made his announcement in parliament thursday
we do not choose to be gay or lesbian and are not seeking special rights, merely the right to live openly in dignity without losing our jobs or homes or being subjected to violence,'' robinson, 36, said
his honesty had consequences
robinson's constituency office in burnaby, british columbia, was vandalized last weekend following reports he was about to confirm longstanding rumors about his sexual orientation
premier grant devine of saskatchewan, father of five children, expressed fear that robinson's statement would encourage young people to try homosexuality. devine said his compassion for gays equaled that for bank robbers
pollsters said the declaration may damage the new democrats' chances in the next election
but toronto gay rights activist russell armstrong called robinson's decision a ``quiet act of heroism.''
he set a wonderful example for all of us who have to make that same kind of revelation in our lives,'' armstrong said. ``i feel a kind of jubilation.''
the minneapolis-born robinson explained in an interview with the associated press why he chose this week to make his disclosure after a nine-year parliamentary career which made him the enfant terrible of canadian politics
it was a difficult decision in both personal and political terms. i didn't want to be perceived as a single-issue candidate or a gay member of parliament, but rather as a member of parliament who happens to be gay
for me as for any other gay or lesbian person, it is a liberating experience,'' the legislator said
robinson, whose family moved to canada in 1964, said it was important to make his declaration before the federal election which conservative prime minister brian mulroney may call this year
the new democrats are at a historical high in the polls under their popular leader, ed broadbent, and could vie for power
other factors in his decision, robinson said, were the government's two-year delay in fulfilling a pledge to outlaw discrimination against gays and lesbians, a growing trend of violence and harassment against homosexuals, and ``attempts to link aids to homosexuality by the jimmy swaggarts of the world.''
rather than allowing extreme right-wing fundamentalist homophobia to become stronger, i think it's important that we stand up and say this is enough,'' he said
he denied being pressured into revealing the truth but cited past harassment, including an incident following the 1985 aids death of film star rock hudson. a conservative member yelled across the floor of parliament, ``why aren't you at rock hudson's funeral?''
it stung,'' said robinson, who disclosed his secret in a speech and two major television interviews earlier this week
a lawyer and graduate of the london school of economics, robinson is known as an aggressive spokesman for minority and left-wing causes and has been thrown out of the house of commons several times
broadbent chastised robinson last year for heckling president reagan over u.s. support for nicaraguan rebels when reagan addressed the canadian parliament
robinson's judgment was criticized again this week for saying there are homosexuals in the federal cabinet, a statement he later withdrew. he also said he wished it were socially acceptable to stroll ``hand in hand'' with the man he cares about in vancouver's stanley park
columnist orland french of the toronto globe and mail noted that robinson is justice critic for the new democrats. french commented how odd it would be if the new democrats are elected and justice minister svend robinson were seen traipsing hand in hand through the park with his male lover
is canada ready for this?'' the columnist asked
robinson said he knows of three other legislators who have revealed their homosexuality: labor member of parliament chris smith in britain, and congressmen gerry studds and barney frank from massachusetts
robinson acknowledged ``political risks'' but was confident he would be renominated for his seat this weekend
pollster angus reid said the new democrats would find it harder to shed their fringe-party image. the financial post commented: ``the reality is that there is an undercurrent of fear of homosexuals in canada.''
robinson didn't shed all his apprehensions. he asked a reporter if his story would reach u.s. newspapers. ``i've got relatives in the states and some are aware and some aren't,'' he said. increase</head>
a sharp increase in methane gas in the atmosphere since 1978 probably will make earth warmer and may worsen seasonal losses of protective ozone over antarctica, scientists say
but the 11 percent increase in methane in the past decade also may slow depletion of the ozone shield over the rest of the planet, said f. sherwood rowland and donald r. blake, chemists at the university of california at irvine
their nasa-funded study was published today in the journal science
methane is the major component of natural gas, but about 80 percent of atmospheric methane comes from decomposition in rice paddies, swamps and the intestines of cows, with some contribution from wood digestion in termites, rowland said
humans are responsible for increased methane levels because they are raising more cows, growing more rice and chopping down tropical forests, which provides food for more termites, said atmospheric scientist pat zimmerman of the national center for atmospheric research in boulder, colo
researchers generally agree that by trapping solar heat like glass in a greenhouse, methane, carbon dioxide and pollutants are likely to warm earth's lower atmosphere by 3 to 5 degrees by the year 2050
they fear this ``greenhouse effect'' may cause crop-threatening droughts and partially melt polar ice caps, which could raise sea levels up to 15 feet and threaten coastal cities
ozone is an air pollutant at low altitudes, but in the stratosphere it shields earth from harmful ultraviolet radiation. scientists say reduction of the ozone layer will cause more skin cancers and might trigger climatic changes
in 1974, rowland and chemist mario molina first warned that the ozone layer was threatened by man-made chlorine compounds called chlorofluorocarbons, or cfcs, which are used as refrigeration coolants, aerosol propellants and for making plastic foams. the united states banned spray-can cfcs in 1978
mounting evidence indicates cfcs are responsible for the worldwide loss of about 1 percent of earth's ozone shield and the formation of a hole that forms in the ozone layer above antarctica for a few months starting every september
blake and rowland said methane increases may worsen the ozone hole by aiding formation of ice clouds above antarctica. that's because studies by molina and others suggest the clouds enhance chemical reactions that allow chlorine from cfcs to break down ozone
as methane rises into the polar stratosphere, it breaks down and releases hydrogen, which combines with a chemical called hydroxyl to form water, which in turn freezes into clouds, blake explained
outside antarctica, wind and higher temperatures prevent formation of stratospheric clouds, so methane attacks chlorine from cfcs, reducing the amount of chlorine available to destroy ozone, blake said
the 11 percent methane increase ``will make the ozone hole over antarctica more severe. it will probably make the ozone depletion in the rest of the world less severe,'' said molina, of the national aeronautics and space administration's jet propulsion laboratory in pasadena
he said the increase ``will make the greenhouse effect more severe.''
rowland and blake also said that because increasing atmospheric methane reduces the amount of hydroxyl present, it indicates the atmosphere is losing its ability to cleanse itself of pollutants. hydroxyl reacts with many pollutants and removes them from the atmosphere
their study also indicates the rate of increase in methane gas slowed slightly during the past five years
blake and rowland collected air samples regularly between january 1978 and september 1987 at up to 60 locations around the pacific to measure methane levels
earlier studies suggested methane levels more than doubled during the previous 200 years. based on that, blake and rowland calculated methane increases may have raised the amount of water vapor in the stratosphere by 28 percent since the 1940s and by 45 percent over the past two centuries. public</head>
american jewish leaders ending a visit to israel say they are still troubled by the ongoing violence in the occupied lands but are convinced that u.s. jews should air their criticisms in private, not public
it is a formula supported by prime minister yitzhak shamir, who told the american jewish leaders this week: ``it is absolutely un-jewish and very dangerous to join an anti-israeli front with non-jews'' by publicly chastizing israel
the 42-member presidents of major american jewish organizations met in jerusalem for a week-long annual conference that ended thursday
morris b. abram, the group's chairman, said he had arrived with ``a good deal of anguish, a good deal of anxiety and misgivings.''
other american jewish leaders also have spoken publicly of their concern over seeing nightly television footage and reading daily news reports on the israel army's tough tactics to quell three months of unrest in the west bank and gaza strip
reports of troops using excessive beatings of palestinians and burying alive four arabs near nablus heightened that unease
but abram said that, after private meetings with israel's political and military leaders, ``i have not the slightest doubt the policy is to use restraint ... and the time is not right to publicly criticize israel's handling of the unrest
the question is not whether american jews have the right to express dissatisfaction. of course they do,'' abram said in an interview with the associated press. ``the question is, on matters of israel's defense and security, is public criticism effective or prudent?''
shamir called on the u.s. jewish leaders to stifle outspoken criticism among their ranks
every critical statement of a jewish leader does much more harm than many violent demonstrations in gaza,'' shamir said. ``it is inconceivable that, god forbid, american jews would permit themselves to be used in the campaign against us.''
not all u.s. jewish leaders agree they should be silent partners with israel
we as jews need to cut through our illusions and self-delusions about israel,'' albert vorspan, vice president of the union of american hebrew congregations, told the organization
he said american jews should speak out about their concerns and warn israeli leaders that ``the tv pictures that multiply every day are potentially explosive'' in terms of israel's image abroad
vorspan also expressed frustration that israel's divided government seemed to be throwing away a chance for peace
he described u.s. secretary of state george shultz's middle east peace mission as ``a shuttle between shamir and (his rival, foreign minister shimon) peres.''
the deep divisions in israel's government concern some u.s. jewish leaders as much as israel's inability to put down the anti-occupation unrest. some warn that that issue is potentially more damaging to israel's relations with the united states than the riots themselves
zvi rafiah, a retired israeli diplomat who served in israel's embassy in washington, said u.s. leaders are alarmed because israel appears ``incapable, even incompetent in resolving one of its most important problems, the peace process.''
in a speech to the jewish leaders, rafiah warned: ``the palestinian problem has become a time bomb in our relationship with the united states.''
actor burt reynolds says that for a long time he felt it was impossible to marry an actress, but he's changed his mind
reynolds, 52, says he'll probably marry longtime steady loni anderson, 43, within the year, and that they want to have children
it's so difficult for an actor and actress to get married, to fight for the mirror,'' he said in an interview in the current issue of us magazine. ``loni has been successful in breaking down all of those things.''
reynolds also said ms. anderson has suffered the classic ``dumb blonde'' misperceptions
she's a college graduate, an art major and she's taught school. she's raised a fabulous daughter,'' he said. ``all of that speaks for itself. that's part of what makes me so proud of her.''
added ms. anderson, ``you'd think that when i peroxided my hair my brains went down the drain.''
academy award-winning actress bette davis says she set aside five years to establish herself as an actress. sixty years later and a month away from her 80th birthday, she's still working
miss davis, born april 5, 1908, is preparing for her role in a new larry cohen thriller
miss davis, who wrote the best seller ``this 'n' that,'' has overcome a mastectomy and a severe and temporarily crippling stroke to keep working
she has just moved from the east coast to a hollywood apartment
i've never been all that fond of southern california weather and i miss the east,'' she said in a recent interview. ``but i decided i'd become too much of a hermit. i needed to get back in the world.''
as for her birthday, ``i haven't quite decided what to do on the day. on my 70th, i put a black wreath on the front door. but to be working on your 80th birthday, that's quite something.''
