a $9.4 million damage award to the family of a woman whose killer was hired through a soldier of fortune magazine classified ad is ``sending out a warning'' to other publishers, the jury foreman says
an attorney for the magazine said it would appeal thursday's verdict in favor of gary wayne black, 18, and his grandmother, marjorie eimann, 64, who sought $22.5 million in their lawsuit
this fight goes three rounds like a lot of first amendment cases,'' said soldier of fortune attorney larry thompson. ``we lost the first round but put your money on us in the next two rounds.''
after deliberating for 12 hours over three days, the jury awarded black $1.5 million, $400,000 to mrs. eimann and $7.5 million in punitive damages to the plaintiffs
we're sending out a warning or message to other publishers that ads placed in a certain context can be a very dangerous message and publishers as such should be responsible,'' said jury foreman herman castex
sandra black, black's mother and mrs. eimann's daughter, was shot to death feb. 21, 1985, at her home in bryan, about 90 miles northwest of houston
mrs. black's husband, robert, is on death row for paying john wayne hearn $10,000 to kill her. hearn is serving three life terms in florida for that slaying and two others
robert black contacted hearn through a classified ad hearn placed in late 1984 in soldier of fortune, the self-styled ``journal for professional adventurers.''
in a pretrial decision, u.s. district judge david hittner ruled that the boulder, colo.-based magazine and parent company omega group ltd. could not enjoy full first amendment protection because of the ad's commercial nature
this will have no effect on the legitimate press,'' said plaintiffs' attorney ron franklin. ``soldier of fortune knew in fact that it was advertising for contract killers and that offers no first amendment protection.''
publishing and legal experts were not as certain
when magazine publishers' advertising people hear a big verdict based on this kind of ad, they may be more concerned than necessary to accept controversial advertising,'' said slade metcalf, chairman of legal affairs for the new york-based magazine publishers association
these kinds of cases really open the door,'' said david protess, a professor at northwestern university's medill school of journalism in evanston, ill. ``there's very little case law on media negligence. there are almost no precedents.''
attorneys said it could take 18 months before the case reaches the 5th u.s. circuit court of appeals in new orleans
mrs. eimann shook hands and hugged the six jurors after the verdict. ``i lost a daughter and he lost a mother,'' she said, looking at her grandson. ``we felt something had to be done to save other people's lives.''
soldier of fortune publisher robert k. brown said the verdict would not affect the future of his publication, which sells about 150,000 copies monthly
please understand this was a terrible tragedy, a terrible crime,'' he said. ``we have a great deal of empathy for them, but we didn't do it.''
this means every publisher is going to have to read every ad and look into the minds of those placing the ad,'' brown said
hearn's ad in four issues of soldier of fortune read: ``ex marines. `67-69 nam vets. ex-di, weapons specialist _ jungle warfare. pilot. me. high-risk assignments. u.s. or overseas.''
attorneys and witnesses for the family said ``high-risk assignments'' meant hearn and others placing similar ads were willing to commit crimes
soldier of fortune witnesses defended the publication as a legitimate military journal and described the ads as providing employment for vietnam veterans as bodyguards, security workers or mercenaries overseas
but the family's lawyers linked at least nine other crimes to ads before september 1984, including a 1982 houston murder-for-hire case
a white house commission has adopted its chairman's recommendation to pour an additional $2 billion a year into the the fight against aids
the panel unanimously approved retired navy adm. james d. watkins' 60 pages of suggestions thursday night during a brief business meeting that wrapped up four full days of hearings on a variety of topics _ such as testing and protection against discrimination _ that are to be addressed in subsequent reports
watkins had outlined his recommendations at a news conference last week and they were formally considered by the full commission on monday
the final version contained no substantive changes although there were some additions to emphasize particular areas of concern
for example, a paragraph was added to emphasize ``that available data do not provide a basis for comfort or complacency to any segment of our society. ... we express our concern that inaccurate and misleading statements suggesting that (the virus) cannot be spread through heterosexual activity could stimulate transmission among those who would see such reports as bases for ignoring the danger that does, in fact, exist.''
in a section on drug abuse, a sentence added to say: ``in addition to direct transmission, the use of drugs that impair judgment can contribute to sexual transmission.''
that had been suggested by commissioner theresa l. crenshaw, a physician who specializes in sex therapy and has expressed the view that alcohol, marijuana and other drugs can lower inhibitions and result in people engaging in risky sexual behavior that they otherwise would avoid
the bulk of the increased spending called for in the report _ about $1.5 billion a year in federal and local funds _ would go directly to attacking intravenous drug abuse. the rest, all federal funds, would go for development of drugs to treat the disease and additional ways of caring for aids patients, such as more group homes for those who do not require constant hospitalization yet are unable to care for themselves
the recommendations are geared toward the establishment of a `treatment on demand' system for iv drug abusers, whereby treatment would be immediately available for any iv drug abuser,'' the report said
health authorities are convinced aids is spreading most rapidly among iv drug users _ who often pass the virus by sharing contaminated needles _ and their sexual partners and offspring
it is estimated that there could be as many as 20,000 babies infected with aids by 1991, most of them catching it directly or indirectly from the estimated 1.3 million iv drug users in the nation
the other two sections of the report focus on patient care and basic research for drug development to treat the disease
the commission recommends expanding resources for the food and drug administration, expanding community based clinical trials and ``removing placebos in clinical trials whenever possible.''
the section on patient care says the aim is ``to promote a continuum of comprehensive, accessible, cost-effective high quality care for persons infected with hiv.'' hiv is the medical term for the aids virus
three young men standing on the side of a road were killed and a fourth injured when they were hit by a passing van that then fled the scene, authorities said
fairfax county police spokesman walter carmichael said the accident occurred about 10 p.m. thursday in a suburb of washington, d.c., as the victims were attempting to change a tire on the car in which they had been riding
witnesses told police that a white van struck the youths as it passed their car, knocking them between 25 and 50 feet, carmichael said. the three were pronounced dead on the scene, while the fourth victim was rushed to fairfax hospital, where his condition was not immediately available
names and ages of the victims were not released, although carmichael said all three appeared to be in their late teens or early 20s
an all-points bulletin was issued for the van, but carmichael said witnesses provided little more information than its color
vice president george bush holds a strong lead over rival bob dole among likely gop voters in south carolina's primary, according to a poll published today
the washington post said bush had the support of 49 percent of 1,000 people who said they would vote in the gop primary, while dole had 26 percent, pat robertson garnered 14 percent and new york rep. jack kemp claimed 7 percent
among those voters most likely to go to the polls _ those who said they were certain to vote, had voted in 1986 and strongly supported a specific candidate _ bush had 55 percent support to dole's 22 percent and robertson's 17 percent. figures for kemp were not provided in that category
the post survey, taken over six nights ending wednesday, had a margin of error of plus or minus three percentage points. the south carolina contest takes place just three days before the big round of super tuesday primaries and caucuses concentrated in the south
the post survey found that even among several different categories of christians, former television evangelist robertson was not the favorite. among voters who said they watch television evangelists almost every week, bush got 44 percent to robertson's 27 percent
the core of robertson's support, according to the poll, was among voters who placed high priority on moral and social issues
about 83 percent of robertson's backers said their main reason for supporting him was his stand on pornography. robertson's stand on abortion was cited by 78 percent of his supporters as a big factor. about half cited concerns about ``declining moral standards'' or school prayer as the biggest reason for their support
a house panel chairman investigating fbi conduct says a bureau official used mccarthy-like tactics when he disclosed unproven allegations against an anti-reagan organization
in a floor speech thursday night, rep. don edwards, chairman of a house judiciary civil rights subcommittee, likened the disclosure to misuse of fbi files by the late sen. joseph mccarthy in the early 1950s
mccarthy used ``investigatory information from the fbi'' to label government officials as communists without proving the allegations, edwards said
edwards' panel and the senate intelligence committee are investigating the fbi's march 1983-june 1985 probe of opponents of president reagan's central america policy. the lawmakers want to know whether the bureau improperly investigated political activity protected by the first amendment
the intelligence panel held a public hearing feb. 23, at which fbi executive assistant director oliver b. revell sought to justify the bureau's investigation. the probe focused primarily on the committee in solidarity with the people of el salvador, but it broadened to include a number of other groups and individuals
revell released a report that detailed some of the allegations against cispes, none of which were proved by the fbi
during the mccarthy era, it was a common practice of the fbi to secretly disclose investigative, file information to congressional committees,'' edwards, d-calif., said
if the fbi responds to criticism by doing publicly, before tv cameras, what it once did privately, then we have not come very far at all,'' he said
fbi spokeswoman sue schnitzer said: ``mr. revell testified at the request of the committee. this was an open hearing and therefore the information provided at that hearing was not of a classified nature.''
edwards said he was not trying to prove or disprove the information, but said the allegations amounted to ``guilt by association'' since no charges were ever filed against cispes or its members
some of the information released at the hearing was made public previously under a freedom of information act lawsuit filed on behalf of cispes. other information disclosed at the hearing had not been made public before
edwards called revell's disclosure of ``unsupported allegations'' at a public hearing ``a major violation of the key rule for police investigatory files _ that none of the information can be published except according to established rules and safeguards.''
improper release of file information by the government ... is a violation of the constitutional and statutory right of privacy and can cause grave injury to innocent people or groups,'' edwards said
among the allegations that edwards said should not have been released:
_claims that some cispes members were ``involved in the distribution'' of a soviet-forged document to the media
_a statement that cispes was ``believed to have been established with assistance of'' the communist party of the usa
_linking cispes' political support of the salvadoran guerrilla group fmln to terrorist actions by that organization, suggesting, according to edwards, that ``cispes was somehow connected with these actions.''
_a possible connection between cispes and two bombings in washington, because one took place ``about the same time'' of a cispes rally in the capital; and responsibility for the second was claimed by a group with positions ``similar'' to those of cispes
the fbi never brought any charges against cispes or its members
the government says a weeklong military exercise in the falkland islands set to begin monday is not intended to provoke argentina, noting that fewer than 1,000 troops are to take part
argentina, which claims the islands it calls malvinas, lost a 74-day war with britain for their possession in 1982 and still has not formally declared an end to hostilities in the south atlantic
a communique thursday from argentina's foreign affairs and defense ministries said argentina has adopted plans for ``vigilance and defensive alert'' during the british exercise and, if necessary, ``will execute corresponding defense plans.'' it did not elaborate
britain's minister of state for the armed forces, ian stewart, told the house of commons thursday night that fewer than 1,000 troops and only a small number of aircraft would take part in the exercise, code-named fire focus
stewart said the exercise involves an airlift and is part of a defensive strategy to keep a minimum of troops in the islands about 400 miles east of the southern argentine coast
the british defense ministry announced last june that it was reducing the strength of its falklands garrison, but refused to disclose the size of the cut. published reports at the time said the move would cut the garrison then consisting of more than 2,500 troops by about 400
britain completed an international airport at mount pleasant near the falklands capital of stanley in june 1985. the airport can take wide-bodied military jets, enabling britain to fly in reinforcements at short notice if necessary
stewart said the development of contingency plans for a massive airlift had enabled britain to halve the size of the garrison
he gave no figures for the present strength of the costly garrison but added: ``such a substantial reduction of the military presence ... serves to confirm that our purpose is entirely defensive.''
a defense ministry spokesman, who in accordance with british practice declined to be named, said later: ``we are not intending to increase the tension down there ... there is nothing significant about the timing of it (the exercise). it is not meant in any way to be provocative to argentina.''
a foreign office spokesman said britain recently notified argentina through swiss diplomatic channels that the exercise was purely one of reinforcement
diplomatic ties between britain and argentina, cut during the 1982 war, remain severed. dukakis strong</head>
vice president george bush had a commanding lead over bob dole in the south and jesse jackson was in front on the democratic side in the race for votes before super tuesday primaries and caucuses, according to a poll published today in the new york times
the cbs-times poll, based on telephone interviews between sunday and wednesday of 2,251 likely voters in 14 southern and border states, found bush in front with 44 percent over dole's 20 percent, pat robertson's 12 percent and rep. jack kemp's 3 percent
in the democratic contest, jackson garnered 21 percent support to 14 percent for michael dukakis and 12 percent for albert gore jr., according to the cbs-times poll, which had a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percentage points. rep. richard gephardt had 10 percent, gary hart 8 percent and sen. paul simon, 2 percent, the times said
another poll, by cable news network and usa today, indicated bush leads dole 48 percent to 27 percent in the south
among democrats in the south, the cnn-usa today poll suggested dukakis had 19 percent, jackson 18 percent and gephardt and gore, 14 percent each
the poll was conducted feb. 23-28, with a margin of error of 5 percentage points, the newspaper said
still another poll, this one in today's editions of the los angeles times, said jackson had the support of 23 percent, followed by dukakis and gore with 16 percent each
the poll surveyed 964 people across the super tuesday states who were likely to vote in the democratic primaries. the margin of error for democrats was 4 percentage points in the poll, which was conducted for five days, ending monday
on the republican side, with a 5-point error margin from 766 voters surveyed across the super tuesday states, bush held a nearly 3-1 lead over dole, getting 61 percent of the backing. dole got 22 percent
meanwhile, an nbc news-wall street journal poll found that nationwide, the race appeared to be narrowing on the republican side to a two-man race between bush and dole and on the democratic side to a two-man contest between dukakis and gephardt
the poll, based on telephone interviews with 1,368 likely voters between sunday and tuesday, found bush leading dole 39 percent to 31 percent, with his lead widening to 45 percent to 24 percent over dole in the south
the nbc-journal poll found dukakis with 29 percent being trailed by gephardt with 17 percent. jackson had 10 percent, it said
the poll had a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage points
federal researchers could find no new or unusual pathways by which aids spread in a study of 2,059 people who apparently contracted the deadly disease from unknown sources, says a report published today
another new study concluded that routine screening of surgical patients for the aids virus is unwarranted because it would wrongly identify as many as 130,000 people as having the virus for every surgeon it saved from infection
even though surgeons are very important people, somehow changing the lives of 130,000 people to protect one of them doesn't seem quite right to me,'' said one of the researchers, dr. stephen g. pauker
both studies were published in the journal of the american medical association
the national centers for disease control in atlanta investigated 2,059 cases of aids recorded through the end of september in which there was no evident means for the patient to have acquired the infection
cdc researchers concluded that known but undetected risk factors were probably responsible
the risk factors are male homosexual contact, intravenous drug use and receiving tainted blood transfusions or blood products, the researchers said. other factors are sexual contact with people infected with the aids virus or at high risk, and residency in a country where aids is passed mainly through heterosexual contact
it can be concluded the disease is still following patterns of transmission that have already been identified, said co-author dr. kenneth g. castro
we've had six or seven years of epidemic,'' he said in a telephone interview thursday. ``we should have had some change by now'' if other modes of transmission existed
although the aids virus has been detected in saliva, tears and urine, there is no evidence for believing it can be passed through these fluids, according to an accompanying article by dr. alan r. lifson, a public health specialist with the san francisco department of public health
of the 2,059 cases, 921 were eliminated because no detailed medical history could be obtained. another 825 were found to involve risk factors that had not been identified originally
an additional 32 cases were excluded because the patients had been incorrectly diagnosed as having acquired immune deficiency syndrome
that left just 281 cases for which no risk factors seemed to exist, the researchers said
the patients or relatives in about two-thirds of these cases were questioned. it turned out that 34 percent of those subjects had a history of other sexual disease and 38 percent had visited prostitutes, the researchers said
the findings suggest that the group with no known risk factors ``probably represents a mixture of persons who either had undetected risk factors or were sex partners of persons in high-risk groups,'' the researchers said
the 2,059 cases were among a total of 41,770 reported to the cdc through september since june 1981, when record-keeping began
by monday, a total of 54,723 cases had been reported. of those, 30,715 died
in the study of pre-surgical screening, doctors at boston's new england medical center concluded that routine testing for the aids virus was unjustified
for a surgeon to get an infection, three things must happen,'' pauker said in a telephone interview wednesday
the patient must have disease, the surgeon has to stick himself or herself, and the infection needs to be transmitted,'' he said. ``the (chance) all three events will occur is quite low.''
pauker and his colleagues said a surgeon's likelihood of getting infected while working on an infected patient is between one in 130,000 and one in 4,500, based on figures for surgical accidents and their frequency of causing infection
the researchers weighed this against prevalence of the aids virus in u.s. populations _ ranging from one in 100 to one in 10,000 _ and the lowest known false-positive test rate for people who are screened _ one in 20,000
the researchers found that for every surgeon saved from infection, between 22 and 130,000 people would be falsely labeled as aids-infected. the researchers said those people then would be told they were infected and perhaps would be denied surgery
aids desroys the body's defenses against disease, leaving a person prey to life-threatening infections and certain cancers. him</head>
jesse jackson accused the democratic party leadership in the south of a ``sustained effort'' to thwart his presidential candidacy, but said it's not working
he said he has a two-pronged message that will reap strong support for him on super tuesday, with its round of caucuses and primaries, concentrated in the south
jackson said one part of his message is the need to rid our society of drugs, a message that brings an enthusiastic response wherever he goes
the other, he said, is that a ``growing body of american working people feel abandoned by the law'' and are turning to him because he addresses their concerns
jackson made the comments in an interview thursday aboard his campaign plane flying here. he declined to predict how well he will do in tuesday's critical primaries. but he expressed cautious optimism that his ``economic justice'' theme is reaching whites as well as his traditional base of black support
one can never be...certain what's going to happen tuesday night,'' he said, but added: ``my sense is there's a higher comfort level,'' among whites about his candidacy
asked about exit polls following february's iowa caucuses and new hampshire primary that showed his white supporters were mostly upscale and well-educated rather than the working class he is appealing to, jackson said:
that is changing. iowa led the breakthrough. people were wrestling with an ancient cultural barrier.''
by the time maine held its democratic caucuses last weekend, jackson contended, the working class had become a main force behind his second-place finish
drugs, he tells his audiences, are the no. 1 ``national security threat'' against the united states today. people respond to that, he said, because ``every parent knows their child is threatened every day by drugs ...people see this as a moral issue of our day.''
as president, jackson says his priorty would be to beef up the customs and border patrol interdiction efforts, press drug-producing nations to develop other crops, and crack down on corruption in law enforcement agencies and banks that work with the drug traffickers
the democratic candidate is criss-crossing the south, touching down at five states per day for rallies at schools, churches, and auditoriums to shore up his widespread black support and woo new white voters
on thursday, jackson held events in arkansas, oklahoma, mississippi, but had to cancel a trip to new orleans because of a tornado watch that grounded his plane. instead he spoke by telephone to a church full of people who were waiting for him
the campaign is filled with made-for-tv events to augment the $100,000 tv ad campaign that begins today in several southern states
casual conversations with voters along the campaign trail reveal some sentiment that white voters are more willing to support jackson than they were in 1984. several said the race issue is far less of a concern
jackson represents something we've needed a long time,'' said thomas delong, a 57-year-old white man who came to hear jackson thursday at mississippi state university
the majority of people in this country are not wealthy, they're not yuppies, they're poor. and they can't get up because the system won't let them,'' he said
jackson said he senses the difference between this campaign and his unsuccessful white house bid in 1984 because ``black and white interests are coming together'' and the racial factors have been overtaken by economic concerns
jackson cited this week's endorsements of his campaign by prominent white politicians _ texas agriculture commissioner jim hightower, oklahoma state sen. gene stipe, and tennessee democratic activist john j. hooker _ as evidence of an expanding base
historical movements in this country have always been kind of race-based. this is becoming a class-based movement for economic justice,'' he said in the interview
he accused southern democratic leaders _ many of whom have lined up behind the other southern native son, sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee _ of a ``sustained effort'' to try and keep democrats from his campaign
all these elected officials are trying to stop me,'' he said
but stipe said that ``regardless of what the power brokers say, they cannot stop that momentum'' that jackson is building
hooker said that in 1984, many whites who would not accept jackson are taking a new look after he garnered substantial white totals in the early primary and caucus states
regardless of how the convention turns out this summer, jackson said he will work with the party leaders and push for the party platform to include planks addressing his priorities on raising the minimum wage and other concerns of working people
he will also seek foreign policy planks on renewing trade with nicaragua and working with banks to relieve latin countries' debts so those nations can afford to buy more u.s. goods, he said
physicians must be more aware of self-destructive impulses in aids patients, who are much more likely to commit suicide than the general population and even victims of other terminal illnesses, a new study says
the study, published in today's journal of the american medical association, found that the risk of suicide among men 20 to 59 years old with aids was 36 times greater than for other men in that age group and 66 times greater than for the general population
other studies have shown that cancer victims are up to four times more likely than the general population to kill themselves
while suicide is statistically rare, the study found that the threat to aids victims comes first when they learn they have the disease, then again when it begins to affect the central nervous system
the acquired immunodeficiency syndrome has been associated with secondary depression and other psychiatric syndromes ... all of which are associated with higher suicide rates,'' the researchers wrote
the lesson is that physicians treating aids patients must be aware of the possibility of suicide, said one of the researchers, dr. peter m. marzuk of cornell university medical college
physicians should evaluate suicide risk in these patients carefully,'' he said. ``because of the risk for suicide, the presence of concomitant psychiatric syndromes, especially depression and delirium, should lead to early psychiatric intervention.''
an accompanying editorial emphasized the potential suicide risk for people who test positive for the aids virus, even though some of them might not have the disease
the presence of aids antibodies in a person's blood does not mean he has the disease, but only that the virus that causes aids has entered his system and provoked a natural disease-fighting response
the risk of suicide is one more reason that such tests should never be considered as `routine,''' dr. richard m. glass, an associate professor of psychiatry at the university of chicago hospital, wrote in the editorial. ``the enormity of this problem is indicated by estimates that approximately 1.5 million americans have hiv antibodies.''
there were reports last spring of seven suicides in the miami area among people who had tested positive
roger lane, hotline coordinator for miami's health crisis network, said in a telephone interview thursday that others tried unsuccessfully to take their own lives on the basis of very preliminary tests
the suicide outbreak coincided with the opening of new aids-testing centers, many of which offered no counseling and some of which merely gave test results over the telephone, he said
if you were notifying someone they had terminal cancer, you wouldn't do that over the phone,'' he said
doctors must specifically ask patients about any suicidal feelings, glass said
the study reported in jama focused on suicides in 1985 in new york city, where aids is the leading cause of death of men in their 30s. there were 3,828 people who had aids in the city then, of whom 12 were known to have killed themselves
these are conservative estimates (of the number of suicides),'' marzuk said. ``we don't know how many people may have taken an overdose of heroin, for example. these would never have been counted as suicides.''
aids destroys the body's defenses against disease, leaving a person prey to life-threatening infections and certain cancers
stock prices inched up in trading today on optimism about japan's economy, while the u.s. dollar dipped slightly as traders awaited market-affecting news
the dollar closed at 129.22, down 0.08 yen from thursday's close. the dollar opened at 129.16 yen, and ranged between 129.16 and 129.30 yen
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei stock average index of 225 selected issues finished the day at 25,615.62 points, up 19.31 points, or 0.07 percent, from thursday's close of 25,596.31 points
the market is strong,'' said yoshio ogawa of nikko securities. ``there aren't any real factors today, but the market is still looking good for the same reasons as late last month _ japan's economic fundamentals look good, and that is affecting trading.''
there were no important trends today, with the market holding fairly steady,'' said an analyst who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``but trading was very active.''
although volume was a heavy 1.3 billion shares in the first section, share prices closed mixed, with pharmaceuticals up and banks and other financials lower, according to dealers
the u.s. currency topped the 129-yen barrier in active trading thursday, but the market failed to gain momentum due to the lack of new incentives, said a currency dealer with a major commercial bank in tokyo
this was the kind of day that is very hard to comment on,'' said a foreign exchange analyst who requested anonymity. ``very little happened.'' ^by john king</byline>
the reagan administration has suspended new regulations that would have cut off federal funds to family planning clinics which offer abortions or abortion counseling, after a judge ruled the guidelines were unconstitutional
abortion referral and abortion counseling are constitutionally protected speech under the first amendment,'' said u.s. district judge walter j. skinner, issuing a permanent injunction thursday against enforcement of the regulations
denying an otherwise eligible organization a grant because it provides abortion counseling or referral, even with non-federal funds, constitutes an impermissable penalty for the exercise of a constitutionally protected right,'' he said
the regulations are specifically designed to suppress speech, and particularly directed at the suppression of one viewpoint,'' skinner said. ``as a result, they run directly contrary to the dictates of the first amendment.''
he said the regulations also were contrary to the intent of congress when it established the family planning program under title x of the public health service act of 1970
the regulations, scheduled to take effect thursday, will not be enforced while the administration reviews the ruling and decides whether to appeal, said lucy eddinger, a spokeswoman for the department of health and human services
skinner ruled the guidelines would cause irreparable harm to women who receive services from the clinics and violate a woman's right to privacy and to choose to have an abortion
federal judges in denver and new york city had issued temporary injunctions against the new rules, but had not ruled on their constitutionality and it was not clear whether those rulings had full nationwide force
this court has national jurisdiction in federal question cases,'' skinner saidin his 28-page ruling
the regulations had not been expected to affect the estimated 4,000 family planning clinics operated with federal funds because the rules apply only to new grants. about 5 million poor women receive services through the clinics
the injunction was requested last month by the state of massachusetts, the national family planning and reproductive health association and 13 other local and national family planning groups
although the injunction applied only to those clinics represented by the groups, skinner said he expected secretary of health and human services otis r. bowen to scrap the regulations
scott r. sterling, executive director of the washington, d.c.,-based family planning association, said he expected the administration to appeal ``because of political pressure
we expect to be successful at the appeals level as well,'' sterling said
massachusetts attorney general james shannon called the ruling ``a major victory for a woman's right to consult privately with her doctor.''
the new rules would have prohibited federally funded family planning programs from providing abortion counseling, referring women to abortion providers and engaging in lobbying or legal action to increase availability of abortions
if the facility also performs abortions, to keep title x funding for its other programs the clinic would have to maintain completely separate facilities for each type of patient
in its attempt to implement a health care policy which promotes childbirth, the defendant has devised a system which rests in large part of keeping title x clients in ignorance,'' skinner said
the title x budget for fiscal 1988 is $137 million, down from $142 million in fiscal 1987
a factory director whose labor-efficiency plans won him a $2,700 prize has decided to give up the money because of the lingering stigma against wealth and a deluge of request for handouts, a newspaper said today
the prize, 10,000 yuan, is a huge sum for most chinese, equal to 10 years' wages for the average urban worker and double that for a typical peasant
zhang xingrang, director of the no. 1 plastic factory in the eastern city of shijiazhuang, decided not to keep the money after being besieged with petitions for loans, the state-run workers' daily said
the paper said he was receiving dozens of letters each day from strangers wanting to share in his new wealth, with friends and co-workers adding to the chorus
zhang won the prize for developing what he called a ``full-load work plan'' for allocating labor more efficiently at his factory. he became a nationally famous labor hero, winning praise from communist party leader zhao ziyang
the workers' daily said colleagues told zhang, ``old zhang, now that you're rich don't forget we helped you. you can eat meat now, a little soup or some bones is enough for us.''
one letter-writer pleaded for 375 yuan to buy a three-wheeled pedicab so he could take his children _ including 9-year-old triplets _ to school
take pity on these children,'' he pleaded, addressing zhang as ``the god of wealth.''
another writer said he needed 2,000 yuan to get out of ``financial straits,'' adding, ``this amount is nothing to you.''
the paper said zhang feared criticism that has been heaped on other factory directors who have become rich in recent years because of incentives and profit-sharing programs designed to spur production
he put the money in a bank and is busy trying to devise a give-away plan that will satisfy most people, the paper said
zhao declared last october that china is in the ``primary stage of socialism'' and that it is permissible in this stage for some individuals to become rich while others lag behind
egalitarianism was the rule for most of china's first four decades under communism. in recent years, the chinese government has relaxed many of its economic policies, allowing for free enterprise. but many of the new rich have been criticized and even hit with criminal charges for acquiring large amounts of money
ms. magazine will be opening a news bureau in washington and veteran political reporter peggy simpson has been appointed bureau chief
ms. intends to become a force in washington,'' said editor-in-chief anne summers. ``we aim to become an authoritative voice in national political affairs on behalf of women. we will be non-partisan, but will express our views forthrightly.''
simpson ``combines the special qualities we were looking for _ solid experience of political and economic reporting, with a special sensitivity to how these impact on women,'' said summers
simpson, has covered national politics since the early 1970s, first for the associated press and since 1982 for hearst newspapers. she has covered every national political convention since 1972
ms., one of the first magazines focusing on political issues involving women, was acquired late last year by fairfax publications ltd., a major australian publisher
the state department has violated ``the spirit and letter'' of a new law by denying a visa to the head of the legal political wing of the irish republican army, says a new york-based group advocating the end of british rule in northern ireland
gerry adams, president of the ira's sinn fein, was denied a visa because of his alleged involvement in terrorist activities in northern ireland, donna sherman, a state department spokeswoman, said thursday
he was ineligible under (the section) of the immigration and nationality act which excludes from admission to the u.s. people who are personally involved with terrorist activities,'' sherman said
but martin galvin, spokesman for the irish northern aid committee in new york, said in a statement, ``irish-americans are outraged by the refusal of the state department to comply with the spirit and letter of the new visa provisions.''
he was referring to an amendment to an appropriations bill, passed last year, which in effect overturned that portion of immigration law allowing the u.s. government to deny visas to aliens who participate in political activities in their native countries which would be legal for u.s. citizens in the united states
the ira is fighting to end british rule in northern ireland and is outlawed on both sides of the border, although sinn fein is legal
usair says it has agreed to buy 50 boeing 737 jetliners with options for 30 additional aircraft, a deal worth $2.4 billion if all the options are exercised
delivery of the new jets will begin in april 1989 and continue through december 1991, the airline said
the twin-engine, short-to-medium range aircraft is the most popular jet ever sold by the seattle-based boeing co. the deal with usair brings to 2,001 boeing 737s on order
edwin colodny, usair chairman and president, said the order ``is indicative of the health and vitality'' of the airline, which has its headquarters at washington national airport
our track record makes it possible to order these new aircraft which will benefit our passengers and the communities we serve,'' colodny said in a statement
usair group, the holding company for usair as well as piedmont aviation and pacific southwest airlines, recently reported a 1987 net income of $194.6 million on revenue of $3 billion
korean officials shudder and editorial writers sputter when rep. richard gephardt says a mid-sized american car costs $48,000 in south korea because of tariffs _ but they admit the presidential hopeful is three-quarters right
an american car that would cost $10,000 in the united states costs about $36,000 in south korea after taxes, tariffs and duties, according to korean and u.s. officials
the charges limit foreign car sales in south korea to a few hundred each year. last year, south korea exported 442,557 vehicles to the united states that averaged $7,000 in price
gephardt has used the $48,000 figure on the campaign trail to underscore his argument that many nations close their markets to u.s. goods while taking advantage of washington's free trade policy to flood american markets
the argument has appealed to some americans and the missouri congressman has emerged as a frontrunner in the race for the presidential nomination of the democratic party
gephardt's platform has caused resentment in south korea at a time when the country is under american pressure to open its markets to imports. south korea's trade surplus with the united states, its main trading partner, reached $9.5 billion last year
gephardt is a name on many lips here. but the government isn't too worried since there's still a long way to go in the elections,'' said a u.s. trade official in seoul who asked not to be identified
korean newspapers and television have provided regular reports on gephardt since he started singling out south korea. gephardt has been attacked by newspapers as an unreasonable politician trying to blame others for america's failure to keep its economy healthy
the charges gave the impression that malicious korean trade practices are responsible for the sad state of the u.s. economy. it's really shocking to us,'' said the kyunghyang shinmun in a feb. 13 editorial
but the government has not challenged gephardt because trade restrictions do exist, officials said
it is true to a certain extent that there exists some discrimination against imported cars,'' said one offical, who spoke on condition of anonymity
korean officials say their country has many economic problems and is only just emerging as a modern nation. they say the economy is fragile and needs protection, including some import barriers
the gross national product is below $3,000 per person and the economy is weighed down by $35 billion in foreign debt
radical students have seized on american trade pressure in recent weeks in a bid to attract public support. farmers worried about cheap u.s. agricultural products have dumped cow manure at government buildings
most koreans agree that the economy must be protected, but the small, scattered protests have attracted little support
the korean attitude is to wait until it really becomes a problem,'' a u.s. diplomat said
the government has pledged to open its markets wider to american and other imports as quickly as possible, but u.s. pressure to move more quickly is rejected as bullying
they're promising changes, but if it's going to happen is anyone's guess,'' said one u.s. business representative based in seoul, who asked not to be named
the united states has been pressing south korea to drop import restrictions on a wide range of goods. recent talks have centered on allowing beef imports and lowering the price of american cigarettes
the disparity in the car industry is a good example of the problems and discrimination faced by american companies, u.s. diplomats said
our figures show about 10 foreign cars have been sold in south korea so far this year. we don't think any of them were american,'' said one, noting that the only levy imposed by the united states on imported korean cars is customs duty of about 4 percent
the massive rioting and arrests of opposition leaders that followed this week's re-election of president abdou diouf have shaken this west african nation's belief in itself as a democracy
two days of rioting in the capital that followed sunday's national balloting took the government by surprise. it denounced the hail of stones as stemming from the opposition's ``reckless manipulation of youngsters.''
opposition parties had claimed diouf's socialist party rigged the voting
a state of emergency and curfew were imposed, and soldiers and riot police flooded the capital's streets. officials were granted sweeping arrest powers and authority to curb the media
more than 80 buses were damaged, dozens of gas stations and stores looted or gutted by fire, the homes of some officials of the governing socialist party ransacked. police raided the university and opposition party headquarters and fought running battles with stone-throwing protesters
several top opposition leaders were arrested, including the main opposition presidential candidate abdoulaye wade of the senegalese democratic party
wade's fiery rhetoric and call for change clearly struck a responsive chord. opposition supporters say the socialists, after 28 years in power, had themselves become the state, losing touch with the country's 6.7 million people
a senior government official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the nation's leaders were shocked:
they did not understand the depth of the feeling. they don't want to face it and since the campaign began they have been shrinking away from the real issue. they talk about democracy but they won't relinquish power.''
no black african government has ever handed over power to an opposition party after an election defeat
there are 17 registered political parties in senegal, but just six participated in the elections. a free press regularly lampoons the government and even pokes fun at diouf without fear of reprisal. senegalese are proud of those freedoms
but the opposition parties act more like rip van winkle than real parties. every five years, they wake up to watch the political parade, then nod off again
many senegalese, including diouf supporters, said the 52-year-old president was not powerful enough to control his own party, which they say has too much at stake to allow the freedom people demand
diouf supporters joined those who expressed frustration with nepotism in government
serigne mor diop, an out-of-work carpenter, said he thought diouf was a good leader and an honest man whose party had gone unchallenged for too long
we need diouf's leadership but we don't need the ps and their corruption,'' he said. ``no party should be allowed such power.''
a senior western diplomat, whose government strongly supports diouf, said the president's commitment to democracy was not matched by the government bureaucracy
democracy has been an evolutionary process going on here since 1848,'' said the diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``these elections are one way of viewing how far it's come. in the long run, there will have to be further evolution.''
the senegalese are outraged when they think their rights have been abused
in riot-torn sections of dakar and in the industrial city of thies about 45 miles away, senegalese young and old angrily denounced what they saw as police brutality and violation of their rights this week
with tear gas-reddened eyes and tear-stained faces they angrily demanded, ``is this what diouf calls a democracy? we have a right to peaceful assembly, our government has no right to stop us.''
jacques nzouankeu of dakar's center for studies and research on pluralistic democracy in the third world sees such violence as a serious threat to the handful of democratic countries in africa and those moving towards democracy
it is a catastrophic thing, because those who don't want democracy are numerous'' he said. ``they are looking for a chance to say, `see, democracy doesn't work, we need a new system.'''
omar bongo, who heads the one-party central african state of gabon, called the senegalese troubles proof pluralism is not for africa
see what this leads to?'' bongo said. ``we are for democratization of our states, but not for the multiplication of anarchy.'' friday to today.</note>
republican presidential hopeful pat robertson said god had spoken to him, calling him to usher in the second coming of jesus christ, a newspaper reported today
in a tape of a december 1984 address to a religious seminar in dallas, robertson said christ's return is imminent and would be accompanied by christians ``taking dominion'' over the wealth and property of non-believers, the los angeles times reported
in a reference to dallas' downtown office buildings, robertson said: ``imagine the time the people of god have inherited that property, because the bible says that the wicked lay up and heap up treasures for the righteous.''
in the 1984 tape, robertson said god had told him ``i have called you to usher in the coming of my son.'' he also briefly speaks in tongues, a form of unrecognizable language uttered by those who practice charismatic christianity, during his closing prayer
robertson has said he received the prophecy in 1968 through harald bredesen, a close associate who laid his hand on robertson's head and spoke as if god were speaking through him
however, when questioned about the prophecy, both bredesen and robertson characterized it as applying to robertson's ministry, the christian broadcasting network. robertson resigned from cbn before undertaking his presidential campaign
bredesen said, ``we would all be appalled and pat would be appalled,'' at the prospects that robertson's remarks would be construed to mean that god's words applied to him personally
asked thursday to comment about the 1968 prophecy, robertson said bredesen ``may have been referring to middle east television,'' and predicted robertson's role in ``spreading the gospel thoughout the middle east'' via cbn's transmitter in lebanon
however, in an april 1982 letter to cbn contributors, robertson quoted the bredesen prophecy and said god has assigned a ministry to cbn ``to prepare the way for the second coming.''
robertson has rebuked reporters for referring to him as a former television evangelist. he insists on being evaluated on the basis of his record as a businessman, educator and founder of the multimillion-dollar christian broadcasting network
robertson contends that examinations of his religious beliefs in the context of his presidential campaign constitute bigotry. and he maintains that his fervent evangelical beliefs would not interfere with his execution of presidential power
police arrested two men in the slaying of a rookie patrolman who was shot in the head as he guarded a drug witness last week, a spokesman said today
the suspects were picked up thursday afternoon in the borough of queens and questioned for about six hours before their arrest around midnight, said officer peter o'donnell
two women picked up with the men were released, o'donnell said
the suspects' names, the charges and other details will not be released until a news conference today, o'donnell said
officer edward byrne, 22, was shot three times in the head at point-blank range early feb. 26 while sitting alone in a patrol car outside the queens house of a man who had complained to police about neighborhood crack dealers
the daily news and new york times, quoting unidentified sources, said one of the four picked up was 24-year-old todd scott of queens. the newspapers said scott works for howard ``pappy'' mason, an associate of reputed drug kingpin lorenzo ``fat cat'' nichols
nichols, 29, was sentenced feb. 25 to 25 years to life in prison on drug and gun charges, and is awaiting trial on charges he had his parole officer killed for revenge. mason is awaiting trial on charges he helped carry out the killing
police have speculated that nichols may have ordered byrne's killing as retribution for his long sentence
since the slaying, police have rounded up 294 suspected drug dealers in their investigation
shooting at cops, it's just bad for business. i think experienced criminals know that; perhaps these inexperienced ones will learn it,'' police commissioner benjamin ward said thursday
the community has been very helpful,'' ward said
the reward for information leading to a conviction grew to $130,000 thursday with a $25,000 contribution from members of the new york stock exchange
wnbc-tv reported wednesday night that investigators had identified two men, including the gunman, and two women believed to have been in the car that quietly coasted up to byrne's police car before he was shot
wnbc-tv said police believe the women accompanied the men so it would look like they were out on a date if stopped. police declined to comment on the report
