rose cipollone was so hooked on cigarettes that she smoked a pack while in labor with her first child, even though she had tried to quit, an addiction expert testified in support of her family's liability suit
dr. jerome jaffe cited several instances on the stand thursday to show that mrs. cipollone was so dependent on cigarettes that smoking governed her behavior until her death of lung cancer at age 40
he depicted a smoker who picked butts from the garbage, ordered groceries just to have cigarettes delivered and puffed away even after part of her lung had been removed
mrs. cipollone became a vivid presence for the first time during the five-week federal court trial. after her death in 1984, her widower, antonio of lakehurst, carried on the suit against three tobacco companies
the defendants _ philip morris co., lorillard inc. and liggett group inc. _ deny they are responsible for her death. one of their arguments is that mrs. cipollone smoked of her own free will
jaffe, a clinical psychiatrist and director of the national institute of drug abuse's research center in baltimore, described what he learned about mrs. cipollone's smoking habits during a 75-minute interview at her lawyer's office months before she died
she was dependent, and i thought heavily dependent, on tobacco and cigarettes,'' jaffe said
under cross-examination by liggett lawyer james v. kearney, jaffe acknowledged that he did not examine mrs. cipollone physically and never saw her smoke
until now, testimony in the case has centered on allegations that the companies failed to do enough research on the health effects of smoking, tell the public what they did know or put a safer product on the market
as the focus shifted to mrs. cipollone, jaffe related that when she was in labor with her first child in 1947, she was asked by doctors what she wanted. her answer was a glass of water and _ despite having nearly quit during her pregnancy _ a cigarette. the doctors brought her a pack
she said, `i smoked a whole pack before the baby was born,''' according to jaffe, who referred to his notes of the interview while being questioned by marc z. edell, an attorney for her estate
in 1964, when the surgeon general's report linking smoking and disease came out, mrs. cipollone consciously tried to ignore it
it's typical,'' jaffe said. ``it's the heart of most dependences. ... denial is the cardinal symbol.''
in 1981, when a spot was found on her lung, mrs. cipollone threw away her cigarettes. but jaffe recalled her saying ``i was smoking when i went into the hospital'' for a lung operation
she continued to smoke after the operation, he said, stopping the following year when her right lung was removed
jaffe also served as a special consultant to the president for narcotics and dangerous drugs from 1971 to 1973
the cuban government forced some lepers to join the 1980 exodus for the united states from the port of mariel, cuban exile leaders claim
the charges came during a campaign by cuban exile groups seeking to have their homeland's communist government declared in violation of human rights
the exile leaders say expelling the lepers against their will violates their rights, and they hope to bring up the matter before the commission on human rights meeting now in geneva
castro did not show any respect for the human rights of lepers or for the american people,'' said jorge mas canosa, head of the cuban american national foundation
about 30 of the patients being treated in miami for leprosy, or hansen's disease, arrived during the 1980 boatlift, which brought about 125,000 refugees to the united states
a leper now living in louisiana said he was forced onto a florida-bound vessel on may 3, 1980
they said `you go or we will put you in prison,''' jose antonio perez ortiz, 41, said in an interview taped last week. ``i could not work. i said `send me there.'''
angel pino, spokesman for the cuban intrests section in washington, denied the charge, saying all who left cuba did so voluntarily
paramedic michael flaherty jumped into his emergency vehicle and recognized the address: one of his parents was in trouble
if you walk in and see your mother on the floor, you react,'' flaherty said. ``i gave her mount-to-mouth ventilation. everything worked.''
his parents were having breakfast wednesday when his mother, theresa, 65, collapsed about 8:45 a.m
when i heard the address, i could have run there faster than the ambulance, if that had been necessary,'' flaherty said. ``nobody was going to beat us to that address.''
flaherty's father, peter, who is not trained in cardiopulmonary resuscitation, applied chest compressions before the younger flaherty and his partner, jake willens, arrived
mrs. flaherty was rushed to st. francis hospital in evanston where she was in fair condition, apparently suffering from inadequate blood supply to her heart
chief fire department paramedic ronald smith praised flaherty's actions. ``he saved his mother's life. he brought her back,'' smith said
i didn't know if it was a heart attack or respiratory arrest,'' flaherty said. ``no paramedic or firefighter wants to resuscitate or work on his own parents or children or friends
but when something happens and you have to do it, you react,'' he said
indian troops prevented tamil students from holding demonstrations they called for today, warning people that they would be shot if they gathered, reports from the region said
sri lankan military officials said four tamil rebels were killed thursday in a shootout with indian troops in a village near the northern town of jaffna
the officials, who cannot be identified under briefing rules, said the rebels were killed after they attacked an indian patrol. they said one indian soldier was badly wounded
india has about 45,000 soldiers in sri lanka to enforce an indian-sponsored peace accord signed last july to end the tamil rebels' four-year separatist insurrection
the liberation tigers of tamil eelam, the largest of the rebel groups, has rejected the accord. the tigers have been the focus of indian search operations in and around batticaloa, a town 140 miles northeast of colombo
protest marches were called for in batticaloa by the eelam revolutionary organization of students, which has endorsed the peace accord but alleges sri lankan soldiers are violating it through shootings and arrests. under the accord, the sri lankan army is to be confined to barracks
in telephone interviews, batticaloa residents said that indian troops drove through the town warning civilians they would be shot if they violated orders prohibiting public gatherings
the residents, speaking on condition of anonymity, said no incidents were reported
tamils, who are mostly hindus, make up 18 percent of sri lanka's 16 million population. they claim they are discriminated against by the island's majority sinhalese buddhists, who control the government and military
the peace accord signed july 29 calls on the tamils to lay down their arms in exchange for more political autonomy in the northern and eastern regions where they live
india has become involved because it has about 60 million ethnic tamils in its southern states who are sympathetic to their sri lankan brethern. nimitz</head>
england's duchess of york watched apprehensively as her husband, prince andrew, rocketed off the bow of the world's largest nuclear-powered aircraft carrier for a thrilling jet ride
it was incredible. a sensational end to a great visit to the nimitz,'' andrew said thursday following his catapult in an s-3a viking anti-submarine warfare jet
the flight and an air show were highlights of a day at sea for the duke of york and his pregnant wife, sarah, both pilots, who also inspected one of the vessel's catapults and massive chains that hold the ship's two 60,000-pound anchors
the couple, on a 10-day tour of southern california to promote british culture and trade, began the day visiting park century school for learning-disabled children accompanied by british actress joan collins
today's schedule for the royal couple includes visits to the offices of armand hammer, chairman of occidental petroleum corp., and the university of california, los angeles
as the prince proceeded to the jet plane for the afternoon flight, he said, ``this is one of the loneliest walks i've ever done.''
the engines screamed, and sarah, wearing a flight helmet of her own, clutched a gift teddy bear as she watched the jet soar off the ship. it turned back for a low fly-by and the pair waved to each other before the duchess boarded a helicopter for her own flight to long beach, where the royal yacht britannia is docked
the duke and duchess returned to the britannia to host a thursday evening dinner
earlier, the duchess was presented a boatswain's mate's whistle, used to pipe dignitaries aboard, and she playfully tooted on it as she and the duke rode up to the flight deck on a huge aircraft elevator
sarah also chatted with sailors on the mess deck, asking airman michael mcamis, 25, of akron, ohio, if his sleeping quarters were roomy enough
it's all relative,'' mcamis replied, drawing a smile from the duchess
sarah then headed to the ship's port side, which drew laughter from mcamis, who said, ``we only cleaned the starboard side today.''
the nimitz, powered by two nuclear reactors that drive four propellers, had sailed from san diego heading north to its home port at bremerton, wash., with 3,000 men, half its full flight compliment, and only a few aircraft aboard
the couple were presented leather flight jackets bearing the inscriptions ``duke of york'' and ``duchess of york,'' then sat down to watch an air show from the main deck
jet after jet touched down on the deck at 160 mph, catching one of four cable arresters on the carrier's stern and stretching them 150 yards before coming to a halt
the policy-making body of the assemblies of god will resolve an unprecedented rift between national and state church leaders over the punishment of fallen tv evangelist jimmy swaggart, a spokeswoman says
this will be a final decision with no right of appeals,'' said juleen turnage, assemblies secretary of information. ``our executives feel that this is a situation that needs to be ... expedited quickly.''
g. raymond carlson, the general superintendent of the pentecostal denomination based here, said in a statement thursday that the general presybtery would meet march 28 to make a decision
meanwhile, in new orleans, three state appeals court judges heard arguments on whether they should revive a $90 million lawsuit filed against swaggart by a preacher he accused of adultery
a lawyer for preacher marvin gorman said evidence gathered by private detectives who investigated swaggart will be made public in court if the lawsuit is reinstated. if the judges refuse to revive the suit, attorney thomas frasier said, the evidence will be made public in some other manner
the judges gave no indication when they would rule
swaggart, a baton rouge, la., evangelist with a $150 million empire and a worldwide television following, confessed to undisclosed sins after reports linked him to prostitutes
swaggart has admitted sinning against his wife, but has not gone into detail. what others are saying he has done, depending on the specifics, might best be described as voyeurism, sexual perversion or pornographic acts
an investigation to determine if swaggart can keep his ministerial credentials has grown into a circle of meetings with the louisiana district council and the executive presbytery debating his punishment
the louisiana officials recommended swaggart be suspended from the pulpit for three months, but national leaders have said such a short suspension for a minister who has confessed to moral misconduct would be unprecedented
national officials asked the state leaders to reconsider their recommendation, but in another unprecedented move, the state refused
mrs. turnage said the executives had hoped to have the march 28 meeting earlier, but previous commitments by some of the 250 general presybters prevented it. the general presbytery meets annually, usually in august
the general presbytery consists of the 13 executive presbyters, representatives of the assemblies' districts, foreign missions and colleges and honorary members. it is described as the policy-making body for the church and serves as the court of appeals on ministerial credentials
only once within the last 25 years has it convened in special session to deal with a church matter. the matter then was the founding of evangel college in springfield, mrs. turnage said
the majority vote prevails,'' she said. ``the only item on the agenda is jimmy swaggart. they will have open discussion and a vote will be taken.''
she said the presbyters can request that swaggart attend the meeting, ``but at this time, that point has not been discussed.''
mrs. turnage said figures will not be available for another three weeks to determine whether the swaggart situation has had any effect on contributions to the nation's largest pentecostal denomination
last year following the ptl scandal, contributions rose 6 percent, and the assemblies gained more church members and churches, she said
new york city's new schools chancellor says he will begin shaping up one of the nation's most troubled school systems by abolishing time clocks and paring down the bloated central bureaucracy
richard r. green's inaugural message, delivered amid unprecedented pomp and splendor thursday in the ornate chapel of erasmus hall high school, was that new york city's schools are ``on trial. business as usual must come to an end, and it must do so today.''
green left behind a 30-year career in minneapolis schools to lead the 939,000-pupil system, the largest in the nation with a $4.8 billion annual budget
green was ushered into the oak-paneled chapel by six children wearing sashes reading ``the class of 2000.'' greeting him on the speaker's podium were gov. mario m. cuomo, mayor edward i. koch, board of education president robert f. wagner, jr., and other dignitaries, all wearing academic robes
frequently departing from a prepared text of a 20-minute inaugural address, green took a generally conciliatory tone toward the many problems and constituencies he faces. but he vowed that the infamous central bureaucracy would likely face cuts, especially with mayor koch pressuring the board to find $28 million in budget savings
i have heard that 110 livingston street has been immobilized by the twin abuses called apathy and cynicism,'' he said. ``this is a new day.''
by july 1, i will have a management team in place that i can rely on. and there will be some transfers out of 110 livingston,'' he said, referring to the brooklyn headquarters of the city board of education
he also vowed to remove the time clocks that teachers are required to punch. and he said that ``we are going to find a way to open schools to parents who want to use facilities and i am certain we can reach a new accommodation with our custodians.''
green did not mention his controversial suggestion of an 11-month school year which he made off-the-cuff on wednesday while touring several schools
united federation of teachers president sandra feldman called the 20-minute speech ``an exciting beginning. he was both tough and caring. i was especially gratified that he singled out the work done by the city's teachers and the fact that they don't get enough recognition as professionals.''
the city's first black chancellor has his work cut out for him. the system, which has 32 autonomous districts, has a dropout rate pegged by the school board at 30.7 percent. an independent panel put the figure at 50.4 percent
many of the city's 1,050 school buildings are deteriorating, and an estimated 25 percent have serious problems
green's staff of 61,000 teachers exceeds the number of students in the minneapolis system, yet officials expect the city will need 40,000 new teachers by 1994
the newest house rejection of aid for the nicaraguan contras has put the rebels on the defensive as they near face-to-face peace talks with the sandinista government, a contra spokeswoman says
the house rejected a $30 million humanitarian aid package thursday night, only hours after contra leaders agreed to meet the sandinistas inside nicaragua without a mediator
every time the united states turns its back on the contras, it puts us in a less favorable position,'' said contra spokeswoman marta sacasa. the sandinistas ``will become even more intransigent and more hard line.''
the failed bill had limited the use of the funds to food, clothing and medical supplies and a plan to help young war victims. the 216-210 vote against the package meant the rebels, whose last u.s. aid ran out tuesday, would be left without new supplies unless congress passes another measure
we of course wanted a positive vote, but the death or survival of the nicaraguan resistance is not tied to the u.s. congress,'' ms. sacasa said. ``we have adapted and we will continue to adapt.''
she said this setback, coupled with a feb. 3 house rejection of a $36.2 million aid package proposed by president reagan, makes it clear the contras cannot count on the united states
we are fighting against an enemy that doesn't have these kinds of problems. the aid from the soviet union has not stopped flowing to the sandinistas,'' she said
while a date for the peace conference has not been set, the contras on thursday accepted in principle an offer of face-to-face talks made by nicaraguan president daniel ortega
but the contras insisted in a communique that cardinal miguel obando y bravo of managua, who was dismissed by ortega as a mediator after two previous negotiating sessions, be present as a ``witness and guarantor.''
ortega has proposed that the talks take place in southern nicaragua with his brother, defense minister humberto ortega, heading the government delegation
the contras appointed adolfo calero, considered to be one of the more hardline directors, to head their delegation
we are accepting a face-to-face meeting in nicaraguan territory,'' director alfredo cesar said after a daylong meeting of the directorate
ortega had suggested that the meeting be held in the town of sapoa near nicaragua's costa rican border on march 10-12, but cesar said the time and place should be worked out later
the communique signed by the five directors of the nicaraguan resistance, as the contra rebels are formally called, lambasted ortega for dismissing obando y bravo as a mediator
it called the action ``unilateral and dictatorial,'' and praised the cardinal for his help in pushing the peace talks
when kate reed ambled into her bathroom early one morning and flipped on the light, she found she didn't need a cold shower to wake up _ there sat a 6{-foot long boa constrictor on her toilet seat
she went back to her husband, rob, and calmly said, ``honey, please wake up. there's a snake in the bathroom
he sat bolt upright in bed and said, `what?'''
meanwhile, their dog, tootsie, slept calmly on the bathmat
the snake escaped jan. 28 from upstairs neighbor brian wycoskie, who, after a call from rob reed, came downstairs to retrieve his wayward pet, named cleopatra
wycoskie said he hadn't told the reeds about the escape because he thought someone had stolen it
cleopatra apparently slithered down wycoskie's toilet on thursday and picked the wrong pipe to return home
i found out they're a water animal,'' said wycoskie, who also owns connie the florida cottonmouth rattlesnake, hercules the tarantula, sting the scorpion, vince the black widow spider and tropical gecko lizards named abbott and costello
caught in rush-hour traffic with his wife in labor, ray snyder stopped at a convenience store to call for help _ but left with a baby boy born in the back of his pickup truck
it happened in five minutes, but it seemed like a lifetime,'' said debbie spivey, a schoolteacher who stopped at the store to buy a soda but wound up helping to deliver the 8-pound, 9{-ounce baby thursday
mrs. snyder and son were doing fine at holmes regional medical center in nearby melbourne in east central florida
she said she hopes her next child is born in a hospital. ``you don't ever want to have a baby in a pickup truck,'' she said
a 12-year-old girl who earned $500 by going without television for a year says she doubts she'll revert to heavy tv watching, even though she's now free to do so
i think i'm going to continue on doing my homework first,'' jenny machalleck said thursday after watching her first television program since march 2, 1987
i'm really happy with how my grades have come out,'' she said. ``they weren't bad before, but now they're at the head of the class.''
earlier in the day, she received the $500 check her parents had promised if she could go a full year without tv. they made the deal to cure her of her six-hour-a-day addiction to the tube
but jenny said she was too busy doing homework thursday night to celebrate by watching the show she had wanted to, ``cosby.''
she said she finished in time to watch the last half of ``cheers.''
her first tv viewing in year was fun, she said, ``because i hadn't watched in so long. but i found i hadn't really been missing anything. i was just not as enthusiastic as i thought i would be.''
communist gunmen killed a soldier and a policeman in a suburb of the capital today in the second deadly attack by urban guerrillas in two days, police said
elsewhere, the military said about 200 communist new people's army rebels raided a northern mountain village, set fire to a police detachment and kidnapped a policeman
president corazon aquino vowed today to crack down on crime and pursue an ``unrelenting campaign'' against communists
she told a conference of 1,700 newly elected mayors and governors that their main task will be to restore order
the first and most important is law and order throughout the land,'' the president said. ``this calls for curbing criminality and the destruction of rightist and leftist elements in our society that are bent on the overthrow of our government and our democracy.''
she also called for breaking up illegal gambling syndicates and ``flushing out and shutting down the vice dens.''
in suburban pasig today, four gunmen opened fire on tech. sgt. norberto fungo as he was walking near the public market, police said. as they were escaping, the rebels opened fire on patrolman severino francisco as he tried to draw his pistol, police added
the gunmen commandeered a passenger jeep and escaped
the killings occurred one day after two men and two women gunned down margarita tenorio, 62, a ward leader and president of the anti-communist vigilante crusaders for peace and democracy
police said the assailants scattered leaflets claiming responsibility in the name of the ``jun somono squad'' of the alex boncayao brigade, a rebel urban guerrilla group that killed scores of police and soldiers in the capital last year
somono, an urban guerrilla, was slain last year by police
the attack on the police detachment occurred thursday in sadanga, about 180 miles north of manila
a constabulary report said police manning the outpost put up a brief fight but surrendered after two defenders were wounded. the report said the rebels confiscated police firearms, burned down the outpost and took a patrolman hostage before fleeing to the forest
mrs. aquino was swept to power in a february 1986 military-civilian revolt that ousted president ferdinand marcos after 20 years in power
the military chief of staff said today he did not believe the time was right to allow marcos to return from exile in hawaii
if you would ask me personally, it is not advisable for him to be back at this time,'' gen. renato de villa told reporters
the general's remarks follow reports that two of mrs. aquino's relatives met with marcos in hawaii to discuss terms for his possible return
de villa said former military officers implicated in coup attempts remain at large in the country and marcos' return might jeopardize security. but he expressed doubts that the marcos groups could muster enough support to topple the government. closed</head>
a university of pennsylvania fraternity that sponsored a strip show in which white students jeered black dancers has been ordered to close for 1{ years, and a black student activist received a death threat he believes stemmed from a protest of the incident
blacks and feminists at penn have complained bitterly during the past few weeks about the rush party at the all-white fraternity. during the party last september, two black women stripped, performed sexually explicit acts and danced naked before an audience that shouted racial epithets, according to the university
the school on thursday ordered the 112-member zeta beta tau to close for at least 1{ years because of the incident, the fraternity said
zbt president zane brown, in a statement, apologized for the incident but said the decision by the penn judicial board was ``unjust.''
the death threat was made earlier this week against conrad tillard, director of the organization of black consciousness, in a letter sent to a reporter at penn's student newspaper, the daily pennsylvanian
the writer claimed to be a student member of the jewish defense league, but school officials did not believe the claim, and the jdl denied any connection with the threat. the fraternity that was ordered closed is primarily jewish
the main thing it said was that i was a target on their hit list,'' tillard said. ``it also said that in general they're trying to stop the rise of this black power group that i'm helping bring about.''
tillard will receive around-the-clock protection by campus police that will continue ``as long as is necessary,'' said security spokeswoman sylvia canada. philadelphia police said they were investigating the letter; the fbi also acknowledged receiving a copy but declined to comment
tillard said he believed the letter stemmed from a rally monday sponsored by his group, which called on the school to oust zbt. however, the letter did not mention the fraternity incident, tillard said
black officials said the fraternity incident and the death threat reflect growing racial tension not only at the ivy league campus but at colleges around the country
what is happening now, in terms of the real tensions on campus, is just the tip of the iceberg,'' said jacqueline wade, director of penn's afro-american students department. ``i think we're going to see across the nation something that's very reminiscent of the '60s.''
racism never left the university environment,'' she said
meanwhile, at dartmouth college in hanover, n.h., about 300 people rallied thursday to protest bigotry. the day before, police guarded the offices of a conservative weekly campus newspaper that revived stinging attacks on a black professor and reawakened charges of racism at the school
rabbi howard alperg, director of penn's jewish campus activities board, said ``black radicals'' are trying to turn the fraternity controversy into a black-jewish issue
but daniel gamulka, chairman of the jewish student council, said the fraternity incident enraged both white and black students
the jewish community does not support what happened at zbt,'' said gamulka. ``they find it offensive, just as anyone would.''
relationships between black and jewish penn students have been strained since a verbal confrontation between the groups in 1986, when the black student unity conference planned to feature a keynote address by louis farrakhan, nation of islam leader. farrakhan's critics say he is anti-semitic
a driver who secured his teddy bear with a seatbelt but failed to do the same for himself died after being thrown from the car in a crash, authorities said
the 31-year-old victim, whose name was being withheld until his family could be notified, died late wednesday on the long beach freeway, said california highway patrol officer richard perez
for unknown reasons, he drifted to the right and struck a guardrail,'' perez said. ``he went airborne about 35 feet and down into a chain-link fence.''
paramedics pronounced the man dead at the scene, said chp dispatcher ruth frias
the teddy bear remained in the vehicle, perez said
the investigating officer was telling me that (the driver) was alone in the car, but he had a little teddy bear with him,'' perez said. ``he had the teddy bear seated in the passenger seat with a belt on.''
increases in federal seizures of imported cocaine and marijuana raise the demand for greater amounts of drug imports and likely fatten the coffers of latin american drug producers, a study concludes
the study, released thursday by the rand corp., found that more and more narcotics shipments are being stopped at the borders, but an even greater number are getting through to meet demands of american drug users who are ``relatively insensitive'' to higher prices that may result
while interdiction raises smugglers' risks, they adapt in the short run and learn in the long run. very large increases in expenditure might lead to more seizures and arrests, but not to large decreases in consumption,'' said the study by the research institute
between 1981 and 1986, the government tripled its spending in the war against imported drugs, from $237 milion to $801 million, the study said. the military portion of that rose from $1 million to $196 million
despite the increase, the amount of cocaine reaching u.s. users rose from between 38 and 68 metric tons in 1981 to between 111 and 153 tons in 1985, the latest year for which figures were available
the amount of marijuana entering the united states during the same period rose from between 8,700 and 12,700 metric tons to between 9,447 and 12,228 metric tons
seizures of cocaine rose from less than 2 metric tons to more than 25 metric tons, while seizures of marijuana were halved from 4,000 metric tons to 2,000 metric tons
the figures were based on official estimates of the u.s. drug enforcement adminstration, the study said
in addition, latin american drug manufacturers may be getting even richer because they make money whether the drugs are successfully smuggled or not, said the study
meanwhile, it added, a stepped-up seizure of cocaine from colombia has caused a shift to mexican and domestic sources
the study, which looked only at cocaine and marijuana, comes as congress considers a proposal that would make the defense department a primary agency in the interception of drugs at substantially increased costs to taxpayers
the defense department now serves a secondary role, mostly by providing radar surveillance and limited air and sea pursuit, to the three agencies that have primary responsibility in stopping the drug flow: the coast guard, the customs service and the immigration and naturalization service
meanwhile, on thursday the u.s. coast guard said it has ended its routine drug-smuggling patrols by land and sea off the west coast because of budget constraints
the decision to stop routine sea patrols and surveillance flights will result in more smugglers successfully delivering their cargo, rear adm. a. bruce beran said
beran, commander of the coast guard district that includes california, oregon, nevada and arizona, said he ended the patrols six weeks ago in an effort to trim some $1 million from his district's budget
he cited as an additional budgetary pressure some $100 million in cuts to coast guard funding contained in a proposal for the 1989 federal budget
a tugboat leased by a company in this small fishing village in northern baja california was repossessed, reportedly at gunpoint, by its u.s.-based owners early today, the u.s. coast guard said
coast guard officials in san diego received a distress call in broken english early today on an emergency radio channel reporting that armed men were hijacking the vessel, said jeff d'annolso of the san diego office
the report said six armed americans went aboard the tugboat northern warrior,'' said petty officer reid crispino of the coast guard station in long beach
the report was called in by the chartering panama co., which runs a fleet of tugboats that escort tankers in and out of rosarito beach, about 30 miles south of the u.s.-mexico border, crispino said
the tugboat was leased to the mexican company by seattle, wash.-based stabbert &amp; associates, he said
we contacted the owners in washington and they confirmed they were repossessing the tugboat due to a lack of payments by the lessee,'' crispino said
investigators had not determined how many men boarded the boat, which was in port at the time, or confirmed whether they were armed
crispino said the coast guard had no control over the matter because it took place in mexican waters
if (chartering panama co.) wants to pursue the matter, they'll have to go to a civil admiralty attorney. it's now a legal matter,'' he said
a chicago obstetrician has been indicted on federal charges that he lied on the witness stand about his role in tests concerning the safety of the dalkon shield birth control device
dr. louis g. keith, 53, an obstetrician-gynecologist at northwestern university medical school at chicago, testified falsely about transfer of bacteria by the tail string of the intrauterine shield, the justice department said thursday in announcing the indictment
keith faces eight counts of perjury and one count of obstruction of justice. if convicted on all counts, he faces 45 years in prison and $85,000 in fines. an fbi spokesman said keith was expected to surrender in chicago today and be arraigned march 17 in tampa
dr. keith is innocent and will be vindicated,'' said his lawyer, matthew kennelly. ``that is all i will say.''
on march 15, 1983, keith told jurors in a tampa lawsuit against a.h. robins co., the manufactuer of the iud, he had performed experiments that verified the safety of the birth control device. in fact, he did not design, direct, conduct or do the scientific experiments ``about which he testified,'' the indictment announced in washington said
the alleged perjury came during the suit brought by linda harre of tampa, who alleged that the shield caused her to become sterile. she lost the $12.5 million suit
mrs. harre won a new trial in march 1985 when the 11th u.s. circuit court of appeals in atlanta issued a scathing opinion attacking the veracity of keith's testimony
five months later, a.h. robins filed for protection from its creditors in federal bankruptcy court in richmond, va., a measure which barred future action on pending lawsuits, including mrs. harre's
john d. taylor, a spokesman for a.h. robins in richmond, va., said thursday evening that keith had testified for the company in several lawsuits, and the firm has no reason to believe he ever lied
the company halted production and sale of the dalkon shield in the united states and abroad in 1974, although distribution continued in some foreign countries until early 1985, said taylor
some 200,000 claims have been filed against a.h. robins by women who contend they suffered pelvic infections, sterility or spontaneous abortions because of the dalkon shield. a.h. robins sold 2.8 million of the devices between 1971 and 1974 and has paid more than $300 million in legal damages involving its shield
robins spokesman roscoe puckett said the firm is awaiting court approval of a reorganization plan that would set aside $2.375 billion to settle claims relating to the dalkon shield. increasing majority in parliament; corrects that parliament has 330 sted of 300 seats; adds details on 1986 results and number of eligible voters. no pickup.</note>
president hussain muhammad ershad's jatiya party increased its majority in parliament today after national elections marked by violence, fraud and an opposition boycott
at least 11 people were reported killed and more than 300 were injured during voting thursday for 299 contested seats in the 330-seat parliament. turnout appeared very low and even jatiya party members acknowledged ballot boxes were stuffed
with results in for 194 races, jatiya candidates had won 176 seats. in 18 of those contests, they ran unopposed. one race was postponed because one of the candidates for the open seat was killed
a coalition of 73 minor opposition parties won nine seats, according to election commission figures. two other small parties had one seat each, and independents gained seven
another 30 seats in parliament are reserved for women, who are chosen later
opposition leaders alleged that the outcome was due to rigged voting, which is common in bangladesh politics
the opposition, which launched a campaign nov. 10 to demand ershad's ouster, succeeded in shutting down most of dhaka on election day with a general strike. but the government said the election, the fourth in bangladesh's 17 years of independence from pakistan, was ``successful and peaceful.''
foreign reporters who visited polling stations in and around dhaka noted a low turnout and much vote tampering
ershad, a former army general who seized power in a 1982 bloodless coup, called the elections in a failed attempt to appease the opposition
at separate news conferences today, chief opposition leaders sheik hasina and khaleda zia vowed to continue the campaign to oust ershad, who was elected president in 1986 in balloting they say was rigged
in those elections, the jatiya party won 152 seats in parliament. the main opposition awami league won 102, and small parties held the rest
the two opposition leaders said rallies in dhaka were planned for saturday to protest the balloting
ershad scheduled thursday's elections after he dissolved parliament last december, 3{ years ahead of schedule. the move was aimed at working out a compromise with his foes, but they demanded instead that ershad step down and said elections held under him wouldn't be fair
election officials and some jatiya party said ballot boxes were stuffed to favor the governing party and inflate the turnout
the independent bangladesh observer newspaper reported on polling in nine cities and did not list any with heavy voting. the descriptions it used for turnout in various cities were ``very negligible ... very meager ... 1 percent to 2 percent'' of the 47.8 million eligible voters
home minister abdul matin claimed there was a good turnout
he told reporters that on the basis of 12 voting centers he visited in dhaka, he estimated voter turnout at 50 percent
a teen-ager accused of fatally bludgeoning a classmate with a baseball bat for a thrill smiled while denying any knowledge of the boy's fate two days after the slaying, a detective testified
he was very calm, almost bored, sort of like, `don't bother me.' he grinned, when i asked if he knew where shaun was,'' detective john devine said during the second day of rod matthews' trial in norfolk superior court
devine said thursday he questioned matthews twice about 14-year-old shaun ouillette's whereabouts
prosecutors say matthews, a 15-year-old being tried as an adult in the 1986 slaying, showed the body in the snowy woods to friends, who stayed mum for weeks
defense attorney john philip white has not denied that matthews killed his classmate. but white said matthews was a mentally ill child from a troubled home and whose use of the prescribed drug ritalin, used to counter hyperactivity in children, contributed to his actions
devine testified he went to matthews' home after a bus driver said he had seen matthews and ouillette together the previous afternoon
when asked where ouillette was, matthews, then 14, said he had not seen him the previous day and suggested he might be in a neighboring town, the detective said
during later questioning, matthews said he played pool at home with ouillette on nov. 20, two days before matthews' initial questioning, but still denied knowing anything about his whereabouts, devine testified
forensic pathologist george katsas, who performed an autopsy, testified the victim had three head injuries, the largest six inches long, which fractured the skull
chemist robert pino of the state police crime lab said blood and hair on the bat matched ouillette's
other former friends told a shocked courtroom wednesday of viewing ouillette's body only hours after a pre-thanksgiving pep rally, then bicycling with matthews to a shopping mall pizza parlor for a snack
he said it could happen to us. he said, `you never know,''' testified robbie peterson
the former friends said matthews named several potential victims before settling on ouillette, an overweight high school freshman who had moved to the community south of boston a year earlier
nicaragua called for direct talks between president reagan and president daniel ortega and said congress' rejection of aid to the contras would help peace in central america
the lefist sandinista government thursday also urged the reagan administration not to interfere in cease-fire talks between it and the contras, the u.s.-backed group that has been fighting to overthrow it
a statement released by government spokesman manuel espinoza said the u.s. house of representatives' rejection of aid for the nicaraguan rebels ``must contribute to the peace efforts taken by the presidents of the central american countries.''
the house voted 216-210 to kill the $30 million package of ``humanitarian'' aid
the contras, meanwhile, accepted ortega's proposal to resume negotiations in nicaragua march 9-11, but said cardinal miguel obando y bravo must be kept on as mediator
ortega said the talks should go on without the roman catholic archbishop of managua, who mediated two previous rounds
the president proposed that the new talks be held in the town of sapoa near the costa rican border. the government also reiterated its call for direct talks between ortega and reagan
the government of nicaragua urges one more time that the president of the united states undertake direct negotiations with the president of nicaragua that take into account security aspects (and) the normalization of relations'' between the two countries, the statement said
the united states has insisted on talks between the contras and sandinistas and has refused to talk to the nicaraguan government
the nicaraguan talks are being held in line with a peace plan signed by five central american presidents on aug. 7. japanese firm</head>
the washington metropolitan area transit authority has rejected a $49.2 million low bid from a construction consortium that included a japanese firm, citing a congressional ban on awarding federally funded contracts to japanese companies
the provision, signed by president reagan in december, bars the awarding of contracts to firms of any country that discriminates against foreign bidders in its own public works projects
it was aimed at japan, which has prohibited foreign participation in more than $60 billion worth of public works projects it plans during the next 10 years
the metro board made its decision thursday as u.s. and japanese negotiators were meeting at the state department in an attempt to resolve the construction dispute, a major source of contention between the two countries
sen. frank murkowski, r-alaska, who co-authored the provision with rep. jack brooks, d-texas, hailed metro's decision
the japanese private sector needed to know that america is ready to use the leverage at our disposal to open their market. if they didn't think we meant business before, they know it now,'' murkowskiaid
no one is going to take a chance of using a japanese firm in any capacity for any project,'' said metro deputy general counsel robert polk. the law ``will have the desired congressional effect,'' he said
the low bid came from a joint venture between kiewit construction of omaha, neb., and the kajima construction company of japan to work on tunnels and rails for a new subway line, which is to run beneath an existing station in northeast washington. kajima was a 30 percent partner in the plan, and kiewit 70 percent
john f. mcelhenny, metro's assistant general manager for design, said bidding on the project will be reopened. he said rejection of the contract is not likely to delay construction, which is scheduled for completion in 1993
a 77-year-old man accused in the mercy killing of his ailing wife received reassurances from family members as he attended her funeral in the company of the county sheriff
you know i really loved her, don't you?'' a weeping oscar carlson asked his daughter, marcene cole, as he reached to hug her after the service thursday at faith lutheran church
of course,'' mrs. cole said through her tears as they embraced
carlson, described as a kind man and a regular churchgoer, was escorted to the funeral by douglas county sheriff terry eilers and three deputies. the frail former farmer did not wear handcuffs or leg chains
asked if carlson's family had forgiven him, nephew gordon johnson said, ``right after it happened.''
look at what oscar was going through,'' johnson said. ``you live with someone for 40-some years ... they were always together ... and then it all falls apart. i think there's a lot of sympathy for oscar.''
carlson was charged with first- and second-degree murder after authorities said he used a .22-caliber weapon to shoot his 71-year-old wife, agnes, four times monday at a nursing home
carlson said he killed his wife of 47 years to spare her from the agony of alzheimer's disease, a debilitating ailment that leaves its victims disoriented and often unable to care for themselves. agnes carlson exhibited the first signs of the disease four years ago
just before the service thursday, carlson was allowed a moment alone at the open casket. he held his wife's hand for a time and then relatives came up to embrace him
pastor george larson did not mention the circumstances of mrs. carlson's death. instead, he urged the family to take comfort in the biblical promise of life after death
agnes believed in the lord,'' larson told the approximately 120 mourners. ``when we believe in the lord jesus christ we have already begun our eternal life and death is just a passing.''
carlson was returned to jail in alexandria after the service to await a monday hearing, at which his attorney plans to request that carlson's $100,000 bail be reduced and he be allowed to use his house as collateral. pvs: `on wednesday...'</note>
a british official of the oxfam relief organization was kidnapped with a syrian colleague in the southern port city of sidon, oxfam headquarters said today
peter coleridge, 44, and omar traboulsi, 31, were seized thursday night, oxfam spokesman john magrath said in oxford, england. coleridge is the organization's middle east coordinator and traboulsi is its lebanon representative, he said
we've had conflicting reports as to whether they are still being held or not,'' magrath said
no one claimed responsibility for the abductions, which brought the number of foreigners missing and believed kidnapped in lebanon to 24
there were no eyewitnesses confirming the abduction, said nissrine rawda, an official at oxfam's beirut office
oxfam is a british charity that aids refugees and poor people around the world
ms. rawda said coleridge went to sidon thursday accompanied by at least two local oxfam staff members and had been expected back in beirut later today. sidon is 25 miles south of beirut
she said coleridge arrived in lebanon two days ago on his first visit in three years to inspect oxfam's operations. he lives in oxford with his wife and two daughters
magrath said he could not give any other details of the abduction. a police spokesman said lebanese authorities had no information about a missing briton
we have ideas about who might have done it, but we don't want to speculate,'' magrath said
the people we work with on the ground have told us not to panic. we know they're making contacts in sidon to find out exactly what's happened and see that peter and omar are released.''
the christian-controlled voice of lebanon radio station earlier reported in beirut that coleridge and trabousli were missing shortly after their arrival in sidon
a british embassy official termed the report at that time ``a false alarm.''
sidon is lebanon's third largest city with a predominantly sunni moslem population of about 250,000
on wednesday, pro-iranian shiite moslem militants released a west german captive, ralph schray, 30, in beirut five weeks after he was kidnapped
two u.n. relief and works agency officials, jan stening, 44, of sweden and william jorgensen, 58, of norway, were kidnapped near sidon feb. 5, apparently by palestinians acting independently of guerrilla groups
their abductors handed the two over to the palestine liberation organization on tuesday after 25 days in captivity
twenty-two other foreigners are missing and believed kidnapped in lebanon. they include nine americans, four frenchmen, three britons, a west german, an italian, an irishman, an indian and two unidentified men
the hostage held longest is american terry anderson, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press. he was seized march 16, 1985. figures. picks up in 3rd graf, ``productivity among.</note>
unemployment slipped 0.1 percent to 5.7 percent last month as half a million new jobs were created, the government said today
the february decline brought unemployment to its lowest level since the summer of 1979 and followed no change in jobless levels in january, the labor department said
employment grew by 280,000, with the number of jobless americans falling by 108,000 to 6.9 million, the department said in its survey of households
a separate survey of business payrolls showed a net increase of 531,000 jobs in february, 40 percent of which were in service industries
on thursday, the department said the nation's productivity rose just 0.9 percent last year, only slightly more than earlier estimates and the lowest since the last recession, the government says
meanwhile, the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks slipped 7.80 points to 2,063.49, the dollar was mixed in foreign exchange and bond prices barely budged in lethargic trading
productivity among non-farm businesses that are responsible for three-fourths of the nation's economic activity rose at an annual rate of 0.3 percent in the fourth quarter, the labor department said. that contrasted with a 0.2 percent deterioration reported in preliminary figures last month
productivity is a measure of the amount of labor required to produce goods and services
the revisions raised the productivity improvement for the entire year from 0.8 percent to 0.9 percent, slightly more than half the 1.6 percent gain of 1986
the efficiency improvements for the year were the smallest since 1982, when an economic recession depressed output so much that productivity actually declined 0.6 percent from 1981
anything less than 1 percent is a disappointing number,'' said roger brinner, an economist for data resources inc. of lexington, mass. ``it gives you very little room to buffer pay increases and not much leeway to improve the standard of living.''
the revised figures on productivity showed output of goods and services by non-farm businesses rising by an annual rate of 5.6 percent in the fourth quarter
that was the greatest increase in nearly two years and compared with a rise of 5.1 percent in the preliminary figures before the gross national product was revised upward last week by the commerce department
but in achieving that higher output, businesses increased the total hours worked by their employees by 5.3 percent
frankly, we don't foresee much improvement in productivity this year,'' said donald straszheim, chief economist for merrill lynch. ``productivity improvements require rapid growth and we haven't been experiencing much of that lately.'' edits to trim. no pickup</note>
a twin-engine commuter plane flying from nancy to paris crashed near the capital this morning while waiting to land, killing all 22 people aboard, aviation authorities said
the fairchild 227 turboprop, owned by the small aviation company tat, apparently hit high-tension wires and crashed in a field in pamfou, a town near melun, 25 miles southwest of paris, police said
the force of the crash gouged a huge hole in the plowed land, police said. officials said there was snow in the region and temperatures were below freezing
the aircraft was carrying 19 passengers, including a baby, and three crew members, tat commercial director patrice decourt told the associated press. earlier reports said 21 people were aboard
debris from the plane was spread out over hundreds of square yards and workers were combing the field and surrounding forests
the director of the nancy-essey airport, jean-claude philippe, said the plane had been circling the melun area in the seine-et-marne region, 25 miles southeast of paris, waiting for orders to land at orly airport
planes are landed sooner or later. so they are stacked up, waiting for a free runway,'' philippe said. ``they don't wait long, of course. several minutes.''
decourt said the plane was in the holding pattern for six to seven minutes after the 50-minute flight from nancy, then ``plunged very rapidly'' to the ground
the cause of the accident was not immediately known. police and rescue workers were searching the area for the aircraft's black box
the plane ... was perhaps in a situation of intense icing, but tat's experience with this type of plane leads us to believe that circumstances which we are not yet aware of led to the accident,'' said a statement issued by tat
the u.s.-made fairchild 227 is built under license from the dutch company fokker
the last ground contact with the plane was at 7:32 a.m., according to the control tower at orly. the aircraft disappeared from the radar five minutes later
a trainee flight attendant, helene guillou, said in nancy that she missed the flight because she overslept
i was an intern hostess and this morning i didn't hear the alarm clock,'' ms. gillou said in a telephone interview with the associated press
she said the same plane made a trip without problems thursday night but that the pilot had mentioned icy conditions
today's crash was the worst plane accident in france since 1981, when a yugoslav dc-9 went down near ajaccio, corsica, in the mediterranean, killing 180 people. returning to pakistan. no pickup. najib, one name, is cq.</note>
peace talks on afghanistan recessed today so pakistan could decide if it is willing to sign a settlement with the soviet-backed afghan government. the mediator said all substantial differences had been worked out
the head of the pakistani delegation, acting foreign minister zain noorani, flew back to islamabad for weekend consultations with the country's political leaders, including opposition representatives
the meeting will mark the first time the pakistan government has sought direct contact with its opposition since president gen. mohammad zia ul-haq seized power and imposed martial in july 1977 coup
pakistan has represented afghanistan's anti-marxist moslem guerrillas in the peace talks
the two sides agreed thursday to a nine-month timetable for the pullout of soviet troops from afghanistan, with half the estimated 115,000 troops to be withdrawn in the first 90 days
u.n. mediator diego cordovez said no major differences remained. but the negotiators did not resolve the issue of what government would be in power in afghanistan to oversee implementation of a settlement
over the weekend, pakistan will try to decide whether it is willing to sign a settlement with president najib's government, which it does not recognize
noorani said there was no change in pakistan's position that the settlement should be accompanied by formation of a transitional government in kabul to prevent more bloodshed
not all opposition parties have declared their stand on afghanistan but most have urged the government to sign a soviet pullout accord, then worry about a political settlement later
the geneva talks are set to resume monday
cordovez told reporters that that the withdrawal issue had long stalled the almost 6-year-old negotiations. he said its resolution meant a ``significant step'' toward concluding a settlement
i am not going to consider that these documents are absolutely ready until they are signed and sealed,'' he said, but also stated repeatedly that the ``remaining differences are not of substance.''
there is no doubt about the political significance of the agreements reached this week and also of some understandings that have started to evolve'' regarding other oustanding problems, he said
he did not elaborate but made plain that he is increasingly confident that there will be an eventual accord on the future shape of the kabul government
cordovez said that both kabul and islamabad recognized that a broad-based afghan government would make a settlement ``more effective,'' although their concepts differ
he also said he believed that the afghan resistance movement, which is flatly opposed to any power-sharing with the present leadership, will change its attitude once a settlement is complete
the chief afghan delegate, abdul wakil, reiterated thursday that kabul was ready to talk with all political forces, including the resistance movements, about the formation of new government
a three-member team from the office of the u.n. commissioner for refugees returned to geneva today from a fact-finding visit in afghanistan
a spokeswoman, judith kumin, said the team followed an invitation of the kabul government. she said it was evident that the office would have a role in repatriating the more than 5 million afghan refugees once a settlement was reached
an estimated 3 million refugees are in pakistan, and another 2 million are in iran. differences</head>
police today dragged away dozens of protesters demanding the release of political prisoners and trying to march into the presidential mansion
about 30 family members of imprisoned dissidents gathered in front of the blue house, the presidential residence, demanding an interview with president roh tae-woo
riot police took away the protesters, who shouted anti-government slogans and tried to march into the residence
at seoul national university, about 200 students called for the release of political prisoners and denounced a recent government amnesty as insufficient
the government released about 130 political prisoners last saturday, saying only dissidents guilty of violent crimes or subversion remained in prison
the joong-ang ilbo, an influential seoul newspaper, said the freed dissidents are under surveillance and that their daily activities were reported to security authorities
also today, the governing and opposition parties resolved their differences over electoral rules and other issues, clearing the way for national assembly elections expected in mid-april
in addition, senior officials of the two main opposition parties, controlled by kim young-sam and kim dae-jung, agreed on basic rules for their merger before the balloting
in december's presidential election, the two kims split the opposition vote. roh won with 36.6 percent of the vote
the officials said after a three-hour meeting that they would propose the elections be held under a system picking one lawmaker instead of two in each district
the governing democratic justice party welcomed the opposition proposal
the governing party, which had favored a system electing one to three members in each district depending on the size of population, changed its position today on the order of the president
before today's meeting, the opposition camp was itself divided over the election formula, forcing a delay in adopting the new laws needed before balloting can be held
the proposed reform would increase the overall number of legislators from 271 to 300 by increasing the number of districts
the government today decreed a ban on smoking in public places and launched a campaign to try to convince this nation of smokers to give up the habit
the government of socialist prime minister felipe gonzalez also outlawed the selling of tobacco to anyone under 16
the ban will take effect in july, three months after its publication in the official state bulletin. it was in keeping with directives issued by the european economic community
representatives of spain's tobacco industry agreed to accept a complete ban on television advertising and restrictions limiting outdoor advertising to the name of their brand
according to eec statistics, 41 percent of spain's 38.8 million people smoke, the second highest figure in the 12-nation community after greece
the same statistics indicate about 60,000 spaniards die each year from smoking-related diseases
the decree requires cigarette and cigar packages to carry the warning that smoking causes cancer and endangers the life of the smoker as well as unborn babies
it bans smoking in hospitals, department stores, elevators and places where pregnant women work and prohibits the sale of tobacco products to minors under 16
the decree says that the rights of non-smokers over those of smokers will take priority in all legal questions. it carries fines on infractions ranging from $4,400 to $880,000, but its enforcement mechanism remains unclear
spanish explorers who traveled to central and south america in the 16th century returned with string-tied rolls of tobacco leaves that became the rage among their wealthy countrymen under the name ``cigar.''
etymologists believe the word comes from ``sik'ar,'' the term the mayan indians of central america used for smoking
cigarillos'' or ``little cigars'' were devised by street beggars in seville from the butts of cast-off cigars and are the forerunners of today's cigarettes
the government will hold an unprecedented meeting with its political opposition to discuss whether pakistan should sign a peace accord with afghanistan, officials said today
saturday's meeting will mark the first time the pakistan government has sought direct contact with the opposition since before july 1977, when president gen. mohammad zia ul-haq seized power and imposed martial law
officials said nearly all 19 parties have accepted an invitation to meet with prime minister mohammad khan junejo
the chief of the pakistani delegation to the u.n. afghanistan talks in geneva, foreign state minister zain noorani, was to return to islamabad today, after the third day of indirect negotiations with the communist afghan government
pakistani officials said junejo wanted to discuss whether pakistan should link an accord over a soviet troop withdrawal from afghanistan with the formation of an interim coalition government in kabul
about 115,000 soviet troops are in afghanistan. the soviets have been fighting afghan rebels since 1979 when they entered the country and replaced the existing communist government with another one
almost all opposition leaders pledged to attend the extraordinary meeting except pakistan people's party leader benazir bhutto, who was reported ill with influenza. her karachi office said she would at least fly to islamabad to consult with her representatives
ms. bhutto's father, ousted prime minister zulfikar ali bhutto, was hanged in 1979 after he was convicted of plotting a political murder
zia lifted martial law on dec. 30, 1985, after the installation of junejo's muslim league government the previous march
most opposition parties boycotted the election that brought junejo to power and still refuse to recognize his government
pakistan's largest opposition alliance, the nine-party movement for the restoration of democracy, decided to accept the government's gesture because it was not founded in protest over foreign policy, said sheikh rafiq ahmed, an official in mrs. bhutto's party
not all opposition parties have declared their stand on afghanistan but most have urged the government to sign a soviet pullout accord, then worry about a political settlement later
in a recent turnabout, pakistan has threatened not to sign a geneva accord that does not provide a safe environment for the return of the 5 million afghan refugees living in pakistan and iran
islamabad has said it fears that the soviets' absence will clear the way for a new bloody internecine struggle between the pro-moscow government of president najib and afghan moslem guerrillas, based in pakistan
saturday's meeting could give the pakistanis a face-saving pretext to soften their controversial stance at geneva. it also could serve to enhance the muslim league government's own legitimacy at home
about half the city's ambulance workers scheduled for the day shift called in sick today, but police and supervisory employees were helping fill gaps in service, the city said
the emergency medical service instituted a contingency plan to meet the job action, which had been announced in advance as a demonstration for higher pay
sick calls were received from 176 of 347 workers on the day shift, said suzanne halpin of the health and hospitals corp., parent of ems and operator of the municipal hospitals system
the employees calling in are being told they may be violating a court order and the taylor law,'' she said. penalties ranging from loss of two days' pay to dismissal were possible. the taylor law is a state law that prohibits strikes by public employees
some of the gaps in ambulance service were being filled by police and other ems employees, including supervisors, halpin said
the sickout, which was announced as a one-day protest, was barred thursday afternoon by supreme court justice edward lehner, who ruled that ems workers could not stage ``any kind of concerted job action.''
the decision to stage a sickout was made by about 400 workers in a vote taken wednesday night while union leaders were kept out of the meeting
the 2,000-member union, without a contract since july, has demanded salary and benefits comparable to police and firefighters, whose starting pay is $26,000, said richard burstein, the union secretary-treasurer
the union has asked that ems starting pay of $21,500 be raised by $6,000 over three years; the city is offering $600
the nuclear regulatory commission is investigating its own offices in atlanta because nrc internal documents involving an investigation of georgia tech's reactor program were found at tech, a newspaper reported today
leaks from the nrc may have tipped tech to the identities of employees at the school's neely nuclear research center who had complained about lax safety procedures, the atlanta constitution said, quoting unidentified sources with congress and the nrc
the two employees, members of the physics staff responsible for safety of nuclear materials, were dismissed and then rehired and given other jobs by tech three weeks ago. they claim they were fired because they complained to the nrc about reactor safety
nrc officials in washington declined to comment
dr. nelson grace, administrator of nrc's southeast regional office in atlanta, acknowledged he had asked the agency's office of inspector-auditor to ``investigate to determine whether or not internal nrc documents may have come into the possession of'' a reactor manager
grace declined to name the reactor, but the constitution quoted other unidentified sources as confirming that it was the now-idled five-megawatt reactor at tech
georgia tech president john p. crecine ordered the reactor out of service until the nrc investigation is completed
the baltimore city school board has banned telephone beepers because school officials said they were being used by students acting as go-betweens in drug deals
effective march 14, students found carrying a beeper face suspension, under the new policy adopted by the board thursday
school officials say the telephone pagers are a status symbol in the drug world, and are also used by students who want to portray the image of being involved in narcotics
when i see a beeper i assume the worst,'' said arthur pierce, principal of francis m. wood high school. ``at the high school and middle school level, if a child is in possession of an operational beeper, they are usually dealing drugs
`at the elementary level, kids are wearing inoperative beepers to appear tough or macho and mimic the older kids. and that's not something to encourage,'' said pierce, who has been confiscating the pagers at his school for the past three years
beepers also were banned from schools in nashville, tenn., in december. similar problems have been reported from florida to michigan
virtually all drug possession arrests in baltimore schools involve marijuana, said larry burgan, school police chief, with a few instances of cocaine or cocaine derivatives
from my standpoint, i don't see any time a student would need to carry a beeper,'' said burgan. ``it's basically a disruptive influence, whether the kids are carrying them to traffic drugs or just to project that image, it's no good.''
pierce said it is hard to determine the scope of the problem because most beepers go undetected
new beepers no longer emit the three short beeps from which their name was derived
the more sophisticated ones vibrate against the body or are fitted with a silencer that keeps them from being detected,'' pierce said
burgan said the drug problem is kept under control largely because city high schools have officers patrolling the halls
the 800-year-old round tower at windsor castle, one of queen elizabeth ii's homes, has been damaged by shifting foundations, the department of the environment said today
the castle overlooking the river thames is reportedly the queen's favorite home and is one of britain's top tourist attractions. the monarch's royal standard is flown from the tower when she is in residence
there has been a slight movement to the round tower at windsor castle. we are looking into it,'' the government department said in a brief statement
the statement added that the cause was not known and gave no details about the extent of the damage
the daily telegraph, which first broke the story, described the damage to the five-story tower as serious following a shift in its ancient foundations
the london newspaper said the tower moved two weeks ago, bringing down plaster, causing cracks to appear in the stonework and jamming a door and two windows
it said the queen had inspected the tower. buckingham palace said in a statement: ``the queen is obviously concerned and is being kept informed.''
the queen and her husband, prince philip, live for much of the year at buckingham palace in london but they and their family spend each christmas at windsor castle. windsor is 21 miles west of london
the round tower is the most imposing feature of the castle. the foundations of the tower and the rest of its lower part were built by king henry ii in 1172. the upper part was added 6{ centuries later in the reign of king george iv
the round tower is built on a mound thrown up by the saxons, the teutonic invaders who conquered britain between the 5th and 7th centuries. they ruled until their army under king harold was beaten at the battle of hastings in 1066 by duke william of normandy, who then became king william i of england
the original castle was built by king william around 1070. graf pvs, cohen suggested.</note>
the senate, kept in the dark by the reagan administration during the iran-contra affair, today rejected an effort to let the white house withhold details about covert actions from congress
the 65-23 vote came as the chamber worked on a bill requiring that congress be notified of all covert actions within 48 hours
the decision came on an amendment by sen. james mcclure, r-idaho, that would have allowed a president simply to tell congress that a covert action was underway but withhold details and specifics until later
this is a compromise. it gives the president some flexibility,'' said mcclure
but sen. william cohen, r-maine, chief author of the bill, opposed mcclure, telling his colleagues, ``this is not a compromise; it's a capitulation. ... this lets the president play `i've got a secret' but not tell.''
this cannot guarantee that future abuses such as iran-contra will not occur, but it will certainly minimize them,'' cohen, vice-chairman of the intelligence committee, said late thursday as debate began
the bill overhauls procedures for notifying congress about intelligence activites. the central feature would require that congress be notified within 48 hours of the time a covert, or secret, action begins
cohen suggested that the requirement could have helped expose the iran-contra affair, in which u.s. weapons were sold to iran and some of the profits were diverted to the nicaraguan contra rebels
reagan's approval of the iranian arms deal was withheld from congress for 10 months in 1986, until it was revealed by a beirut publication
cia director william webster, testifying last month to the house intelligence committee, said the 48-hour notification requirement ``will not be acceptable to the president.'' but webster did not say whether reagan would veto the bill
cohen noted that presidents normally have notified congress of most covert actions ever since congressional review committees were created 14 years ago in the wake of revelations about a series of abuses by the cia
he said it is time to close the last loophole by requiring notification of all such actions
the iran-contra affair shows what happens when a president seeks to circumvent congress,'' cohen said
sen. david boren, d-okla., chairman of the intelligence committee, called the measure ``landmark legislation.''
reagan has promised to notify congress about future covert actions, but boren said, ``we feel a need to put these changes into statute'' to make sure a president does not go back on his word
we do not want our country ever again to go through what it did these last few months because of the iran-contra affair,'' boren said
there's an old saying that two heads are better than one'' said boren. ``in the intelligence committee, we try to give those in the intelligence community our best judgment.''
sen. james mcclure, r-idaho, opposed the bill because he said the notification provision ``could endanger american lives and the lives of others who have taken the risk of assisting the united states.''
sen. malcolm wallop, r-wyo., agreed with mcclure. ``this bill will cost lives,'' he said
the bill was approved by the senate intelligence committee last december on a 13-2 vote. if passed by the full senate, it will need house approval before it would go to reagan's desk
a group of nationalist legislators today asked the taiwan government to drop its 40-year-old policy of having no contact with the communist government in beijing
huang shu-wek, one of the 12 lawmakers questioning the no-contact policy during a legislative yuan session, proposed a ``temporary two-china policy'' to precede eventual reunification
huang said the taipei and beijing governments must ``compete on an equal footing so we can show all chinese people the achievements of taiwan's development and let them accept our system.''
huang proposed that the nationalist government provide financial and technological aid for china's modernization and discuss bilateral trade and other relations with beijing
the two countries already have a secret trade estimated at more than $1 billion a year through third parties such as hong kong and singapore. taiwan recently began allowing its citizens to visit their families on the mainland
the nationalists have refused official contacts with china since 1949 when they fled to taiwan after losing a civil war on the mainland to the communists. both governments claim to be the rightful government of the mainland and taiwan
premier yu kuo-hwa said in response that ``communist china has never treated us equally and the time has not yet come for peaceful competition'' between the two governments
yao chia-wen, chairman of the opposition democratic progressive party, said, ``we don't care too much about the nationalists' claim to represent china.''
dozens of political activists held a torch-light run today through downtown taipei echoing the demands of president lee tung-hi that elderly nationalist chinese legislators elected on the mainland four decades ago should retire
this is the time for our elderly legislators to step down. most of those who voted for them 40 years ago on the mainland have already died,'' opposition legislator you ching told about 100 people outside the national assembly after the run
led by legislator chu kao-cheng of the opposition democratic progressive party, about 60 runners began at the legislative yuan building and finished an hour later outside the national assembly, where opposition leaders delivered speeches from a pickup truck
many elderly members of the legislative yuan, taiwan's highest lawmaking body, and the national assembly, the electoral college, have rejected a proposal for them to retire voluntarily
last saturday lee urged the elderly legislators to resign in accordance with the government's plans to reform taiwan's political system
we must place national interests and public welfare above our personal opinions,'' lee told the national assembly
lawmakers elected on taiwan now account for 73 members of the 312-seat legislative yuan and 106 members of the 934-seat national assembly
the other seats are either empty or held by aging nationalists
opposition leaders said the elderly legislators, who have been frozen in office to support the nationalists' claim to be the legitimate government of mainland china, should yield their seats so all lawmakers can be elected in taiwan
during the run, some activists distributed flyers listing telephone numbers of 120 aging assemblymen. chu has urged taiwanese to call elderly lawmakers and ask them to retire
an engineer testifying in delta air lines suit against the government used an animated videotape recreating the final two minutes of delta flight 191 in an attempt to disprove government claims that the flight crew could have escaped a violent wind shear
charles bautz, a performance engineering manager for the atlanta-based airline, testified thursday that the pilots reacted properly to the turbulent winds during their approach to dallas-fort worth international airport on aug. 2, 1985
in a non-jury trial being heard by u.s. district judge david o. belew jr. of fort worth, delta contends that the federal government should bear legal responsibility for the crash and pay all or part of more than $90 million in death, injury and damage claims delta has paid in connection with the crash
bautz, who worked as a member of a government technical team investigating the crash, presented the videotape recreation based on recorded flight data, which he said shows the crew encountered a second, fatal wind shear seconds after pulling out of the first downdraft
the co-pilot applied maximum power and attempted to abandon the landing, bautz said
a national transportation safety board investigation said the crash that killed 137 people and injured 25 others was caused, in part, by the sudden downdrafts of wind
the airline claims government air traffic controllers and weather forecasters failed to warn the flight crew of the storm
testimony in the trial could last several more weeks, attorneys said
crocodiles in zambia's kafue river have devoured five people since the beginning of the year, and villagers have asked the authorities to shoot the reptiles, a local official said today
dickson ponde, chairman of kasiba ward council in the central copperbelt province, called for immediate action to stop the crocodiles, which he said are attacking several people each week
the five deaths occurred since the beginning of the year. ponde made his plea to rankin sikasula, a senior member of president kenneth kaunda's governing party, when he was inspecting a pontoon bridge on the kafue river
sikasula promised that hunters will soon be sent to the area to reduce the crocodile population. pvs bgng ``dukakis has...</note>
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis today promised to pursue economic and energy policies to help texas ``come back and come back strong,'' including expanded natural gas sales to northeast states
in a speech to 300 people in this west texas city before flying on to denver, cheyenne and seattle, dukakis said the natural gas of the southwest could provide ``clean, efficient, non-polluting, non-acid rain energy'' at a quarter of the cost of nuclear energy from the controversial unlicensed seabrook, n.h., plant that he opposes
dukakis, wrapping up a two-day, 1,200-mile swing through the state with the biggest super tuesday prize, promised he would help texas' distressed oil industry ``come back and come back strong.''
on thursday, dukakis said the last few days to super tuesday may get ``a little dicey'' because of what he characterized as desperate tactics by democratic rival richard gephardt. the missouri congressman has runs ads accusing dukakis of favoring tax increases and knowing nothing about agriculture
dukakis has responded in kind with ads suggesting gephardt has voted to protect the interests of big banks and corporations from which he has collected political action committee money
after a meeting with community organizers at a church hall in houston thursday night, dukakis told reporters, ``i think the next three, four days may be somewhat difficult, only because things may start getting a little dicey between now and tuesday...i think some people are getting desperate.''
asked if he meant gephardt, dukakis said, ``the record is clear. he's running negative ads right now
the folks that attack are usually those that are behind,'' he said
to gephardt's charge that dukakis has accepted campaign money from businesses that have major dealings with the state of massachusetts, the governor replied, ``i don't know what he's talking about. i have over 65,000 individual contributors to my campaign.''
dukakis, who refuses to accept money from pacs, said he has never taken contributions from state lobbyists, or more than $100 from a state employee
what is clear is that the pac system is a very bad system. ... it's time it ended,'' said dukakis, who blamed sen. bob dole of kansas, a republican presidential hopeful, and his gop colleagues for filibustering a bill to curb pac contributions
if i'm president of the united states, the first bill i will send to the congress is the (campaign contributions) bill,'' he vowed
texas offers the biggest prize, 183 delegates, and dukakis was headed back to san antonio saturday night after stops in spokane and little rock, ark
he picked up endorsements thursday from washington gov. booth gardener and sen. brock adams
dukakis also won the backing of the 95,000-member texas state teachers association, which withdrew its earlier endorsement of illinois sen. paul simon, who is for the most part sitting out the south's primaries
dukakis charged gephardt's retaliatory trade legislation could provoke a global trade war and harm u.s.-mexican relations
before largely hispanic audiences at airport rallies in the border towns of harlingen and laredo, dukakis related how gephardt asked him in a recent debate if he was running for ``president of mexico.''
i said, `dick, if i'm president of the united states, i'm going to pay attention to our relationship with mexico and i'm going to make sure that our proposals do not wreck the economy of mexico,'' dukakis said to cheers
we're going to .. work with our neighbors in mexico as partners to create opportunity on both sides of the border.''
in both harlingen and laredo, the multilingual dukakis, who grew up speaking greek and english _ spoke at length in spanish
in houston, dukakis stood with his wife, kitty, before a two-story lone star flag draped against the glass elevators in the atrium of the hyatt-regency hotel. he told 600 supporters: ``i don't have to tell you how important `super martes' is.''
he ended his appeals with this: ``poco a poco, paso a paso, mano en mano, juntos, vamos a ganar,'' or, as he translated, ``little by little, step by step, hand in hand, together, we shall succeed.''
the cleveland teachers union has recommended that its 5,100 members ratify a tentative agreement reached after a weeklong strike that closed city schools for most of the district's 73,000 students
schools were closed today but probably will reopen monday, superintendent alfred tutela said
the school board scheduled a meeting for saturday night to consider ratifying the agreement and discuss plans for reopening the schools, he said
eugene kolach, president of the teachers union, said the union's executive board voted thursday night to endorse the pact, which was reached earlier after nearly 24 hours of negotiations
our executive board has voted to suspend our strike beginning monday,'' kolach said. ``it's not a case of being happy with the pact, it's a case of understanding when we've gotten the best possible situation.''
both sides declined to discuss the terms of the agreement until after teachers vote on it. kolach said the union planned a five-day voting period for its 5,093 members following an information meeting sunday
teachers walked off their jobs feb. 25, but district officials canceled classes that day because of snow. cleveland schools have been closed since then because of the strike, except for classes that began wednesday for some of the district's 3,600 high school seniors
at least some of the missed school days will have to be made up to meet state requirements
the union's contract expired in september, but union members continued working. the district's teacher salaries range from $17,600 to $37,450, based on education and experience. the average annual salary is $29,500
the last teachers' strike in cleveland, ohio's largest school district and the 30th largest school system in the united states, was an 11-week walkout in 1979. background. pick up 14th pvs, `among the...'</note>
militant sikhs burst into a courtyard and opened fire on a crowd celebrating a hindu holiday, killing at least 34 people and wounding about 45, police said today
the attack in the northern state of punjab was one of the bloodiest since sikh extremists launched their guerrilla war for an independent homeland there in 1982. it occurred shortly before midnight
a. siddiqui, a deputy inspector general of police, said most of the victims were hindus, but nine sikhs were among those killed
about 900 hindus, sikhs and christians had gathered outside a hindu temple to celebrate holi, the festival of color. the national holiday commemorates the triumph of the hindu god lord krishna over evil
the attack brought to more than 370 the number of people killed this year in attacks blamed on sikh extremists. sikhs are a religious minority in india and claim they are discriminated against by the majority hindus
in an apparent peace overture today, the government freed four sikh high priests. the release of 40 sikh militants was also planned, the united news of india reported from the punjab state capital of chandigarh
there was no immediate claim of responsibility for the attack in kari sari, which is about 80 miles east of the sikh holy city of amritsar. police blamed the kalistan commando force. kalistan is the name sikh militants would given to their envisioned nation
mahavir prashad, who was inside a building and escaped injury, said:, ``people ran helter-skelter. there were bodies on the ground, and the injured were crying
i tried to save some of the injured by giving them water, but most of them died in my arms.''
siddiqui, addressing a news conference in the nearby town of hoshiarpur, said the shooting lasted about 20 minutes. he said six to eight gunmen participated
brij kishore, deputy superintendent of police at chandigarh, the state capital, said villagers had gathered around two bonfires and were singing songs when the gunmen drove up in three cars, opened fire with ak-47 assault rifles and machine guns, and fled
police said 23 people were killed on the spot and 11 others taken to hospitals died later of their injuries
punjab security forces and new delhi police were put on alert after the killing to prevent any backlash
the attack was the worst in punjab since last july, when sikh gunmen waylaid three buses and slaughtered 72 people, most of them hindus. thirty-eight hindu pilgrims were killed and 24 injured july 6 when a bus was attacked near chandigarh. the next day, 34 people died in attacks on two buses in neighboring haryana state
among the priests released today was jasbir singh rode, a nephew of the late sikh radical leader jarnail singh bhindranwale
the other three are jaswant singh, kashmir singh and savinder singh, who were arrested in october
rode was the chief priest at the golden temple in amritsar when he was arrested during a june 1984 army raid that drove militants out of the temple, the sikh's holiest shrine. bhindranwale was among the 1,200 killed in the raid
indian prime minister indira gandhi, who ordered the raid, was assassinated by two of her sikh bodyguards four months later. her son and successor, rajiv gandhi, signed a peace accord with sikh leaders in july 1985 to try to end the hostility. the accord later fell apart
on thursday night, punjab representatives from parliament met with leaders of gandhi's party and urged freedom for the priests ``so they can use their high position to restore normalcy'' in punjab, uni reported. 0793</first> praised.</note>
the national research council said today its 14-month review of the challenger disaster has found ``no show-stoppers'' to prevent nasa from resuming manned space flights in august
we are all quite comfortable with what has been done to get ready for the next flight,'' said alton d. slay, a retired general who headed a 12-member committee that audited the space agency's efforts to recover from the accident
but, he cautioned, ``no matter how good you are, you never reach mecca; there is always room for improvement.''
the committee's central finding, he said, is that nasa has the ability to assess and manage risks associated with space flights, but uses so many review boards and safety organizations that the result is ``a fragmented picture of the safety and reliability of the total space transportation system.''
further, he said, those organizations rely on subjective assessements of risk posed by thousands of individual space shuttle components, rather than on engineering evaluations
we are both favorably impressed with nasa's progress thus far in addressing space shuttle safety issues and full of suggestions for further improvements,'' slay said
although we have criticisms, we did not find anything that will delay the next space shuttle launch,'' said slay, a former head of the u.s. air force systems command. launch of the shuttle discovery is scheduled aug. 4
slay praised nasa for having made ``real strides'' in enhancing the safety of the shuttle and said ``we found no show-stoppers.''
in a brief response, the space agency said it acted on early drafts of the committee's report ``and most of the recommendations made by the council essentially are in place.''
the nrc review was recommended by the presidential commission that investigated the jan. 28, 1986 accident that destroyed the challenger and killed its crew 73 seconds after liftoff. the nrc acts as a scientific advisory group to the federal government and is administered by the national academy of sciences, the national academy of engineering and the institute of medicine
as the challenger accident made painfully obvious, no probe into space is routine and the space shuttle is still a developmental vehicle,'' said the nrc committee. ``the risks of space flight must be accepted by those who are asked to participate in each flight as well as by those who are responsible to the nation for achieving its goals in space.''
the report said that one of the key failures that led to the challenger disaster was that the history of problems with the shuttle booster o-rings was not known by the officials who gave the go-ahead for the ill-fated launch. an o-ring that allowed hot gases to escape was blamed for the accident
the committee has found numerous indications that data from sts (space transportation system) inspection, test and repair, and inflight operations do not always feed back rapidly enough or effectively enough into the risk management process,'' the report said
it noted that nasa now intends to review all data from each flight before going ahead with the next one, at least during the shuttle's initial flights. but the committee worried that once the pace increases ``the same dangerous preconditions will once again be present.''
the number of items deemed to be of ``criticality 1 and 1r'' _ items whose failure could doom the shuttle _ has increased from 2,369 before the challenger accident to 4,686 because of re-evaluation of the shuttle system and tighter ground rules, the committee said
but, said the committee, all criticality 1 items are not alike and nasa is wrong in not assigning priorities
the most likely and most threatening failure modes merit the most attention,'' said the report
the committee found:
_nasa tends to focus on ``single-event, worst case failures'' in making risk analyses and ``there does not appear to be an adequate integrated-system view of the entire sts.''
_before the challenger accident, cannibalization of parts from one shuttle to another was routine, introducing greater chance of failure through human error. the committee recommended that enough money be available ``to ensure that cannibalization is a rare requirement.''
_so many boards and panels are watching every aspect of the shuttle system that individuals might ``defer to the anonymity of the process'' and not take responsibility for decisions
_tests on the solid rocket booster are performed at the manufacturing plant in utah and there is a risk that damage may result from the long rail trip to the kennedy space center in florida. the committee recommended that ``non-destructive tests'' _ tests that stop short of firing the rocket _ be performed at the launch site
urban planners eager to revitalize aging industrial centers are urging city dwellers to take charge of their own future, and are looking to britain's prince charles to drive that message home
charles arrived today in cold and rainy to take part in an international architectural symposium and get a first-hand look at the despair and disrepair of once-mighty u.s. steel towns
we see him as somewhat of a catalyst'' for urban renewal efforts from within, said volker hartkopf, an architecture professor at carnegie mellon university here
the prince of wales has emerged as an outspoken advocate of community architecture and inner-city rehabilitation over the past few years
he made worldwide headlines in december when he accused architects of wreaking more havoc on london than german bombers did in world war ii, and said postwar planners were artless, mediocre and contemptuous of public opinion
more than anyone else in his position, he has tried to find out for himself exactly what it (urban decay) is because he is concerned,'' said roger tillotson, lecturer at the university of newcastle upon tyne in england
prince charles is honorary chairman of the four-day remaking cities conference, which is exploring ways to bring prosperity back to depressed communities in the united states and britain
this afternoon, he plans to visit a new jobs center for the region's blue-collar unemployed and a high school computer training classroom
on the conference's last day saturday, he is to address about 350 people attending the symposium sponsored by the american institute of architects and royal institute of british architects
in his speech, the 39-year-old heir to the british throne is expected to comment on recommendations made by conference delegates for helping cities move from single-industry to more diversified economies
before, like it or not, companies took care of life. you may not have liked everything they did. but they were there. it was secure,'' said john clarke, a trenton, n.j., architect
but when that goes away, suddenly you turn around and say, `gee, the leadership used to be the company.' now the leadership has to be you,'' said clarke, who led a 17-member study of the region's depressed steel towns
in its 120-page report presented monday, the team stressed the need for public participation in replacing the darkened factories dominating the monongahela river banks parks, gardens, marinas and shops
that valley is a gold mine, and i think these people would be fools not to take up the opportunity,'' said team member tony mcgann, a planner from liverpool, england. ``it's a golden opportunity that might not come again.'' noriega. removes last 3 grafs pvs to shorten.</note>
the senate foreign relations committee voted unanimously today for a resolution urging the reagan administration to end all contacts with gen. manuel antonio noriega and to consider imposing economic sanctions against his military regime in panama
but the committee took no action on legislation introduced on thursday and co-sponsored by 25 senators which would impose a total trade embargo on panama in an effort to break noriega's hold on the country
the 15-0 committee vote approving the non-binding resolution came after administration officials, seeking to avoid passage of trade embargo legislation, proposed a set of milder alternatives that still would penalize the noriega regime
national security adviser colin powell told reporters thursday night that several economic and financial measures were being prepared for consideration by president reagan, but he refused to be more specific
other officials, insisting on anonymity, said the administration believes a bipartisan congressional proposal for a trade, air, travel and currency embargo against panama would be unwise
the administration believes u.s. interests would be better served if noriega were ousted primarily by panamanian _ and not american _ pressure
the officials said displays of american heavy-handedness could be used by noriega to his advantage and could produce resentment elsewhere in latin america, where u.s. intervention has long been a popular anti-american rallying cry
the committee resolution declares that eric arturo devalle, who was ousted by the panamanian parliament after trying to fire noriega as commander of panama's armed forces, remains the country's legitimate head of state and should reeceive ``the full moral, political and diplomatic support of the government of the united states.''
it called on the white house to ``formally terminate any and all contacts with gen. noriega.''
the government of the united states should consider further measures to support democracy (in panama), including economic sanctions, in the event gen. noriega continues to defy president devalle's lawful order,'' the resolution declared
it also called on the white house to study the impact on u.s. energy supplies if noriega reacts to possible economic sanctions by shutting down the trans-panama petroleum pipeline used to transport alaskan oil to the east coast of the united states
for noriega, panamanian independence from the united states has been his principal line of defense in his struggle to survive. it was a recurring theme at a pro-government demonstration in panama earlier this week when a crowd of 3,000 turned out to cheer noriega
shortly before powell made his comments to reporters while returning with reagan from the nato summit in brussels, belgium, six republicans and democrats introduced the embargo bill
it would prohibit all trade and air travel between the two countries and bar u.s. banks from transferring any funds to panama and its banking system
by stopping the transfer of funds from u.s. banks to panama, we go for the jugular,'' said sen. alfonse d'amato, r-n.y., a principal sponsor of the embargo plan
because of panama's heavy reliance on its economic ties with the united states, the impact of a u.s. trade embargo would be immediate, dramatic and devastating to noriega and his cohorts,'' d'amato said
a ban on panamanian goods would paralyze a $412 million market representing 60 percent of panama's total exports, d'amato said. a ban on u.s. exports to panama would affect a 30 percent slice of all panamanian imports, he said
other sponsors of the embargo bill are sens. edward m. kennedy, d-mass.; david durenberger, r-minn.; bob graham, d-fla.; john kerry, d-mass.; and jesse helms, r-n.c
the administration has been sending mixed signals about the degree to which it is willing to pressure noriega, who is under federal indictment on drug smuggling charges and who forced out the constitutionally elected president last week
some officials are sensitive to charges that the administration has not done enough to oppose noriega while others believe broader u.s. interests require a cautious approach
in any case, there appears to be a consensus within the administration that a trade embargo is too ambitious a step. the administration is hopeful a combination of other pressures will force an end to noriega's rule
the issue of whether to withhold a $7 million u.s. payment due in mid-march to panama for canal-related fees and services has underscored the split in the administration
assistant secretary of state elliott abrams has said that the administration will refuse to deliver the funds if such a request is received from ousted president eric arturo delvalle
but on thursday, state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley said no final decision has been made on that issue even though the administration has had the request in hand since earlier in the week
she acknowledged, however, that the request probably will be honored
with an assist from the administration, panamanian authorities apparently have been denied access to official funds on deposit in u.s. banks
at a news conference thursday night at the panamanian embassy, an attorney for delvalle said federal courts in new york and boston have issued temporary restraining orders to prevent withdrawal of the funds
we believe that whatever funds are in those institutions are at this point frozen and cannot be transmitted to the noriega regime,'' said daniel resnick, a washington attorney. ahead</head> topping with 11 grafs, picking up in 6th graf pvs, kemp battered, and subbing 14th graf pvs, in the; cuts last 5 grafs</note>
most of the presidential candidates campaigned hard in the south today, four days before the region's super tuesday primaries, but albert gore jr. detoured to connecticut to raise money for a southern campaign that he said was turning in his direction
in washington, meanwhile, attorneys for former rep. paul mccloskey filed notice in court that they oppose pat robertson's effort to drop a libel suit filed after mccloskey questioned his war record
unless a federal judge dismisses the case, as robertson has asked, a legal matter that has become a clear distraction for robertson could tie him up even further beginning on tuesday when the trial is scheduled to begin
in appearances today:
_vice president george bush, campaigning in a state that votes on saturday, told a cheering crowd of 1,500 students in west columbia, s.c., ``your state is going to have a mobilizing effect. if we're successful in south carolina, i think you'll be able to say, the next president of the united states was here in our school.''
_massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, in lubbock, texas, told voters in the biggest super tuesday state, he would to pursue economic and energy policies to help texas ``come back and come back strong.''
_gore, in new haven, conn., raised an estimated $50,000 for his campaign during a breakfast with state democrats. he said there is a shift going on to his advantage in southern states, and ``the undecided vote, which has been very large, is now breaking in our direction.''
elsewhere, richard gephardt was gunning for democratic rival dukakis over special-interest campaign contributions. and robertson lashed out thursday night at what he called ``the real fanatics'' opposed to prayer in public schools
a poll published today gave bush a big lead over republican opponent bob dole in south carolina, whose gop primary on saturday rings the opening bell on tuesday's 20-state punchup
the super tuesday contests, with a prize of 1,307 democratic delegates and 712 republican ones, are concentrated in the south
in south carolina, bush had the support of 49 percent of likely voters to dole's 26 percent, robertson's 14 percent and rep. jack kemp's 7 percent, the washington post poll indicated
kemp, battered by weak results in early contests, insisted he has a shot at a respectable showing in south carolina
i don't throw `hail mary' passes,'' said the former pro football player as he campaigned thursday in columbia, s.c
dole, who picked up the endorsement thursday of former u.n. ambassador jeane kirkpatrick, conceded he was running behind bush in south carolina, but pointed to bright spots that day _ a caucus in wyoming, and the election of 14 national gop delegates in kansas, dole's home state
all four republicans were campaigning in south carolina today
robertson bought half an hour of television time on stations around the state thursday night, saying he wanted to ``set the record straight'' about religious issues
the former television evangelist said he believes in the separation of church and state but added: ``the real fanatics in america today are those who try to tell us ... that we should tear down the crosses and the manger scenes at christmas time, that our children should be denied the right to pray in school and that traditional moral values are out of style.''
meanwhile, more polls today pointed to a strong southern lead for bush, while dukakis and jesse jackson dueled for support among democrats
a cbs-new york times survey gave bush a better than 2-1 lead over dole in 14 southern and border states. a survey by cable news network and usa today had similar findings
in the cbs-times poll, jackson led dukakis and tennessee sen. gore in the south. the cnn-usa today survey suggested dukakis and jackson were neck-in-neck in the region
dukakis, in texas, attacked gephardt's plan for mandatory retaliation against countries whose trade practices are judged unfair
there's always somebody who suggests that: throw up the walls, hunker down,'' the massachusetts governor said
gephardt, for his part, sought to turn the tables on dukakis, who has been running ads excoriating the missouri congressman for accepting campaign contributions from the political action committees of banks, defense contractors, utilities and other big businesses
i'll give back every penny of money that i've gotten from political action funds if he will return the money to all the people who have given him money who do business with or are licensed by the state of massachusetts,'' gephardt said
dukakis spokesman leslie dach said the campaign has taken no money from any corporate pacs or registered lobbyists in massachusetts
gephardt told reporters at a news conference at the baltimore-washington airport that he would unveil today ``a partial list of some of the interests that have given money to his campaign.''
he's got appointees of his own state government who are awarding contracts to many of the people who have given money to his campaign. is that a conflict of interest?'' he said
gephardt said his votes in the house have not been dictated by special interests
the missouri congressman, who had the house's worst attendance record for roll call votes last year, was absent thursday night as the house, by a 216-208 vote, rejected a package of $30 million in ``humanitarian'' aid for nicaragua's contras
when the house voted on contra aid last month, just prior to the iowa caucuses, gephardt delivered the weekly democratic radio address on the subject a few days beforehand and made himself a prominent figure in the house debate
geneticist sewall wright, known for his pioneering studies of genetic changes in evolving species, died of complications resulting from injuries sustained in a fall. he was 98
wright, a professor emeritus at the university of wisconsin-madison, remained active until his death thursday. he published his last scientific paper in the january 1988 issue of american naturalist
he broke his pelvis sunday when he slipped on an ice patch while walking near his apartment
wright advocated a mathematical theory of evolution; one of his important theories was that chance happenings can have a significant effect on modifying the gene pool
wright received 10 honorary degrees and was awarded the darwin medal, the national medal of science and, in 1984, the $100,000 balzan prize
he was one of the great thinkers in all of genetics and evolution,'' said james crow, a university of wisconsin colleague and longtime friend
he was responsible _ along with r.a. fisher and j.s.b. haldane _ for our modern theory of evolution, selection and mendelian inheritance.''
wright, who was born in melrose, mass., was a faculty member at the university of chicago for 30 years until 1954, when he retired from that school. he then accepted a position at uw-madison, where he has been emeritus professor of genetics since 1960
wright is survived by two sons and a daughter
british archaeologists discovered fragments of 16th century chinese porcelain at iron age ruins in southeastern zimbabwe, a newspaper reported friday
the porcelain was unearthed by a 12-member research team at great zimbabwe stone ruins of the 13th century tribal settlement from which modern zimbabwe draws its name. the find shows for the first time that the site was occupied in the 16th century, according to the newspaper, the herald
previous research indicated the ancestors of zimbabwe's majority shona tribe abandoned the stone-built settlement by the year 1450
the herald quoted archaeologists david collett and gwilyn hughes as saying the chinese porcelain was probably brought to the african interior by traders from arab trading posts along the east african coast
it proved that parts of the 1,720 acre ancient settlement, the onetime capital of a vast tribal empire, were still occupied after the year 1500, the expedition members said
an electrical problem struck a theater where the musical ``me and my girl'' had just gotten under way, and the audience of more than 1,000 had to be sent home when the show couldn't go on
the problem at the adelphi theater on thursday night developed only 20 minutes into the show, as star karl howman was midway through the title number, according to a statement from the theater
the unspecified problem couldn't be fixed immediately, the statement said
arrangements were being made to get the disappointed theatergoers into other performances of the show, which is in its fourth year playing to capacity crowds
me and my girl,'' about a cockney from london's tough east end who becomes an aristocrat, is a revival of the 1930s noel gay hit which launched the song ``the lambeth walk'' that became part of cockney folklore
hans raffert, who joined the white house kitchen staff 18 years ago, has been named to the top position of executive chef, it was announced today
he is the first to have been promoted to the position from within the ranks of the kitchen staff
raffert has been acting executive chef since january, when jon hill left after five months in the position
raffert, 60, was born in germany and is a naturalized american citizen. he was hired as an assistant chef in 1969 during the nixon administration
