the university of pennsylvania announced friday the 1{-year suspension of a fraternity that hired two black strippers to perform at a party
zeta beta tau ``will be permitted to return only if it meets stringent requirements for its reorganization,'' said penn spokesman william epstein
the exact terms have not been established, but penn president sheldon hackney said the first step is ``an immediate public apology.''
in a joint statement, hackney and provost michael aiken said the charges against the fraternity ``were very serious and deserved the significant sanctions that we are applying.''
behavior that dehumanizes any individual or group will not be tolerated at penn. every one of us has a responsibility to help build a community that values our diversity and the worth of each individual.''
members of zeta beta tau said that have been given until march 20 to move out. the 112-member, all-white fraternity will not be allowed to pledge new members and will not be allowed to reapply for recognition by the university until september 1989
zbt president zane brown, in a statement, complained the decision was unjust, but apologized for the rush party incident
the university charged the fraternity in february with engaging in lewdness, indecent exposure and hazing through activities that were ``indecent or shocking to moral or religious scruples.''
the charges stemmed from a rush party in september, when two black women stripped, performed sexually explicit acts and danced naked with a prospective freshman pledge before an audience that shouted racial epithets, according to the university
the fraternity had offered to pay a $2,500 fine to the campus women's center, make a public apology and attend educational programs on sexual harassment. but black student leaders said they wanted zbt expelled
the alabama beverage control board is making a mistake by planning to open a liquor store near a halfway house for recovering alcoholics, say officials of the halfway operation
the store, to open next month in downtown tuscaloosa, is one door away from the phoenix house, which houses up to 17 men who are trying to get off alcohol
i'm an alcoholic, and i went through the house eight years ago,'' said ted jones, now its acting director. ``looking back on it, during that first year, if something had been that convenient, i would have patronized it.''
most of the residents have been sober ``for only about six weeks when they get here. and like i said, that first year of sobriety is a volatile one,'' jones said
the abc board said that by the time it learned the phoenix house was so close to the store site it was too late because a 10-year lease had been signed for the store
had the board known about this previously, they never would have approved the location,'' said lucricia foster, the abc's alcohol awareness coordinator. ``but now we're entered into a legal contract with the builder, and we can't break it.''
she said an abc employee scouted the location when it was being considered
in this instance, he was just not aware that the halfway house was there. i know there are some signs marking it, but apparently they weren't very noticeable,'' miss foster said
that sounds like some of the excuses we come up with for drinking,'' said alice mclean stewart, chairwoman of the phoenix house board. ``it's raining, so i'm drinking, that kind of thing
more than 100 people applied for the $5-an-hour job of dogcatcher, a measure of the city's tough economic times, says the director of the animal shelter
the huntington cabell wayne animal shelter advertised for three days last month for someone who is in good health and has a high school diploma and driver's license. one hundred-twelve people applied
i think the number of responses we got is a clear indication of the need for jobs in this area,'' the shelter director, pat thomas, said thursday. ``i just wish i had 112 available jobs to offer these people.''
she said she hopes to fil the job next week
a young moose that had fallen through ice on the androscoggin river was destroyed friday after a community effort to save it failed
volunteers and game wardens used blankets overnight in an effort to keep the animal warm ``but she had suffered enough and couldn't even lift her head. so i made the decision to destroy it,'' said fish and game warden martin garabedian
when an animal gets in trouble, garabedian said, ``we usually let nature take its course, but there were so many people who wanted to help that we gave it a shot,'' adding that about 30 volunteers in the community of 300 people brought blankets
garabedian on thursday supervised the rescue of the 2-year-old, 600-pound moose
garabedian said he looped a noose around the moose, and ``it took seven or eight of us to pull her out.''
enhanced images of a 150 million-year-old, fist-sized dinosaur egg did not establish whether there's an embryo inside
columbia scientific inc., a maryland software company, enhanced cat-scan images of the egg, and the high-tech pictures revealed a small piece of shell inside the egg, in addition to a polliwog-like image of a possible embryo, said brent harker, a spokesman for brigham young university
the polliwog image looks very lifelike, much more so than on the unenhanced film,'' harker said
but it would require cracking the egg to be sure, and that ``would destroy it. we're not going to do that,'' he said
the egg will soon be displayed at the university's earth sciences museum
paleontologist wade miller announced last week the egg may contain the oldest dinosaur embryo ever found, dating from the jurassic period, which ended about 145 million years ago. the egg was unearthed last summer from a quarry in utah
i think the chances are good we have an embryo inside,'' miller said wednesday, after studying the enhanced images
a burglar who took a briefcase from a motel room probably didn't know it contained six artificial eyes, police said friday
police lt. harlan lyson said a salesman from milwaukee reported thursday night that someone had taken the briefcase. the eyes are valued at $5,000, lyson said. the burglar also stole four packs of cigarettes, some checks and six shirts, police said
sen. gordon humphrey claimed friday that there has been a sharp decline in the movement of u.s. aid to the afghanistan resistance fighters battling soviet troops
the new hampshire republican, one of capitol hill's strongest supporters of the afghan rebels, told a news conference: ``i want to know if this is negligence or a sell-out of the afghan resistance.''
last week, a top state department official denied a similar charge by members of the afghan resistance
we will not abandon the afghan resistance,'' said robert peck, deputy assistanct secretary of state. he said u.s. support would go ahead ``until that support is no longer needed.''
humphrey spoke a day after afghanistan and pakistan, which represents the guerrillas, agreed on the main elements of a u.n.-mediated peace accord that includes provisions for the withdrawal of some 115,000 soviet troops from afghanistan within nine months
that agreement ``makes it all the more imperative that we get some airlifts under way,'' humphrey said
humphrey said one of his staff members, michael pillsbury, spent four days in peshawar last week talking to afghan resistance leaders and came back with the conclusions that ``the flow of weapons has decreased markedly and suddenly.''
humphrey said pillsbury ``was shown warehouses which he and i had visited a year ago, which were bulging then, but which are all but empty now.''
the united states provides weapons such as stinger anti-aircraft missiles to the guerrillas, but the amount of military aid is classified. however, government sources have said congress increased the level to $630 million this year
rep. william h. gray, d-pa., asked the congressional general accounting office last month to investigate reports that more than $1 billion in covert cia aid to the afghan rebels has been diverted to corrupt pakistani officials or to the nicaraguan contra rebels, congressional sources told the associated press
however, the gao said it had no authority to subpoena material from the cia. update with contra statement. pick up 8th pvs, `</note>
contra rebels kidnapped 13 people in northern nicaragua, including an american volunteer for the witness for peace organization, its local director said today
edward griffin, the local director for the organization, identified the kidnapped american as richard boren, 29, of elkin, n.c
organization officials said boren was a witness for peace volunteer in the jinotega province of nicaragua and had been documenting contra activities, including human rights abuses
witness for peace opposes the contras and the reagan administration's policies in central america
griffin said boren was abducted tuesday in the mancotal area of jinotega province, about 120 miles north of managua. it is a zone where the rebels operate regularly in their six-year fight against the sandinista government
a defense ministry communique said two contras and four defenders of the resettlement village were killed in the attack. it said the contras' leader, identified only as wilmer, was one of the dead rebels
in washington, contra spokesman bosco matamoros denied that the group had been kidnapped, saying they were ``detained'' by rebel forces who suspected them of being foreign military collaborators with the sandinistas
matamoros said the 13 will be released as soon as a ``trustworthy'' nicaraguan can be found to return them to a safe location
generally, kidnapped civilians are held for a few days by the contras and then released
matamoros accused the sandinista government of sending foreigners, especially americans, to war zones. ``its purpose is to put them into a dangerous situation,'' he said
witness for peace said boren had been in nicaragua since november ``documenting contra human rights abuses and leading delegations to areas of conflict.''
the group's statement said boren was a self-employed construction worker and had worked for three years with the peace corps in ecuador before coming to nicaragua
last october, another witness for peace volunteer, paul fisher, was kidnapped and held for 14 days by the contras
in washington, witness for peace said it had contacted the u.s. state department and the u.s. embassy in managua. the state department had no immediate confirmation
dennis marker, the organization's washington director, said two witness for peace volunteers in jinotega were going today into the area where boren was taken to get more details on the incident
marker said witness for peace has no connection with the nicaraguan government and documents abuses by the sandinistas and contras, although ``our experience in the last four years is that the large majority of abuses are contra abuses.''
he said witness for peace has 32 full-time volunteers in nicaragua. the group also sponsors tours to rural nicaragua every two weeks for americans interested in the contra issue
president reagan plans to nominate donna f. tuttle as deputy secretary of commerce, succeeding clarence j. brown, the white house said friday
mrs. tuttle, 40, has been undersecretary for travel and tourism since 1983. before that she was active in a number of republican political campaigns in california
the president also plans to nominate w. allen moore as undersecretary of commerce for international trade administration, succeeding s. bruce smart, the white house said
moore, 43, has been chief of staff of the senate commerce committee since 1985 and before that was director of legislation for sen. john danforth, r-mo
in addition, the white house said, the president will nominate jan. w. mares to be assistant secretary of commerce for import administration, succeeding paul freedenberg
mares, 51, has been senior policy analyst for the white house office of policy development since 1985 and before that was assistant secretary of energy for international affairs and for policy
the white house also said reagan will nominate edward r. hamberger, 37, a washington lawyer, as assistant secretary of transportation for governmental affairs. he succeeds rebecca range, now director of the white house office of public liaison
gordon a. smith, 53, will be nominated as assistant secretary of defense for command, control, communications and intelligence, succeeding donald c. latham. smith has been deputy director of the strategic defense initiative organization at the pentagon since 1986
the madison square garden audience thursday night forgot the elephant man's bones, plastic surgery and other controversies and sat, mesmerized by michael jackson the performer
his high voice, with its controlled vibrato, was enthralling, especially on ``she's out of my life,'' which followed a duet of ``i just can't stop (loving you).'' video screens amplified jackson's stricken expression as the duet ended, with the female singer walking away
the girlish face of jackson, 29, often was shown large on the screens that flanked the stage. but he made no attempt to maintain a ``pretty'' expression, adopting a tearful, grieving pose several times at the end of songs
unlike his 1984 tour, in which jackson was by far the most graceful, dancing in a line with his brothers, this time he was among equals, surrounded most of the time by four men obviously well trained in dance
jackson's kicks and spins were so fast the eye only registered them after they were over. his pelvic thrusts, like different jackets he donned, conveyed little sexual suggestion and much childlike ``dressing up'' like grownups
the stagecraft looked simple but probably was far from it. there were no giant structures, just the smooth front half of the stage where jackson sang and danced and a lower-level back of the stage for four backup singers, seven musicians and modern music's mounds of equipment
much use was made of spotlights, sometimes on four sides of the singer, each filled with his silhouette, and laser beams stabbed the air. once, jackson ended a song and a circle of green lights surrounded his feet
there were tricks, in which he seemed magically to move from one place to another, as in 1984. in one, jackson he stood on a ladder and a cylinder drape dropped over him from above. his next appearance was on the other side of the stage, where a ``gangplank'' lifted up and swung him out over the audience
near the beginning of the evening, a man walked out on stage, shook hands with jackson and began to dance opposite him. briefly, it seemed part of the show, then a couple of large bodyguards walked the intruder offstage, fairly unobtrusively. no abrupt moves were made and the show's pacing wasn't dented
spontaneity was in short supply but the well-planned entertainment being offered was so fascinating that a viewer didn't mind
jackson's dancing and just trotting around stage is grace itself. a couple times he did a robot sequence, but obviously is playing down his ``signatures'' of one jeweled glove and the moon walk. he used both only once, during ``billie jean.''
jackson's solo tour began in september in japan. in america it began feb. 23 in kansas city, mo., and will run till mid-may. this first of three shows at madison square garden was a benefit for the united negro college fund, to whose president jackson presented a check for $600,000 on tuesday
israel blocked journalists from major trouble spots in the occupied territories friday in an effort to limit news reports of explosive palestinian protests following weekly moslem prayers
the media clampdown came after complaints from politicians, soldiers and settlers that the presence of journalists often inflamed arab protests in the west bank and gaza and caused more violence
despite the absence of cameras and notepads, palestinian revolts occurred friday in most of the west bank's major cities
friday also marked the first time since the start of arab unrest on dec. 8 that israeli soldiers had blocked major roads and turned back journalists from cities and refugee camps that typically are the sites of post-prayer protests
brig. gen. ephraim lapid, the army's spokesman in tel aviv, told the associated press the barricades did not represent an official change in military policy
there are a few localities that are closed according to existing policy which allows local commanders to shut an area based on operational needs,'' lapid said
the army declined to say how many cities and refugee camps were off-limits to journalists. but in the west bank, soldiers barred reporters from more than half a dozen major cities. only bethlehem, the traditional birthplace of jesus, was open
this is a closed military area,'' one soldier told an ap photographer outside nablus, 40 miles north of jerusalem. ``if you don't leave now, we will arrest you.''
an army jeep then followed the photographer's car for about three miles, apparently to make sure it was headed toward jerusalem
journalists were permitted to enter the gaza strip, but kept from the area around gaza city's main mosque and the major commercial street
the decision to bar journalists from the occupied territories drew mixed reviews from israelis
the right to see bang-bang is not protected by the first amendment,'' said zeev chafets, a former director of the government press office and a native of pontiac, mich
i would support closing off the west bank to the world press in a minute, but keeping it open to the israeli press,'' chafets said in an interview. ``the world press is only an asterisk here. to me, what's important is my press.''
but israel peleg, also a former director of the government press office, disagreed
it is better to let the media operate freely and without any obstacles than to be depicted in the world as a country that restricts journalists,'' peleg told the ap
israel's image may be immediately harmed by these pictures (of protests), but in the long run, the fact that these pictures can be circulated speaks for israel's democracy,'' he said
prime minister yitzhak shamir of the right-wing likud bloc twice this week publicly referred to the possibility of restricting media access and accused journalists of bias against israel
some soldiers serving in the west bank also have said journalists make their jobs more difficult. angry settlers in hebron attacked foreign photographers thursday, accusing them of impeding troops' efforts to arrest an arab who stabbed a 15-year-old settler
four soldiers were arrested after a cbs news crew photographed them beating palestinians with rocks last week
but foreign minister shimon peres of the left-leaning labor party has warned that barring media access to the occupied territories will simply spark rumors of atrocities that journalists will be unable to refute from on-the-scene reporting
other israeli officials have warned that denying media access could lead to unfavorable comparisons between israel and south africa, which the government has been sensitive about
in south africa, police can declare areas off-limits to journalists on the spot and demand that all reporters leave. in israel, local commanders also are permitted to declare an area closed if they deem the presence of journalists will make the army's job more difficult
in addition to limiting access, israel has military censors who, in an effort to prevent what they consider to be incitement, carefully control arabic-language newspapers based in jerusalem which circulate in the occupied territories
but the censorship controls on foreign press coverage of the occupied territories have been less stringent
robert slater, chairman of the foreign press association, said he was ``appalled but not surprised'' by israel's decision to bar journalists from large portions of the territories friday
from the prime minister's statements and comments by cabinet members, it appeared increasingly likely the government would do something to keep us away from this story,'' slater said in an interview. ``we have fought it for three months, and we will continue to fight it.''
the vast majority of americans view ties with europe as very important for the united states, but at the same time they recognize that trans-atlantic links have waned over the past 10 years, a poll commissioned by the european economic community shows
the gallup poll of ``national opinion leaders'' and the general public, published in the march edition of the eec magazine, ``europe,'' also shows the majority of respondents believe u.s. troops must be stationed in europe to prevent a soviet attack
of those polled, 86 percent said u.s. ties with europe ``matter a great deal,'' compared with 65 percent who answered the same way in a 1973 poll commissioned by the magazine
asked how today's ties compare with those of 10 years ago, 33 percent of the respondents said they were closer, but 53 percent said they were ``not as close.''
the united states should strengthen its links with europe, according to 53 percent of those polled. thirty-one percent favor the level of current ties and 11 percent support reduced ties with the continent
although about one-third of the respondents said west european countries engage in unfair trading practices, both the general public and national opinion leaders _ which the magazine defined as business and academic leaders and policy makers _ cited japan as an unfair trading partner more than twice as often as the countries of western europe
for example, 30 percent of the public said they view europe as an unfair partner, while 65 percent cited japan
respondents are more likely to know about the u.s. trade deficit with japan than about the one with western europe, according to the poll. the 1987 deficit with japan was $59.8 billion _ the largest chunk of the $171.2 billion overall deficit _ while the deficit with europe was $30.2 billion
of those polled, 47 percent said they ``mostly agree'' that europe is a good market for the united states, while 31 percent said they ``completely agree.''
those polled generally said they respect european achievements in arts, but gave higher credit to u.s. achievements in science, encouragement of individual creativity and equal opportunity
among the general public, 54 percent said the united states provides an excellent education for its citizens, while 21 percent said europe has a good educational system. but among the opinion leaders, 33 percent said the united states provides an excellent education and 34 percent credited europe with the same service
the poll, conducted late last year by telephone, surveyed 1,300 adult americans and 387 opinion leaders. the poll results had a 3 percentage point margin of error
a man arrested after a 17-day manhunt was acquitted in the execution-style murders of four suspected drug dealers but was returned to jail to await trial next month on charges of attempted murder of police officers
the jury returned its verdict against larry davis, 21, on thursday night after nine days of deliberations
davis' attorneys, including william m. kunstler, argued that he was framed and police tried to kill him because he knew about police corruption involving drugs in the south bronx
besides the trial stemming from the shootout with 27 police officers, davis also faces separate trials for two other murders
the nov. 19, 1986 shoot-out, in which six police officers were wounded but davis escaped unharmed from a bronx apartment, set off the manhunt. police said they had gone to the apartment to question davis about the deaths of the alleged drug dealers
the winter olympics won the february rating sweeps for abc, putting it into second place for the season and breaking nbc's 11-sweeps win streak
based on a.c. nielsen co. ratings for the 28-day sweeps period, abc won with an average prime-time rating of 17.3 and a 27 share, thanks to the average 19.3 rating for the olympics, which dominated 59 percent of prime time
nbc, which won each of the 12 nights that didn't include olympics coverage, came in second with a 15.9 and 25. cbs was third with 13.8 and 21
the rating is a percentage of the nation's 88.6 million households with televisions. the share is a percentage of sets in use
unless cbs beats abc by 1.5 rating points each week for the remaining seven weeks of the television season, it will end the season in third place for the first time ever
february is one of four sweeps months each year when rating companies measure local station audiences for use in negotiating advertising rates. to help affiliates, the networks load their schedules with special programming
nbc and cbs insist the february sweeps will have less impact on local advertising rates than other sweeps, because stations can refuse to negotiate based on ratings for the unusual olympics programming
nevertheless, the win was a boost for abc, which hasn't won a sweeps since 1984. the games were also a boost for the networks in general, since the three-network share of the viewing audience rose to 75 percent from 71 percent
the olympics also apparently helped abc's ``world news tonight'' take the top spot in the network evening news race for three weeks. but the games didn't help ``good morning america'' out of the no. 2 position it has occupied behind nbc's ``today'' show for 15 weeks in a row
of the four miniseries that aired during the month, ``elvis and me'' on abc was the highest-rated, with a 24.4. ``windmills of the gods'' on cbs was second with an 18.2 and cbs' ``bluegrass'' was third with 18.0. nbc's ``noble house'' was last with a 16.3. all were two-part, four-hour miniseries, except ``noble house,'' which aired eight hours over four nights
the top-rated specials of the months, not counting the olympics, were: ``super bloopers'' on nbc with a rating of 21.3; the special prime-time ``late night with david letterman'' on nbc, with a rating of 19.3; the premiere of the new nbc series ``day by day'' with 18.6; the ``miss usa'' pageant on cbs with a 16.2; and ``the wizard of oz'' on cbs with a 15.3
the top-rated movies of the sweeps were: ``hostage'' on cbs with a 19.4; ``perry mason'' on nbc with 17.4; ``moving target'' on nbc with 17.2; ``police academy ii'' on nbc with 16.7; and ``return of desperado'' on nbc with 16.0
a high-ranking tibetan official confirmed friday that a buddhist monk jailed for advocating tibetan independence had died in prison, the official xinhua news agency said
xinhua said gyamco, vice-chairman of the tibetan autonomous region government, told foreign reporters in tibet that lobsang wangchuk died last year of lung cancer while serving an 18-year term
tibetan exile groups in india said last year that wangchuk died nov. 4 of injuries suffered in a beating after he refused to admit he was wrong to support tibetan independence. he was 74
at the time, chinese authorities in beijing dismissed the report of wangchuk's death as ``sheer fabrication.''
xinhua's report did not say why authorities initially denied the report. however, his death came during a time of great tension in the remote himalayan region. one month earlier, three anti-chinese demonstrations were led by buddhist monks and at least 14 people were killed
in the people's republic of china citizens can freely air their views,'' the report quoted gyamco as saying. ``but advocating independence for any part of the nation is a crime.''
wangchuk was first arrested in 1959, nine years after chinese troops entered tibet, for taking part in an uprising against chinese rule. tibet's god-king, the dalai lama, fled to india during that uprising
according to exiled tibetan groups, wangchuk was detained without trial until 1962, when he was sentenced to a 10-year term. he was released at the end of his term but was arrested again in 1981
xinhua said wangchuk ``renewed his splittist activities by distributing leaflets advocating the independence of tibet'' and was sentenced to three years in jail. the term was extended to 18 years because he refused to change his views, the report said
splittist is a term coined by the chinese to refer to individuals who advocate independence for regions in china
xinhua also quoted gyamco as saying last year's protests ``had no impact at all'' on china's policy of allowing religious freedom in tibet
on the contrary, it (the policy) will be more effectively implemented,'' it quoted him as saying
tibetans traditionally are deeply religious, and before the chinese red army entered in 1950 were governed by a theocracy headed by the dalai lama and the buddhist monasteries
the chinese smashed the temporal power of the monasteries and for many years banned public worship. thousands of monasteries were destroyed and their monks forced to marry during the 1966-76 cultural revolution
since then, public worship has been restored and some monasteries have been rebuilt. however, most monks and many lay tibetans remain hostile to chinese rule
an eight-day great prayer festival that ended this week in lhasa, tibet's capital, was boycotted by many monks because of the heavy chinese police presence. attendance by pilgrims also was sharply down, according to tibetan sources and westerners who observed the festival this year and in the past
the vast majority of americans view ties with europe as very important for the united states, but at the same time they recognize that trans-atlantic links have waned over the past 10 years, a poll commissioned by the european economic community shows
the gallup poll of ``national opinion leaders'' and the general public, published in the march edition of the eec magazine, ``europe,'' also shows the majority of respondents believe u.s. troops must be stationed in europe to prevent a soviet attack
