former defense secretary caspar w. weinberger will serve as president reagan's official representative in australia this month during the country's bicentennial celebration, it was announced friday
he will be accompanied by his wife jane, visiting canberra, melbourne, brisbane and sydney from march 16-22
the weinbergers were married in australia in 1942 while both were serving in the u.s. army
a white house statement said the couple will participate in ``a wide range of activities underscoring u.s. admiration and appreciation of australia at this historic time.''
while in australia, weinberger will meet with prime minister bob hawke and other government leaders
in connection with the bicentennial, the united states has made a $5 million gift to the australian national maritime museum. in addition, the u.s. coast guard's sailing vessel, eagle, will participate in the parade of tall ships in sydney harbor on australia day. a u.s. pavilion will operate at brisbane's world expo '88, which will run from april through october
six hundred florida national guard troops will go to panama for a two-week ``total warrior'' training exercise despite riots and a general strike there, officials announced
the political turmoil has no effect on the training there,'' florida guard spokesman maj. ken forrester said thursday. ``this has been scheduled a year in advance, and we see no reason to change it.''
u.s. army maj. gen. bernard loeffke in panama sent assurances wednesday that troops training in the canal zone would be safe, said forrester from guard headquarters in st. augustine
and with 10,000 regular army troops down there, i can't see us doing anything but the training we have scheduled,'' said forrester
troops from the 3rd battalion, 124th infantry based in panama city, fla., won't be allowed off u.s. bases during the jungle training, he said
there's been some concern, but i haven't had any hysterical moms saying their son or husband isn't going,'' lt. charles boss said
during total warrior _ 12 days of mock raids and ambushes _ troops would have little time for sightseeing, he said
we're going to fly into howard air force base and go directly into the jungle,'' boss said. ``after 12 days ... they'll only be interested in a shower, a cold beer and getting back to sleep.''
two florida guard battalions have trained in panama for each of the last three years, forrester said
the battalion troops are to leave tyndall air force base near this gulf coast resort area march 12 and return march 27
the unit will be the first u.s. troops sent to panama for training since then-president eric arturo delvalle's failed feb. 25 effort to oust strongman gen. manuel noriega. panama's de facto leader was indicted last month by tampa and miami federal grand juries which accused noriega of involvement with drug dealing
james b. odom, a veteran engineer with the national aeronautics and space administration, has been appointed head of the agency's most ambitious program in the next decade: putting a manned space station into earth orbit
odom, currently director of science and engineering at the marshall space flight center in huntsville, ala., will succeed andrew j. stofan, who is leaving nasa on april 1
odom headed nasa's space telescope project, was actively involved in developing earth satellites and unmanned space probes and guided the external tank project for the first space shuttle
the commerce department celebrated its 75th anniversary friday as commerce secretary c. william verity cut a 10-foot-by-6-foot cake and president reagan issued a special proclamation
this moment is an historic snapshot in time of the development of our government which goes back over 200 years,'' verity said at a celebration attended by an estimated 1,600 agency employees
reagan issued a proclamation declaring friday as department of commerce day
the employees of the department of commerce have always reflected the finest traditions of public service. that was surely true of the department's late secretary, malcolm baldrige, and our present secretary, c. william verity jr,'' reagan said in the proclamation
verity, who became commerce secretary in 1987 after the death of baldrige in a freak horse-riding accident, was joined by one of his secretaries, willa petty, in leading the audience in a rendition of ``happy birthday'' before cutting the cake, a replica of the commerce department headquarters
ms. petty was a stand-in for singer pearl bailey, who had been scheduled to preside over the proceedings but who canceled at the last minute
six men have been indicted on 23 felony counts of fraud and conspiracy, alleging they stole timber worth ``hundreds of thousands of dollars'' from the olympic national forest
among those indicted late thursday are the former owner and crew chief of one of the most powerful independent logging operations on the olympic peninsula, glenn t. anderson inc
after a four-year investigation, the government accused the six of stealing forest service timber from the national forest, conspiracy to steal, filing false statements and conflict of interest
federal court documents filed last october allege the thefts to be in the range of ``hundreds of thousands of dollars.''
court files accuse five of the men of devising scams to cheat the forest service of revenue on logs harvested off public land. the alleged scams included forging log brands, sawing up unscaled logs, and recycling log-truck load identifier tickets, the documents say
the documents also say one defendant, gregory b. maurer, 43, of aberdeen, former u.s. forest service timber sale administrator on the olympic forest's quinault ranger district, allegedly looked the other way to allow the scams
the indictment also says maurer ran a secret forest cleanup company that catered to the logging operators he was supposed to regulate as timber sale administrator
the charges carry maximum penalties of up to 10 years in prison and fines of up to $250,000
police were summoned to quell a revolt by angry commuters who vandalized and jammed the doors of a delayed subway train, and refused to get off in protest, authorities said friday
it was the second such mutiny in the underground this week
we got the message the first time. this is only making things worse,'' said david morris, a spokesman for london regional transport, which operates the massive system
the spectacle of rebellion by london's usually reserved and mild-mannered commuters is making headline news in the capital, and a member of parliament says he will raise the issue in the house of commons
morris said the latest incident was ``pretty close to an out-of-control act of vandalism,'' while one of the passengers involved said commuters had grown fed up with delays and shoddy stations
the first whiff of trouble came tuesday night when, in what london regional transport called unprecedented behavior, passengers at finchley central station on the northern line refused a request to get off the train prematurely and forced the driver to take them to their destination
the second incident occurred at the same station. in both cases, the trains had been delayed by track defects and passengers were told to get off and catch the next train
the first incident ended in peaceful victory for the commuters without police intervention. the second incident, by all accounts, was nastier
passengers ripped off pieces of the train and used them to jam the doors,'' said morris. ``apparently there was much jubilation. undoubtedly it was inspired by what happened on tuesday. the staff called the transport police who ordered the passengers off the train, and they obeyed.''
london's evening standard newspaper quoted passenger faz razeen, 34, a leader of the revolt, as saying: ``people were really worked up and annoyed.'' some had waited more than half an hour for their train, he said
morris conceded that half-hour waits were not unusual. ``we are trying to do something. but if people don't use their common sense the whole line will come to a stop. whatever sympathy they got over the first incident will soon be lost.''
morris insisted that in both incidents, the passengers behaved selfishly because by trying to force their trains to take them to their destinations, they made passengers at other stations wait longer
but the standard said this response ``betrays an arrogance which ought to be replaced at once by better management on the misery line.''
john marshall, a conservative party lawmaker and northern line commuter, said the northern line ``is the nearest thing to hell on earth,'' and promised to raise the matter in parliament
replied morris: ``when you're running 460 trains a day for 2.5 million passengers, something always goes wrong.'' he said thursday's delays were caused by a beer can that was thrown onto the line, jamming a track mechanism
meanwhile, the standard tracked down the man said to have started tuesday night's rebellion by quietly declaring his refusal to get off the train
described by fellow-passengers as a mild-mannered, well-dressed man, he turned out to be 49-year-old civil servant barry blain
i am not a natural rebel,'' the standard quoted him as saying, ``but like a lot of my fellow commuters i am fed up with our treatment on the northern line.''
thirty-one people were killed in ethnic rioting in the azerbaijani city of sumgait, the state-run news agency tass reported today
it was the first time the official media reported deaths in ethnic violence between azeris and armenians in the two southern soviet republics. dissident sources had reported that as many as 20 people died in the sumgait riots
the rioting erupted sunday in the industrial city 19 miles northwest of the azerbaijani capital of baku. government spokesmen had previously acknowledged people were killed in the rioting, but refused to say how many. a television worker in baku had said one or two people were killed
the tass dispatch blamed the sunday killings on ``hooligan elements provoked by disorder.''
trouble between the azeris, who are predominantly shiite moslems, and armenians, who are christian, began early last month with a dispute over nagorno-karabakh, a region in azerbaijan just north of iran and east of turkey. more than three-quarters of the population is armenian, but it was made part of azerbaijan in 1923
armenians are demanding that the region be made part of the republic of armenia. azeris opposed the move and violence has ensued
earlier today, an armenian nationalist said his sister and at least two other people were killed in ethnic violence in armenia
unstable, immature people, falling under the influence of false rumors about the events in nagorno-karabakh and armenia, involved themselves in lawsless actions,'' tass said. ``criminal elements took part in violent activities and looting. from their hands, 31 people perished.''
an english version of the tass story said the dead included ``members of various nationalities, old men and women.''
on thursday gennady i. gerasimov, chief spokesman for the soviet foreign ministry in moscow, gave the first official confirmation of deaths during the riots in azerbaijan, but would not say how many people were killed
on tuesday, he said he could not confirm reports from armenian activists that up to 20 people were killed in sumgait, in azerbaijan. but he added, ``there was hooliganism, and there can be deaths in such cases.''
the first official hint of deaths in the ethnic unrest came feb. 24, when non-voting politburo member vladimir i. dolgikh said on armenian television that ``in nagorno-karabakh, the matter has gone so far as confrontations between armenians and azerbaijanis, and there have been casualties.''
street rallies began feb. 13 in nagorno-karabakh and later spread to yerevan, the capital of armenia, where dissidents said more than 1 million people demonstrated. on feb. 19 rioting spread to sumgait
mosef gorgisyan telephoned the associated press in moscow to say his sister, avetik gorgisyan, 32, was stabbed today and two other people were shot in their homes in the armenian city of kirovakan. he said the three were killed by azeris
he said six people, all ethnic azeris, were arrested in the killings
gerasimov said he could neither confirm nor deny the report because he had no information about renewed violence in the region
gorgisyan, 26, is a member of an unsanctioned armenian organization called the alliance for national self-determination
gorgisyan said his sister was killed today, but the telephone was cut off before he could say when the two shootings reportedly occurred. he said demonstrations had been held in kirovakan earlier
he said he saw the aftermath of three slayings in kirovakan. he said he had heard 13 other people were killed but could not confirm those reports
gorgisyan said his grandmother and other relatives were in his sister's house when the stabbing occurred
an official at the ministry of internal affairs in yerevan said, ``there were no deaths anywhere in the republic.'' the ministry includes the police forces of the region. the official refused to give his name
an official answering the telephone at police headquarters in kirovakan refused comment. ``i am not obligated to say anything to foreigners about what happens here,'' said the official, who declined to give his name
kirovakan is a city of 137,000 people about 35 miles north of the armenian capital of yerevan. western reporters have not been allowed to travel to the region
since mikhail s. gorbachev became communist party chief, the most deaths previously reported in ethnic unrest occurred in alma ata, the capital of the central asian republic of kazakhstan
up to 3,000 people rioted in that city dec. 17-18, 1986, to protest the appointment of a russian to replace an ethnic kazakh as local party chief. soviet media reported that two people were killed, 200 injured and dozens arrested
a settlement aimed at ending the war in afghanistan appeared to be taking shape friday, and the latest round of peace talks were recessed while pakistan decided if it was willing to deal with the soviet-backed afghan government
still open, too, was the question of whether afghanistan's moslem resistance groups would drop their fierce opposition to future power-sharing with afghan president najib
after a short session of the u.n.-sponsored talks friday, pakistan's chief negotiator, acting foreign minister zain noorani, flew back to islamabad for a rare meeting between the government and leaders of the political opposition
pakistan represents the afghan guerrillas in the negotiations
the meeting in pakistan was convened by prime minister mohammad khan junejo to try to reach a consensus on whether a settlement should be signed with najib's government
it was the first time the government sought such direct contact with the opposition since president mohammad zia-ul haq seized power in a 1977 coup
before leaving, noorani reaffirmed pakistan's position that a settlement must include formation of a transitional government replacing najib's
pakistan does not recognize najib's government and has said it must be replaced if 5 million afghan refugees living in pakistan and iran are to return safely home
most of pakistan's opposition parties have urged the government to sign an accord clearing the way for the withdrawal of soviet troops from afghanistan, then worry about a political settlement later
diego cordovez, the u.n. mediator who has been the go-between in the nearly 6-year-old talks, told reporters that thursday's agreement on a nine-month timetable for the withdrawal of the soviet troops represented a ``significant step'' toward a final political settlement
he stopped short of saying it was complete but exuded confidence that remaining issues would be resolved, noting that all sides showed ``determination and political will.''
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev has said that if an accord is signed by march 15, the estimated 115,000 red army troops would begin leaving afghanistan in mid-may. the soviets intervened in 1979
afghanistan has accused pakistan of ``undermining'' peace prospects by linking the withdrawal to formation of a transitional government
the head of the afghan delegation, foreign minister abdul wakil, told a u.n. human rights commission on friday that his nation's concept of a multiparty government of ``national reconciliation'' has the ``vigorous support of our people.''
opponents say that concept is designed to cement the leading role of najib's governing people's democratic party of afghanistan
wakil said ``political hysteria'' made the opposition reject all attempts by kabul to launch a ``constructive dialogue.'' instead, he said, ``extremist bands'' relying on mounting supplies of american and british arms had stepped up their ``destructive and terrorist deeds.''
the united states has been largely non-committal on the issue and some sources close to the talks said there is a growing feeling in pakistan that washington's prime interest is in sealing a deal before the moscow summit
cordovez indicated friday he is increasingly confident that there will be an eventual compromise on the future shape of the kabul government
he said he was in ``close contact'' with superpower representatives on the problem and was confident the afghan resistance will ``change its attitude once a settlement is signed.''
president hussain muhammad ershad's jatiya party gained a lopsided majority in parliament in an election that brought new calls for protests friday from opposition leaders
an opposition coalition of 21 parties scheduled rallies for a ``day of protest'' saturday and denounced thursday's balloting, which they boycotted
at least 13 people were reported killed and more than 300 were injured in election violence, and reporters who visited polling places found evidence of a low voter turnout and widespread vote rigging
with results announced friday for 218 of the 299 parliament seats up for grabs, the president's party had won 194
a coalition of 73 small factions known as the combined opposition parties won 12, two other small parties had one each, and independents won seven. voting was canceled in one district where a candidate was slain. the other 30 seats in the 330-seat parliament are reserved for women, who will be chosen later
in the 1986 elections, jatiya won 157 seats, but its majority rose to 210 after wheeling and dealing with independents and the addition of the 30 seats for women. those traditionally go to the governing party
the vote did not end the stalemate between ershad and his leading opponents, sheik hasina of the awami league and khaleda zia of the bangladesh nationalist party
the women vowed to persist in their campaign against ershad, and ms. hasina declared, ``we will topple this corrupt government.'' they have been organizing anti-ershad demonstrations and strikes since nov. 10
bangladesh journalists decided to stop work for a night to protest government restrictions on the press that were imposed under a national state of emergency in november
reazuddin ahmed, president of the bangladesh federal union of journalists representing about 1,500 journalists across the country, said government officials had been phoning newspapers each night and telling them not to publish news of anti-government activities
he said they were told not to publish news of a low voter turnout or election violence
most newspapers seemed to have kept low profile about reporting violence or election fraud
the action will result in non-publication of about 15 dhaka-based dailies and half a dozen more outside dhaka on saturday. two national news agencies will also be affected
ershad said he expected the new parliament to serve out its full five-year term
ershad dissolved the parliament last december, 3{ years early, in a move to compromise with the opposition. the opposition declared a boycott of the election
the former lieutenant took power in a bloodless coup in 1982 and was elected president in 1986. congress</head>
the senate, trying to avoid another iran-contra affair, on friday voted down an effort to let the white house withhold details about covert operations from congress
the 65-23 vote came as the chamber worked on a bill which would require that congress be notified about all covert actions within 48 hours after they start
the vote killed an amendment proposed by sen. james mcclure, r-idaho, which would have allowed a president simply to tell congress that a covert action had started, but withhold details until later
mcclure called his proposal ``a compromise'' which he said ``gives the president some flexibility'' about when to tell congress
but sen. william cohen, r-maine, chief author of the bill, said mcclure's amendment ``is not a compromise; it's a capitulation. ... this lets the president play `i've got a secret' but not tell.''
the bill's future is unclear. the reagan administration strongly opposes the measure as an unconstitutional limit on a president's ability to conduct foreign policy. a similar measure is pending in the house, but has not yet reached the floor
cohen is vice-chairman of the intelligence committee and was also a member of the iran-contra committee which investigated the sale of u.s. arms to iran and the diversion of some of the profits to the contra guerrillas. president reagan withheld notice from congress for 10 months about the iranian arms sales
the bill overhauls procedures for notifying congress about intelligence actions. the chief provision requires that notification be sent to capitol hill within 48 hours of the time a covert operation begins, replacing the current requirement that congress be given ``timely notification,'' which is not defined
cohen said the bill ``cannot guarantee that future abuses such as iran-contra will not occur, but it will certainly minimize them.''
sen. orrin hatch, r-utah, an opponent, called the bill ``an overreaction to the iran-contra situation.'' he termed it ``unnecessary, unwise, and unconstitutional.''
but sen. lloyd bentsen, d-texas, said, ``the requirement for this legislation has certainly been demonstrated.''
there is no question but that not being advised for over 10 months (about the iran arms sale) was not a timely notification,'' said bentsen. ``what this legislation does is close that loophole.''
sen. patrick leahy, d-vt., said the bill contained ``small, but necessary steps,'' although he warned ``we can write every law conceivable, but unless the people follow them, they are no good.''
sen. john chafee, r-r.i., said, ``many people believe that if we had this requirement in place, iran-contra would never have happened, but that's not so.''
cohen agreed, noting that ``there's no piece of legislation we can enact that would prevent a president from exercising poor judgement.''
pat robertson was accused in court papers friday of abusing the judicial process by trying to dismiss the $35 million libel suit he filed against an ex-congressman who questioned his war record
lawyers for former rep. paul n. mccloskey jr., r-calif., formally opposed robertson's motion to dismiss the case that is set to go to trial next tuesday, the campaign season's super tuesday when the former television evangelist is hoping make a good showing in southern states
robertson, though still denying mccloskey's allegations, says he felt he had to abandon his libel suit because he couldn't take part in the trial and effectively campaign at the same time
however, mccloskey's lawyers said in court papers friday that robertson ``initiated this action for political purposes and has conducted this litigation in bad faith, putting the defendant to substantial, unnecessary and improper expense and public denigration.''
robertson's ``last-minute tactics to avoid trial are just the latest, most flagrant example of his abuse of the judicial process and his attempt to treat this forum as a court of convenience,'' the lawyers said in papers filed with u.s. district judge joyce hens green
the judge must now make a decision on robertson's motion to dismiss the lawsuit
the libel suit against mccloskey was filed in 1986 following publication of mccloskey's charges that robertson used the help of his father, the late sen. a. willis robertson, d-va., to avoid combat during the korean war
the former television evangelist ``agonized over the decision to seek dismissal'' but concluded that the trial date _ which the judge refused to postpone _ presented ``a hobson's choice of either abandoning his campaign during a critical period or forgoing the opportunity for personal vindication,'' robertson's lawyers said thursday in their motion to dismiss the case
mccloskey's lawyers asked the judge to order the trial to proceed to ensure ``the right of mr. mccloskey to have the same vindication of his integrity that mr. robertson apparently sought.''
if the judge decides to dismiss the lawsuit, mccloskey's lawyers asked that she order robertson to pay the former congressman's court costs and legal fees, which they estimated to be about $400,000
they also asked the judge to preserve mccloskey's legal rights to initiate court action against robertson and his attorneys involving ``possible claims'' of malicious prosecution
to allow plaintiff to initiate an action which may require the expenditure of significant legal fees by or on behalf of mr. mccloskey in defending his first amendment right of self-expression, on the eve of the trial to both denounce the defendant in the most outrageous fashion and then request that the court dismiss the case seems to be the very sort of manipulation of the judicial process which this court should resist,'' attorneys george lehner, roger spaeder and leslie blackmon said in their brief
mccloskey's motion also asked the judge to issue an order preventing ``future legal actions against mr. mccloskey based on any past or future repetition of the statements at issue in this action.''
while a dismissal of the case would prevent robertson from suing mccloskey over the statements he made in 1986, the former congressman ``is concerned that mr. robertson may attempt to silence his free speech again, with yet another lawsuit based on repetitions of the alleged libels,'' the brief said
if tammy and michelle walsh were stumped by the pythagorean theorem or baffled by ohm's law when they were doing their school assignments, help was usually just a call away, by ship's radio
while sailing in the bahamas, an engineer from nassau was there with advice on algebra. a vacationing english professor from the university of california at berkeley once offered essay-writing tips
the sisters now are freshmen at babson college, having completed elementary, junior high and high school while sailing on the atlantic with their parents and two cats on a 45-foot boat called high hopes
they studied french in florida and geometry in georgetown via a chicago correspondence school that once a year mailed books and exams. they completed the tests at their own pace and returned them for grading
i think we got a better education,'' michelle, 21, who took some time off before going to college, said in an interview at the 1,550-student undergraduate business school outside boston. ``you learned much more because you read everything. you had a lot of responsibility. we ended up more well-rounded and ready to take on the world.''
in 1971, when the sisters were pre-schoolers, mickey and joyce walsh of oakdale, n.y., on long island's south shore, decided to take the kids sailing. mickey gave up his job working on a clam dredge and the family left for puerto rico, where they lived for a year
they returned to puerto rico in 1974 for another year, and michelle started in correspondence school. the family sold their house in 1979 and decided to move to the boat
they always liked sailing and wanted to live on a boat and travel,'' tammy, 18, said of her parents. ``they were going to wait until we grew up.''
instead, the family went to sea and the girls learned to discipline themselves in their studies. their parents left them on their own almost from the start, they said
they felt we were mature and responsible enough to do it and by doing that we became more mature and responsible,'' said tammy
the walshes spent summers on new york's fire island, then usually left in october and sailed down the atlantic coast. the trip offered maximum study time, often up to eight hours a day
then we'd get to the beach and not (study) for months,'' michelle said
the family spent most winters anchored off georgetown in the exuma islands in the bahamas. books often weren't a priority; michelle needed three years to complete algebra
michelle and tammy admit that while they disciplined themselves enough to finish the required texts, if the sun was shining and the water glistening, boardsailing won out over shakespeare
we didn't have set hours,'' said michelle. ``if it was a beautiful day outside i wasn't going to sit and read.''
mary mckeown, principal of the chicago-based american school of correspondence, said michelle received her high school equivalency diploma in 1984 and tammy in 1987. they had to take at least 16 credits under illinois requirements
she said the school is accredited by the north central association of colleges and schools and serves a variety of students, from young people living abroad to adults seeking to finish high school. tuition and books cost $679 for four years
science and math courses most frequently sent the sisters searching for help on the radio or high seas
people living on boats are very friendly,'' tammy said. ``you don't think anything about rowing up to someone's boat, knocking on the hull and saying `hi.'''
the walshes say they don't regret missing the typical high school scene. and they offer their scholastic aptitude test scores in defense of their academic preparation: 1,280 for tammy and 1,080 for michelle, compared to the 1987 national average of 906 out of a possible 1,600
they gave you a book and you had to read the whole book, no matter what,'' tammy said. ``i think that's a big difference. i know people who say they never finished a textbook.''
the house interior committee is investigating possible government corruption in the u.s. trust territory of palau, including allegations that senior palau officials may be involved in heroin smuggling
the probe was disclosed this week by chairman morris udall, d-ariz., and del. ron de lugo, d-virgin islands, chairman of the interior subcommittee on insular and international affairs
the lawmakers, in statements not disputed by palauan or u.s. officials, quoted the u.s. drug enforcement administration as saying that the pacific islands ``are being used to transship heroin from southeast asia to the u.s.''
in a letter sent wednesday to rep. dante fascell, d-fla., chairman of the house foreign affairs committee, udall and de lugo said ``several senior palauan government officials have been identified to us as being connected to this drug trade.''
the letter cited no basis for the accusation against the unidentified officials. jeff farrow, staff director for de lugo's subcommittee, said: ``it's coming from our investigation. that's all we can say at this point.''
haruo willter, palau's acting washington representative, acknowledged that his country has a drug problem, ``the same as the united states.'' as for the involvement of senior officials, he said: ``these allegations are made by individuals. i have seen no specific accusations with names.''
howard hills, counsel for interagency affairs at the state department, said: ``we've been aware of allegations of drug trafficking _ including allegations of officials being involved _ for years, and we don't understand why the interior committee is treating them as new.''
the letter said the committee investigation also involves allegations of corruption and bribery among high-ranking palau officials, misappropriation of federal and local funds and violence against palauans opposed to a long-term compact linking the united states and palau
palau and the reagan administration are pressing congress to approve a resolution to implement the compact, leading to the end of a u.n.-sanctioned trusteeship the united states has exercised over palau for 40 years. palau is the world's last united nations trust territory
under the arrangement, the united states would provide economic assistance and military protection for palau, which the pentagon sees as a backup location in case this country loses its military bases in the philippines
the interior committee has made no move toward voting on the resolution, which was endorsed thursday by two subcommittees of the foreign affairs committee. there was no mention of the drug allegations before their votes
about 14,000 people live on the eight permanently inhabited islands of palau, which comprises more than 200 islands in the caroline chain. most of the inhabitants live in koror, the capital, some 4,450 miles southwest of honolulu and 720 miles south of guam
in a letter last october to de lugo, dea administrator john lawn said ``it appears that palau's primary involvement in international drug trafficking is as a transshipment point for southeast asian heroin being smuggled to the united states.''
lawn said ``marijuana is grown freely throughout'' palau and that there may be more than 400 heroin addicts in palau _ far higher than the percentage of addicts in the united states
hills said palau, with help requested from the dea and interior and state departments, is trying to combat the problem. he said that 25 marijuana and heroin suspects were arrested in ``a major bust'' tuesday in palau
about the accusation that senior officials could be involved with heroin smuggling, hills said, ``the issue of who's involved is not going to be commented on because it's under investigation by the government of palau.''
he said congress should move to sever the trusteeship because palauan independence and increased u.s. aid would give the islands' government more resources to combat its problems
udall and de lugo also cited last summer's violence in palau surrounding a plebiscite in which a majority of palauans voted to change their constitution's strong prohibition on nuclear weapons in their country
palauan dissidents have questioned the legality of the plebiscite. a lawsuit challenging the constitutionality of the vote was withdrawn because of government-fostered intimidation, dissidents have told congress
udall and de lugo said they won't act on the resolution until palau's judiciary rules on the plebiscite's legality or the dissidents say they won't renew the lawsuit
the resolution approved by the foreign affairs subcommittees says the reagan administration can implement the compact with palau unless a legal challenge to the plebiscite is pending
agriculture officials from arizona, texas and louisiana came to see for themselves whether florida was doing all it can to prevent citrus canker from traveling in fruit shipments to their states
we are trying to assess the level of confidence we can place on the procedures being taken so that we can determine what inspection methods we need in our state,'' said arizona's director of agriculture and horticulture, ivan j. shields
shields joined florida agriculture commissioner doyle conner and regulatory and technical officials from the two other states in a tour of florida citrus nurseries, groves and packinghouse facilities in the indian river and interior areas of florida's citrus belt
florida fruit presents no threat to their citrus industries, and we want to assure them of that,'' conner said in orlando prior to their departure in three small airplanes to fort pierce, winter haven, frostproof and lake wales
conner invited the representatives from the three states and california as a partial answer to embargoes on florida fresh fruit shipments imposed by texas and louisiana shortly after the u.s. department of agriculture last month lifted a 3-year-old ban on florida shipments to other citrus-growing areas
florida citrus mutual, an organization representing 12,000 growers, and tuxedo fruit co. of fort pierce went into federal court and obtained a temporary injunction against the texas embargo. the first florida truckloads of fruit were expected to reach texas this weekend
conner said florida also was prepared to challenge a louisiana ban from the southern part of the state, where about 1,000 acres of fruit is grown
california, which did not send a representative to florida on friday, and arizona have not interfered with florida shipments
the usda ban was lifted after a joint state-federal scientific task force determined that there was little threat to other citrus-growing states by the florida nursery strain of the tree and fruit disease, which resulted in the voluntary destruction of 20 million young trees in the last three years
john w. impson, state entomologist for the louisiana department of agriculture, said there was little worry about florida's procedures. ``our concern is monitoring, in our state in particular,'' by the usda, he said
florida, which is the largest domestic producer, has almost 600,000 acres of commercial citrus. most of it is processed into juice, but its fresh-fruit exports to other citrus-growing states constitute an annual market of about $25 million
california has traditionally been the second-largest producer, with texas third, followed by arizona, louisiana and hawaii. a 1983 freeze in texas dropped its annual production to about 115,000 tons on 22,000 acres of groves, however. arizona has 35,500 acres yielding about 485,000 tons
citrus canker threatens commercial citrus groves because it is easily spread. it mars leaves and fruit, making it unmarketable, and can damage stems and twigs, causing a general decline of trees. the fruit is edible, however
florida's juice-processing industry has not been affected because, except for the small gulf coast region, the disease has not spread into commercial groves
canker does not affect humans
the school board has prohibited students from carrying electronic telephone beepers, following administrators' complaints that students were using them to arrange drug deals
when the ban vote thursday takes effect, march 14, students found carrying a beeper face suspension
at the high school and middle school level, if a child is in possession of an operational beeper, they are usually dealing drugs,'' said arthur pierce, principal of francis m. wood high school. ``at the elementary level, kids are wearing inoperative beepers to appear tough or macho and mimic the older kids. and that's not something to encourage.''
pierce and other principals said they don't have figures, but pierce said the number of beepers showing up in schools is alarming. pierce said he has been confiscating pagers at his school for three years
