at a hearing before the three-member planning and environment committee this week, residents said the brewery and restaurant would bring drunken drivers, traffic and noise to their neighborhood on the city's westside
city council members ruth galanter and michael woo agreed, but councilman hal bernson, the committee chairman, withheld his vote until he could visit the site
in a telephone interview at spago's, puck's west hollywood restaurant, the chef said he would not push the project against strong local opposition
i want it to be a neighborhood restaurant,'' puck said. ``if the neighborhood doesn't want it, i don't want to spend years fighting them.''
puck envisions building what he called a ``boutique,'' or ``micro brewery'' that would produce a quality beer
the 21-year-old defendant in what has been dubbed the ``preppie murder'' trial peered through trees on a damp, gray friday morning as the jurors in his case tramped over the central park ground where he left a young woman dead
robert chambers, 21, charged with second-degree murder in the death of jennifer levin, sat in the back of a gray car about 40 yards from where her bruised, nearly naked body was found aug. 26, 1986
it was a different vantage point from the low wall behind the metropolitan museum of art where he sat as police investigated the death shortly after miss levin's body was discovered by a passing bicyclist. chambers admits killing her but says it was an accident after she attacked him sexually and hurt him
the cold, damp ground around the tree where the body was found was bare, and the tree was stripped of leaves, a contrast to the green grass and foliage in the park on the warm summer morning when miss levin was killed
the jurors walked over to examine the areas where the victim's body and panties were found and where several police officers testified they had seen a ground disturbance suggesting a body had been dragged
fifty reporters and photographers and a few onlookers watched the proceeding from a distance, kept away by a yellow police ribbon
the trip came a day after a prosecutor testified he was not trying to trick chambers by saying police had not found miss levin's underpants in the park when in fact they had
in a videotaped interview, assistant district attorney stephen saracco is heard telling chambers that his account of how he killed miss levin does not make sense in part because no panties were found
chambers' lawyer, jack litman, has suggested that saracco tried to trick his client by lying to him
chambers and miss levin, 18, went to the park after meeting in an east side bar frequented by children of privilege. both had attended prep schools; miss levin was college-bound while chambers was a college dropout
chambers says the young woman tied his hands behind his back with her panties, sat on his chest facing his feet and grabbed his genitals painfully. he says he freed his hands, threw the panties over his head and reached up with his left forearm and yanked against her throat, flipping her off him
detective michael sheehan testified early in the 9-week-old trial that another investigator passed saracco a note during the videotaping to tell him the panties were found. he said they were recovered some 45 feet from the body
do you remember a note being put in front of you?'' defense lawyer jack litman asked saracco
i don't recall a note _ if there was one,'' saracco said. ``i don't know if there was a note.''
