the plo claimed responsibility for a car packed with explosives that was found near a hotel where secretary of state george p. shultz was staying. the guerrilla group said shultz was the target
police, who defused the bomb safely, said the car had been found accidentally after it was abandoned by its driver. there were no reports of arrests
a u.s. embassy spokesman said the bomb was well off the route the secretary took from the hotel to israeli government offices
but yasser arafat's mainstream palestinian guerrilla group, fatah, said in a statement in beirut that ``the driver had an accident and the car crashed into a power pole about 30 minutes before the time set for the bomb to explode.''
the driver deserted the vehicle and managed to escape,'' the communique said
in a communique telephoned to the associated press office in west beirut, fatah said its military command ``instructed the limassol martyrs group to park a bomb-laden car in front of the hilton hotel in jerusalem targeting shultz, the messenger of imperial'' yehudai said. ``later the chief police explosives expert passed by and through his own experience decided the car was indeed suspicious ... we found it was a car bomb.''
the car carried israeli license plates with a sticker reading: ``contribute to security.''
israel television quoted police officials as saying the car was sold ``to an arab who apparently used a fake identity (card).''
the car was found less than a quarter-mile from the hotel, where shultz spent thursday night
three officials of arafat's palestine liberation organization were killed in a car bomb explosion in the cypriot port of limassol feb. 14
the plo blamed israel's mossad secret service for the bombing
it said the attack was meant to be ``a response to the zionists' brutality against our people in the occupied territories.''
we warn shultz and all agents of imperialism against reaching out for the plo, the sole legitimate representative of the palestinian people,'' the communique added
it was the second report of a car bomb in two days. on thursday, one exploded outside the bus station of kfar saba, a town in central israel, causing no injuries
here, at a glance, is a rundown of some of the new postage rates recommended friday by the independent postal rate commission:
_first class (letters):
first ounce 25 cents, up from 22 cents. additional ounces 20 cents, up from 17 cents
presorted by zip code 21 cents, up from 18 cents
presorted by letter carrier route, 19.5 cents, up from 17 cents
post cards, 15 cents, up from 14 cents
presorted cards by zip code, 13 cents, up from 12 cents
_priority mail:
up to 2 pounds, $2.40, unchanged
_express mail:
under 8 ounces, $8.75, new rate
up to 2 pounds, $12, up from $10.75
up to 5 pounds, $15.25, up from $12.85
_second-class mail (newspapers and magazines):
in county per pound 9.8 cents, up from 9.1 cents. per piece sorted by carrier route 3.4 cents, up from 3.1 cents. the rate for not sorted items would be 5.9 cents, up from 4.9 cents
outside county per pound 12.4 cents to 30.2 cents, up from 11.8 cents to 28.9 cents. per piece 9.9 cents to 16 cents, up from 7.8 cents to 12.3 cents
outside county nonprofit per pound, 9.2 cents to 23.1 cents, changed from 8.5 cents to 28.3 cents; per piece 7.4 cents to 13.1 cents, up from 4.2 cents to 8.7 cents
_third-class mail (advertising):
bulk minimum 16.7 cents, up from 12.5 cents. sorted by zip code, 13.2 cents, up from 10.1 cents.sorted by carrier route, 10.1 cents, up from 8.3 cents. pound rate, 48 cents, up from 38 cents
nonprofit bulk minimum 9 cents, up from 8.5 cents. sorted by zip code 8.2 cents, up from 7.1 cents; sorted by carrier route, 5.9 cents, up from 5.5 cents. pound rate, 28 cents, up from 25.3 cents
_fourth-class mail (parcels):
parcel post: range of $1.63 to $25.46, up from a range of $1.19 to $24.35
library rate: first pound 65 cents, up from 54 cents
_special services:
registered mail, $4.40, up from $3.35
certified mail, 85 cents, up from 75 cents
special delivery, $5.35, up from $2.95
insurance: $25 value, 70 cents, up from 50 cents
money orders: $25 value, 75 cents, unchanged
collect on delivery: $25 value, $2.00, up from $1.50
the best-liked commercials of 1987 included some starring performances from animated characters such as dancing clay raisins, a hamburger chain's moonman and a pizza company's dreaded spoiler called a noid
few of the commercials mentioned most often by consumers polled by video storyboard tests inc. featured traditional show business celebrities, the head of the consumer research firm said thursday
we seem to heading into a period when we see more created celebrities, not necessarily human beings, in commercials,'' said david vadehra, president of video storyboard, in relasing the results of the firm's 10th annual survey of more than 25,000 people
leading the list was the campaign for california raisins, which used clay models of raisins dancing to the sounds of motown music. the ads cost a relatively modest $5.4 million, compared to as much as $344 million for mcdonald's corp. commercials
second was bud light beer commercials, many of which featured the english bull terrier spuds mackenzie while others offered numerous variations of what can go wrong if you simply order a ``light'' without specifying the brand
the ad campaign for pepsi soft drinks placed third, and miller lite beer commercials were fourth. ads for mcdonald's restaurants came in fifth
the noid, the animated imp with the maniacal laugh who threatens the freshness of home-delivered pizza in domino's pizza commercials, was foiled again and wound up 10th
one job title is just like any other _ or is it?
how about ``terminal operator'' for mortician, or ``mobile sanitatian engineer'' for garbage truck driver. or ``vice president, participation and residuals,'' the person in charge of royalties?
these are some of the titles personnel executives from about 100 companies reported in a survey by personnel journal, based in costa mesa, calif., which didn't identify any of the people or companies it quoted
whether humorous or obscure, job titles do serve a purpose, personnel managers insist
titles are accepted as a form of recognition and motivation,'' said an unidentified personnel manager of a chicago-based association management firm. ``they give the feeling of function and stature.''
people need structure and organization to provide a sense of stability and belonging _ where do they fit in the organization? titles help them,'' says a personnel executive at a federal hospital in milwaukee
there are some negatives to titles, the personnel managers admit
they create a class distinction and enhance the we-versus-them attitude,'' said an executive of a mining company in missoula, mont. statement</head>
the ranking republican on the house foreign affairs committee on friday called for a protest to the soviet union, while the state department sought to minimize the significance of its statement on microwave beams aimed at the u.s. embassy in moscow
rep. william s. broomfield of michigan said secretary of state george p. shultz should lodge an official protest over the continuing presence of low-level microwave beams aimed at the embassy
how can we trust the soviets to honor sensitive arms reduction agreements if they are technically attacking our embassy building?'' broomfield said. ``trust is an essential part of improving relations with the u.s.s.r. harassing our diplomats there is unacceptable.''
he added: ``i want the state department to play hardball this time and protest this clear abuse of our fellow citizens'' serving in moscow
in a statement released thursday in response to questions submitted by the associated press, the state department's bureau of diplomatic security said ``microwave signals in the 5-11 ghz (gigahertz) range continue to be detected at the moscow embassy chancery.''
the microwave signal power levels are typically 0.1 microwatt per square centimeter external to the building,'' it said. ``measurements internal to the building are typically less than 0.01 microwatt per square centimeter.''
the current u.s. voluntary safety standard for exposure to microwave radiation _ set by the american national standards institute _ is 5,000 microwatts per square centimeter. by contrast, the soviet union's official safety standard for the microwave frequency range is much lower _ 10 microwatts per square centimeter
the statement thursday said the department could shed no light as to why microwaves have been aimed against the embassy for perhaps as far back as october 1953. it said ``any response would be speculation.''
at a news briefing friday, state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley emphasized the low power levels of the soviet signals currently being detected at the embassy and denied that the situation amounts to ``bombardment.''
the soviets have not resumed microwave bombardment,'' she said. ``we have routinely detected some very low-level microwave activity in our ongoing continuous microwave screening at the embassy. ... there are no known risks from the type of low levels of exposure in moscow that have continued
we are, of course, concerned about this situation,'' mrs. oakley continued. ``in the past, we've protested when levels have exceeded those we consider safe. we're prepared to do so again, should we determine that they pose any threat whatsoever to our staff, however remote.''
she added: ``what we're saying is that there is not a new program of bombardment. we have watched the situation carefully. we continue to watch it carefully. there have been low levels that we have detected, but these pose no risk.'' update with background on noraid</note>
the state department has denied a visa to gerry adams, head of the irish republican army's legal political wing, based on the belief that he is involved in terrorist activity, a spokeswoman said thursday
he was ineligible under (the section) of the immigration and nationality act which excludes from admission to the u.s. people who are personally involved with terrorist activities,'' said state department spokeswoman donna sherman
asked to specify the activities, sherman said: ``our information is that as president of the provisional sinn fein, mr. adams is personally and publicly committed to and abets the armed struggle in northern ireland, and it's on that basis he was denied a visa.''
the ira is fighting to end british rule in northern ireland and is outlawed on both sides of the border, although sinn fein is legal
adams had said on his application that he wished to travel to the united states for ``political work,'' sherman said
martin galvin, a spokesman for the irish northern aid committee, said in a mailgram to the associated press that his group was ``outraged'' by the state department's action, and blamed it on pressure from britain
we regard the continuing denial of a visa to mr. adams as censorship by visa denial,'' galvin wrote
the committee, also known as noraid, charged that the state department was refusing ``to comply with the spirit and letter of the new visa provisions.''
noraid claims to aid the victims of strife between protestants and roman catholics, but the u.s., irish and british governments accuse it of helping finance ira operations
sen. daniel p. moynihan, d-n.y., and rep. barney frank, d-mass., introduced an amendment last year which overturned that portion of the mccarran walter act which had allowed the u.s. government to deny visas to aliens who participate in political activities in their native countries which would be legal for u.s. citizens in the united states
however, sherman said adams was denied a visa based on another part of the law that, she said, ``explicitly preserves the authority of the executive branch to deny a visa to someone who is involved in terrorist activity.''
this was at least the third time that adams, who is also a member of british parliament, has been denied a visa to the united states. earlier rebuffs occurred in june 1986 and february 1985, sherman said
in july 1986, canada denied adams entry because he had been convicted of attempting to escape from prison in 1974 after being held for two years under emergency powers
adams had been trying to reach canada after being denied a u.s. visa to address a conference of irish-americans in buffalo, n.y
police officers from fairfax, calif., weren't libeled by an x-rated film in which actors wore the department's uniforms, a state appeals court ruled thursday
ten past or present fairfax officers, including a policewoman, had sued the filmmaker, distributor and a magazine that had carried a publicity photo from the film for libel, invasion of privacy and emotional distress. they sought $240 million
but the appeals court, upholding a lower-court decision, said in a 3-0 ruling that there was no intent to portray actual fairfax police officers and no danger that the public would confuse the actors with the real officers
the film, ``nightlife,'' made in 1983 by a now-defunct filmmaker, included a segment in which two policemen agree not to arrest two prostitutes in exchange for sex
actors wore surplus fairfax, calif., police uniforms from a costume store in san francisco, the appeals court said
the film did not identify the location of fairfax at a time when there were at least six fairfax police departments in various states, the court said
the court also noted that between 90 and 105 people had been authorized to wear the shoulder patch of the fairfax, calif., police. a0831 on seaton.</note>
henryk szeryng, a virtuoso violinist known for his refreshing and moving renditions of bach and brahms, died thursday in kassel, west germany, of a cerebral hemorrhage. he was 69
szeryng took up the violin at age 7. in 1936, he studied at the paris conservatory, winning the coveted first prize. szeryng studied composition with the legendary nadia boulanger and gabriel bouillon and became friends with jean cocteau, pablo picasso and igor stravinsky
at the outbreak of world war ii, szeryng, who spoke seven languages fluently, was made polish prime minister wladislav sikorski's official translator and later became a personal goverment liaison officer
renowned worldwide for a vast repertoire which he executed with great skill and feeling during a career that spanned more than 50 years, szeryng was to have performed wednesday in brussels at a concert to benefit aids research
louis g. seaton, former chief labor negotiator at general motors corp., died thursday at age 81
seaton joined gm as a graphic artist in 1928, transferring to the industrial relationship department four years later. in 1946, he was named director of labor relations, with responsibility for day-to-day relations with the united auto workers and national contract negotiations until his retirement. he became a vice president in 1957
philip henry alston jr., a confidant of former president jimmy carter's and a former ambassador to australia, died wednesday. he was 76
alston was campaign chairman of carter's successful bid to become governor in 1970 and was chairman of the committee for jimmy carter when carter was elected president in 1976
carter, as governor, appointed alston to the board of regents and, as president, ambassador to australia. he was a co-founder of the georgia foundation, which raised millions of dollars for the university of georgia, where he received his undergraduate degree and was co-chairman of the joint tech-georgia development fund
albert fiala sr., who shot his wife to death in a highly publicized 1985 ``mercy killing,'' committed suicide at the age of 85
fiala shot his wife of 61 years, anna fiala, 79, as she experienced a severe diabetic seizure on aug. 10, 1985
two months later he was charged with second-degree murder. he pleaded guilty. fiala was sentenced to a year's probation and 52 weeks of community service at a bellevue food bank
a 600-pound soda machine toppled and crushed to death a 17-year-old in a school hallway thursday, firefighters said
j.r. strom of lynnwood ``was probably climbing on top and possibly rocking it,'' said shoreline fire battalion chief r. ladue. ``that's the only way it could have come down on him.''
ladue said the boy was found about 15 minutes after the machine fell at king's high school. a teacher needed six male students to help him lift the machine, he said
the house has killed its democratic leadership's proposal for a package of ``humanitarian'' aid for the nicaraguan contras, leaving the vacillating u.s. policy toward central america once again in limbo and the rebels without support
the lawmakers voted 216-208 thursday to reject the democrats' $30.5 million proposal that would have provided four months' worth of food, clothing and medical supplies to the rebels and created a new $14 million program to aid children who are victims of the nicaraguan civil war
forty-five democrats, mostly liberals who oppose any aid to the contras, joined with republicans, who thought the aid proposal too weak, to deal it a fatal blow. only five of 176 gop members present voted for the measure on the final ballot
organizers called off a general strike as support faded, saying a money crunch in the next few days will paralyze the nation and keep up pressure on the government without their help
checks are not clearing, there is no cash and businesses without currency cannot work, so there will be a de facto strike,'' aurelio barria, president of the panamanian chamber of commerce, industry and agriculture, told reporters thursday
the work stoppage, which began monday and was called off thursday night, was aimed at forcing gen. manuel noriega from power after he was fired feb. 25 by president eric arturo delvalle. delvalle himself was promptly dismissed the following day by an emergency meeting of noriega loyalists in the national assembly
the national research council said today its 14-month review following the challenger disaster has found ``no show-stoppers'' to prevent nasa from resuming manned space flights in august
our general impressions are favorable,'' an nrc committee said in a 144-page report
but it also found fault with nasa's way of troubleshooting complex space shuttle systems and recommended a keener and more methodical evaluation of risks and hazards
a late-winter storm blamed for at least seven deaths plastered the midwest with up to 8 inches of snow and ice, toppling trees and power lines and leaving more than 65,000 people without electricity today, officials said
the storm left as much as 8 inches of snow in ohio, while freezing rain in indiana and illinois thickly layered roads, bridges, trees and power lines with as much as 2 inches of ice
it's just a winter wonderland out there,'' said dan mccarthy of the national weather service's severe storms center in kansas city. ``it's like a hockey rink.''
the soviet union still is bombarding the u.s. embassy in moscow with microwave radiation, more than four years after u.s. officials protested a resumption of the tactic, the state department says
microwave signals in the 5-11 ghz (gigahertz) range continue to be detected at the moscow embassy chancery,'' the department said thursday in written responses to questions from the associated press
the statement by the department's bureau of diplomatic security also showed that u.s. officials still don't know the purpose of the low-level radiation bombardment
senior officials of the u.s. trust territory of palau may be involved with smuggling southeast asian heroin into the united states, the chairmen of two house panels charge
the accusation was made by interior chairman morris udall, d-ariz., and del. ron de lugo, d-virgin islands, chairman of the interior subcommittee on insular and international affairs
they quoted the u.s. drug enforcement administration as saying that the pacific islands ``are being used to transship heroin from southeast asia to the u.s.''
federal researchers could find no new or unusual pathways by which aids spread in a study of 2,059 people who apparently contracted the deadly disease from unknown sources, says a report published today
another new study concluded that routine screening of surgical patients for the aids virus is unwarranted because it would wrongly identify as many as 130,000 people as having the virus for every surgeon it saved from infection
even though surgeons are very important people, somehow changing the lives of 130,000 people to protect one of them doesn't seem quite right to me,'' said one of the researchers, dr. stephen g. pauker
ibm researchers say they've set a record high temperature for superconductivity _ a jump of 35 degrees _ by varying the recipe that produced the old mark reported last month
the accomplishment is a significant step toward making superconductors practical, according to a superconductivity expert
the new material lost all resistance to electricity at minus 234 degrees fahrenheit, said edward engler of the international business machine corp. almaden research center in san jose, calif
a sharp increase in methane gas in the atmosphere since 1978 probably will make earth warmer and may worsen seasonal losses of protective ozone over antarctica, scientists say
but the 11 percent increase in methane in the past decade also may slow depletion of the ozone shield over the rest of the planet, said f. sherwood rowland and donald r. blake, chemists at the university of california at irvine
their nasa-funded study was published today in the journal science
for the first time in canadian history, a member of parliament has revealed that he is homosexual, surprising the public, delighting gay rights activists and provoking right-wing ridicule
