we do not choose to be gay or lesbian and are not seeking special rights, merely the right to live openly in dignity without losing our jobs or homes or being subjected to violence,'' robinson, 36, said. concern</head>
ten years after the federal government forced a change in the stuff that makes liquid spew out of aerosol cans, some environmentalists are worrying that it was simply a matter of swapping one evil for another
in a sense we did,'' said lon burnam, clean air consultant for the sierra club in dallas. ``but you can easily make the argument that the one that we went to is less harmful than the one that we left.''
most of today's aerosol products are pushed out of the can by hydrocarbons, a propellant that gained wide use when a government ban on chlorofluorocarbons went into effect in march 1978
the order to remove cfcs from most aerosols came after scientists found the propellants might be reaching the upper atmosphere and thinning the ozone layer that shields people and plants from the sun's potentially harmful ultraviolet rays
the hydrocarbons that replaced cfcs help form ozone _ but close to the ground, where it contributes to the smoggy haze that scores of cities are struggling to combat. extended exposure is known to cause or aggravate respiratory problems
although hydrocarbons are found in much greater concentrations in vehicle exhaust and industrial emissions, some officials under pressure to clear the air are looking at limiting the use of aerosols
we're beginning to run out of things we can do in the industrial sector. we've also already done quite a bit with the automobile,'' said les montgomery, director of regulation development for the texas air control board. ``consumer areas are getting to be the remaining area that we haven't done too much in.''
new york city officials, for instance, are seeking the aerosol industry's cooperation in reducing the hydrocarbons given off by air fresheners and spray pesticides
we'll be asking manufacturers by a specified date to submit their own plan for reducing the ozone-creating pollutants in their products,'' said r.w. groneman, a spokesman for the new york state department of environmental conservation
new york officials expect to propose the regulations by early april. new jersey officials are keeping tabs on the effort, groneman said
but the aerosol industry has been opposed to further regulation after its experience with the fluorocarbon ban _ ``the biggest thing to hit the industry in the 1970s,'' according to evelyne mcfeaters of the chemical specialties manufacturers association
the group represents about 400 makers of household products
the ban cost the industry $1 billion to retool,'' ms. mcfeaters said. ``with this proposal, we'd be seeing an even greater cost. they're talking about potentially billions of dollars. the hydrocarbon propellants are the major propellants in use.''
last fall, the texas air control board proposed a ban on most aerosols in dallas and neighboring fort worth, one of 14 metropolitan areas trying to develop air quality regulations acceptable to the u.s. environmental protection agency
the 14 metro areas have been found by epa to be in violation of clean air act standards, but they won reprieves from federal sanctions. now, their plans for reducing levels of ozone and other pollutants are to take effect aug. 31
under the proposed dallas-fort worth ban, state officials wanted different propellants used or wanted stores to clear their shelves of the hydrocarbon aerosol products, ranging from hair spray to insecticides and paint
the ban on so-called volatile organic compounds eventually was scrapped because of opposition from consumers, retailers and the aerosol industry. the industry association estimated the ban could have cost the area more than $77 million annually in sales
besides, consumers probably would have skirted the ban by driving to neighboring counties to buy aerosols, said ralph engel, president of the chemical specialties manufacturing association
aerosol manufacturers are skeptical about substitute propellants suggested to take the place of hydrocarbons
many of the possible substitutes could actually increase the amount of voc (volatile organic compounds) in the air,'' ms. mcfeaters said
one non-aerosol alternative is the pump spray
i would think people prefer aerosols to pump sprays because of the extra effort involved in using a pump,'' said jim may, a spokesman for s.c. johnson and co. but the racine, wis.-based company had no research on consumer acceptance of pump-spray products
the company, known for its johnson's wax products, uses hydrocarbons _ most often propane and butane _ in more than 90 percent of its products, may said
montgomery of the texas air control board says he recognizes an aerosol ban would be difficult to enforce
it would need to be a national thing,'' he said. ``it's unlikely to expect that a major corporation with a national or international market is going to reformulate its propellant just for the dallas-fort worth market.''
but burnam noted that automakers have accommodated california's stricter air pollution laws by offering cleaner-operating versions of their cars in that state
it's not only practical, but a reasonable thing to do,'' he said of banning aerosols. ``there's a whole range of products that are a waste of the consumer's dollar and are counterproductive to healthy living.''
besides aerosol air fresheners and cleaning products, the proposed texas ban also would have limited solvents used in house and car paints, as well as other products that give off fumes
montgomery expected similar proposed limits on consumer products may become more widespread
if the current federal clean-air act requirements keep driving areas to try to work on this ozone problem and, as we run out of other things, i guess it's a type of control that other areas may look at.''
nestled in the lush jungles of the hawaiian islands is a multibillion-dollar industry that the local growers protect, the government destroys, the vistors bureau rarely mentions and tourists often overlook on secluded mountain trails
it is marijuana, and despite the government's best efforts to eradicate it, the state's largest cash crop continues to flourish and enjoy the reputation as some of the best ``pakalolo'' in the world
the government destroys more pot plants here than anywhere else in the united states, but still the crop thrives, nurtured by year-round, near-perfect growing conditions
a prayer goes into the ground with every plant,'' said roger christie, spokesman for the marijuana political action committee in hilo and a member of the cambridge, mass.-based cannabis corp. ``these islands are a magic place for growing pakololo. the sun, the rain, the energy of the volcano all combine to create the right conditions.''
the islands' light, misty rain, which was considered a blessing by ancient hawaiians, is also a boon to pot growers, christie said, adding that the year-round sunshine is rarely intense enough to scorch the plants
oh, the stuff here is definitely legendary,'' said george auflick, agent in charge at the drug enforcement agency here. ``hawaii pot is so highly prized that a lot of growers from other pacific islands ship their stuff to honolulu first, just so it can go to the mainland with a hawaii postmark. it's just got sort of a mythical reputation.''
that reputation is reflected in the price, auflick said. locally grown marijuana goes for about $150 an ounce on the islands, he said. but on the mainland, what is known as maui wowie, kona gold and puna butter sells for about $300 to $500 an ounce, with the highest prices on the east coast. in comparison, an ounce of mexican or californian marijuana fetches $60 an ounce in los angeles, with colombian selling for about $200 an ounce, according to the narcotics division of the los angeles police department
prices here rise after each big raid, and lately the going rate has been steep. that pleases capt. richard carter, the head of the criminal investigation unit of the police department on the ``big island'' of hawaii, where an estimated 66 percent of the state's crop is grown
every time the price goes up, that means there is less of it around,'' carter said. ``and that means we're doing our job.''
law enforcement officials say marijuana harms the younger population that has grown up with it and creates crime and violence
in 1987, 1.25 million marijuana plants and 752 pounds of dried pot were seized on the big island alone, carter said. each plant is considered to be worth $1,000, which means more than $1.2 billion worth of marijuana was recovered last year on the big island alone
authorities figure about 1.8 million plants were destroyed throughout the state. but for every plant destroyed, two or three were left to flourish, carter said
they (the growers) know we can't get to it all,'' carter said. ``so they sort of plant some for us and some for them. but lately we've been getting to a lot of the stuff they'd thought they'd hidden.''
the department patrols well-known growing areas daily, carter said, but ``operation green harvest'' is the department's twice-a-year all-out effort to get rid of the crop. coinciding with the major harvesting times, the joint effort between the local police and national guard has all the makings of a hollywood movie
helicopters swoop over acres of green fields, carrying specially trained officers. when a sizable marijuana crop is spotted, the cops rush into the fields, armed with machetes, and leave a swath of destruction, carter said. some officers even rappel down from the helicopters into hard-to-reach, mountainside gardens. and police have a new weapon _ diesel oil _ which is even more efficient, he said. sprayed on crops, it destroys them, ``roots and all,'' he said
arrests are infrequent during ``operation green harvest,'' carter said, because the whirring helicopters warn growers of the impending raid
the authorities' increased efficiency has forced growers to be more careful about camouflaging their crops _ scattering them with as few as 25 plants to a patch, or planting under the leafy canopy of ohia trees or in remote canyons or rocky mountainsides
still, many growers are not secretive at all, and plant marijuana at the edge of papaya or sugar cane fields, carter said
that kind of defiance has some officials on the mainland worried about whether hawaii law enforcement officials are really doing all they can to rid the state of a drug trade that is said to bring in more than $4 billion a year, second only to the tourist industry
the issue got national attention recently after rep. charles rangel, the chairman of the u.s. house select committee on narcotics abuse and control, released a report claiming that the drug trade in hawaii was a major industry that had bought influence in the state government
local reaction to the new york democrat's allegations was swift and angry, with rep. daniel akaka, d-hawaii, calling rangel's contentions unjustifiable. after the outcry, the committee agreed to hold hearings on the issue in hawaii this spring
anybody who lives here _ unless they have their head in the sand _ knows we have a drug problem. but we're doing everything we can to fight it,'' said carolyn tanaka, press secretary to hawaii gov. john waihee
illegal cultivation brings a lot of money to the growers, but not to the state in general,'' she said, adding, ``we don't care how much money marijuana would bring in, trying to legalize it just so it can be taxed is out of the question.''
but the marijuana pac's christie, who is leading a drive to legalize marijuana for medical use in hawaii, said the state is giving up a valuable source of revenue in it's zeal ``to dictate the public morality.'' a derivative of marijuana has been used to relieve some side effects of chemotherapy in cancer patients
eradication of marijuana is ``not an issue of the government caring for the people,'' christie said. ``if that were the issue, they'd ban the shot glass and the beer mug.''
he said marijuana can be used to make rope, paper and canvas
the best efforts of local, state and federal law enforcement officials will not stop the marijuana farmers, christie said
backyard growers with just a few plants can make up to $20,000 a year, he said, while those with larger plots rake in $80,000 and up annually
the bottom line is that more people than ever want the stuff,'' he said, ``and there is plenty of it here.''
mister rogers is introducing his young viewers to a new neighbor this week, and he'd like nothing more than for everyone to be friends
the land is the soviet union, which he visited last year as a guest on moscow's ``good night, little ones.'' the neighbor is tatiana vedeneeva, the soviet television program's host who subsequently dropped by ``mister rogers' neighborhood.''
the aim, both say, is to foster a better understanding between the two countries through the eyes and ears of the young
that's the goal of the neighborhood anyway, to be able to understand and care for yourself better and as you understand and care for yourself, you look through understanding eyes at your neighbor,'' said fred rogers, creator and host of ``mister rogers' neighborhood.''
just like children grow little by little, one increment after another, that's the way human beings grow. i think that that's the way countries grow in trust, just one step at a time,'' he explained with the same gentleness that has become his on-screen trademark
this exchange of pint-sized culture, a year in the making, could turn those steps into leaps, according to rogers and vedeneeva. an inspired rogers, in fact, is considering trips to other countries
even though they (children) are tiny, it's a big bridge,'' vedeneeva said during her november visit to pittsburgh's wqed-tv, home of ``mister rogers' neighborhood'' for the past 20 years
rogers' visit to ``good night, little ones'' last september will be aired by the public broadcasting service on tuesday. the show includes street scenes of moscow
even though i can't see those people right now, i can think about them and know that they're somewhere,'' rogers tells his viewers. ``and they're not pretend. they're real. just like you. even though you're not in this room on this couch with me, you're somewhere and you're real.''
ms. vedeneeva's visit to ``mister rogers' neighborhood'' will be shown thursday. rogers greets her with a song he composed just for the occasion
we would like to welcome you. it's good to be in touch. we would like to welcome you. our friendship means so much,'' he sings, accompanying himself at the piano
the message of this week's programs, according to rogers, is ``that children in the soviet union start out as babies and get to be toddlers and get to be pre-schoolers and school-age children just like children here.''
it's (also) trying to demonstrate that adults throughout the world care for children and that people as far away as the soviet union have tender feelings about their children, just the way americans do,'' he said
for vedeneeva, the similarities are just as striking
our children love the same thing as your children love to do,'' she said in russian. ``they would love to get acquainted with american children and especially with mister rogers.''
soviet children last december got their first glimpse of the cardigan- and sneakers-clad rogers, the first guest ever to appear on ms. vedeneeva's nightly 15-minute show. the broadcast coincided with soviet leader mikhail gorbachev's summit meeting with president reagan
except for a few words of russian, the 59-year-old rogers spoke english on the soviet set. still, he managed to master one phrase that he repeated again and again to the many children he met: ``boodish li ti moy sawsed?'' or ``won't you be my neighbor?''
ms. vedeneeva, who speaks little english, was assisted by a translator for ``mister rogers' neighborhood.'' the interpreter figures prominently on thursday's show, narrating a segment showing how russian matrouska dolls are made
i don't think we've ever had an interpreter on the set. so that could help children see what that's like,'' rogers said
rogers was accompanied to moscow by hand puppets daniel tiger and `x' the owl. vedeneeva made her first journey to the united states with stepashka the rabbit and xrysha the pig
the puppets _ kukli in russian _ seemed to have as much fun as their creators. daniel tiger and xrysha the pig, in fact, shared a shy smooch in moscow
oooh, you're such a big pig. a bolshoi pig,'' daniel tiger told xrysha. ``i like you.''
stepashka, however, seemed to put it best
girls and boys, we're going to be your good neighbors. it means good friends, too,'' the rabbit said before leaving ``mister rogers' neighborhood.''
goodbye,'' it said, waving at the cameras. ``i love you.''
elsewhere in television:
marcos miniseries _ hbo plans to present next fall a six-hour miniseries tentatively titled ``the four-day revolution'' about the fall of the marcos regime in the philippines. one of the central characters will be an american journalist played by gary busey. the miniseries is already in production in manila. the script is by david williamson, who wrote the screenplay for ``the year of living dangerously.''
the white house, business groups and some political office seekers, such as george bush, just won't let go of the matter, and so it is seems destined to grow into a major issue
issues are created by differences of opinion strongly held, and on this there are many opinions. it is controversial, debatable, emotional. it can be construed as a battle of haves versus have-nots, rich vs. poor
the question: should the capital gains tax, which was raised in the tax reform act of 1986, be reduced _ perhaps to a rate even lower than before?
central to the issue is another question: can revenues be raised by cutting the capital gains tax, as the white house and bush suggest?
backers of a cut cite the u.s. treasury's own statistics in support of their view. they point to steady increases in revenues since the tax was cut from 49 percent to 28 percent in 1979, and then to 20 percent in 1981
in 1978, when the 49 percent maximum rate was still in effect, tax revenue amounted to $9.1 billion. in 1984, latest year for which figures are available, the total was $19.6 billion
sharp as these statistical differences are, some critics maintain they are not as significant as they seem. stock market prices, they point out, have risen sharply over the years. they say it is this that accounts for the rise
why should lower taxes raise revenues? because, say defenders of a lower tax, those taxpayers with capital gains wouldn't be afraid to take them. until those gains are realized, they observe, uncle sam gets nothing at all
the crux of their argument is that those with big gains in securities or other investments, including housing, decline to sell because of the 28 percent tax liability. if it were half that, they say, sellers would be more active
they contend that while this added activity would be taxed at a relatively lower rate, the government would earn more revenue because of the greater volume. estimates vary, but conceivably these gains could be sizable
david burton of the u.s. chamber of commerce estimates a reduction to 15 percent would produce at least $3.5 billion more each year. harvard economist lawrence lindsey puts the added revenue at $31 billion over three years
one of the most formidable arguments against the reduction is that it might produce a spurt of selling in the first couple of years, but that the benefits to uncle sam would be decidedly less dramatic after that
in short, say these critics, the cut itself rather than the rate of tax is the important thing. they agree that many taxpayers would take advantage of the cut to take postponed capital gains, but that afterward the impact would erode
defenders also contend that the country _ not just those with capital gains _ needs lower rates in order to spur investment in new businesses, new jobs and new technology _ which, of course, would enlarge the revenue-producing sector
they indicate that as matters stand a goodly amount of potential venture capital is tied up in old enterprises, left there by owners who cannot afford to pay _ or who choose to defer paying _ the taxes that would become due
potentially the hottest dispute of all is the contention that a lower capital gains tax benefits the rich and does very little, at least immediately, for the poor. it could be a dispute loaded with more passion than content
prof. lindsey states that 80 percent of the $31 billion he refers to would be paid by taxpayers with incomes greater than $100,000. inherent in that statement, however, is that most of the tax benefits would go to them also
the subject is at the heart of at least two bills in congress. over the next few months, it could become a political hot potato
just when the winds blowing from the soviet union bring the refreshing possibility of greater openness and reform, hungarians find their once-vaunted economy faltering
the government is warning them to expect a decline in living standards, regarded as the best in the east bloc
all that combined with uncertainty over the tenure of the 75-year-old communist party leader janos kadar is leaving hungarians in a bleak and wary mood
yet, the outward signs of economic trouble are few in this lovely capital on the danube. shops along the glittering vaci pedestrian mall are well-stocked and bustling, traffic clamors along the old chain bridge with bmws and hondas vying with soviet-made fiats and czech skodas, and women are dressed in stylish furs
it's only in the windows,'' said a budapest businessman
scratch beneath the surface, he added, and it becomes apparent that times are getting harder
a government austerity program took effect jan. 1, imposing the east bloc's first personal income tax and value-added tax. in addition, the government says inflation could rise from last year's 8 to 9 percent to 15 percent this year, which would make it the worst in the country's postwar history
compared to some nations in eastern europe, hungary remains an island of prosperity and economic stability. poland is expecting inflation of 40 to 45 percent this year. inflation in yugoslavia reached 170 percent this past fall
but hungary's economic woes arose over the last few years with ``breathtaking suddenness,'' one party member said. ``therefore we are bitter.''
the three-year ``program of consolidation,'' as the austerity measures are called, is intended to raise revenues to bridge yawning government deficits, caused largely by huge subsidies to money-losing industries
the government plans to phase out unprofitable factories, raising fears of increasing unemployment. some analysts say the jobless total could rise from 10,000 (0.2 percent) today to 200,000 (3.3 percent) of the 6-million-member work force
hungary borrowed in the 1970s to build heavy industry. now, its 10.6 million people are burdened with a gross hard currency debt of $16 billion, the highest per capita in the soviet bloc
on the positive side, exports to the west in 1987 were up 13 percent to $5.08 billion and tourism boomed, with more than 18 million people visiting the country. hungary's state-dominated agriculture continues to produce more than the country can consume
the austerity program is the work of 57-year-old prime minister karoly grosz, who took over government administration in july. since then, he has discussed hungary's problems with a frankness that surprised many of his countrymen
acknowledging calls for greater democratization, a communist party committee has promulgated a set of theses on political reforms and the party's ``leading role'' which has been presented to basic party cells and is to be put before a central committee meeting
if approved, the proposals would probably be forwarded to the first national party conference since 1957, which a party source said is expected early in june
the theses generally endorse greater consultation between the party and the population, more open debate in the party and a retreat from day-to-day party involvement in the government
diplomats said the theses appear to generate little enthusiasm. members of the unofficial opposition said they are disappointed by the proposals, calling them too vague to bring substantial change
there are many words about the necessity of political reform, but i am afraid that the speeches are not so sincere,'' said gyorgy gado, an opposition writer. ``i am afraid they haven't the courage to make the necessary changes.''
meanwhile, the question on everybody's mind is whether kadar will retire and who will take his place as head of the party, a senior western diplomat said
behind-the-scenes jockeying for position is practically paralyzing the government, the diplomat added. ``nobody does anything except politics right now.''
grosz is considered the leading candidate and the favorite of the soviets, even though his relations with party regulars and the coterie around kadar appear strained, said the diplomat, speaking only on condition of anonymity
also mentioned as possible successors are chief party ideologist janos berecz and, as a darkhorse, imre pozsgay, the leader of the national unity people's patriotic front, who advocates more dialogue with groups outside the party
kadar has been at the helm of the party since the soviet suppression of the 1956 hungarian revolution. described variously by diplomats in budapest as ``a wily old fox'' and ``a declining king surrounded by courtiers,'' he has given no known indication that he will step aside
but sources in and outside the party said kadar increasingly is out of touch with economic problems and is an obstacle to political reform
he has not been a bad dictator. even if you disagreed with him you could work,'' said a party member. ``now people want results.''
people feel as long as he's in power no real changes can happen,'' said ferenc koszeg, editor of the illegal magazine beszelo (talker)
and the public mood?
very gloomy,'' said the diplomat. ``compared to a year ago, the situation is closer to instability, although i still believe it's less than a 50-50 chance.''
said koszeg: ``people are so disappointed that they don't believe anybody any longer. this is an important handicap both for the government and the opposition.''
star wars'' and ``raiders of the lost ark'' made harrison ford one of america's top box office draws, but the actor says both he and his audience are maturing
i'm not an ingenue anymore,'' the 45-year-old actor said
his most recent effort leaves han solo and indiana jones in hyperspace. in the just-released roman polanski thriller, ``frantic,'' ford's cocksure quality disappears as he portrays a bespectacled father and husband caught in a situation beyond his control
it follows ``witness'' and ``the mosquito coast,'' two other movies where ford shucked invulnerability for more complex and sensitive roles. in his next film, the mike nichols comedy ``working girls,'' he has a cary grant-type part
i'm not trying to make a transition into a different kind of persona; i do whatever i think is appropriate for that character to tell the story,'' he said during a recent interview
but this is also related to growing older,'' he said, fingering his reading glasses in his right hand. ``i mean, `star wars' was almost 15 years ago. i am 15 years older. there's no sense denying it. in fact, i revel in it. i've been more interested in those characters that are more mature.''
in ``frantic,'' ford grows more uncomfortable in every scene. he plays a california heart surgeon at a medical conference in paris. terrorists kidnap his wife, but police and u.s. officials believe she willingly left him. he meets a sensuous young french woman who provides clues to the abduction and joins him in a struggle to find his wife
the whole thing depends on this doctor, this fish out of water, reaching this emotional exhaustion, where he does things that are well outside of his nature and experience,'' said ford
a concern for his real-life wife's safety led ford to paris, polanski and the part. he accompanied his pregnant wife, screenwriter melissa mathison (``e.t.''), to meetings in paris on an another project with polanski, the director of ``tess,'' ``chinatown'' and ``rosemary's baby.''
after the first few days, roman described the film to me and it sounded interesting,'' ford said
the script was in french, a language the actor does not speak. ``roman stood up and for two hours _ he told me the movie,'' ford said. ``he played all the parts, and he was great. when it was over, i said, `if you'll right that down in english, i'll do it.'''
ford calls himself ``mono-maniacal'' during filming, but always returns to his ranch in wyoming to ``go grocery shopping, pick up the laundry, work on the fence, plow the snow, read a little, fish a little and go cross-country skiing.''
wyoming is now home for ford. he was raised in a suburban chicago, went to school at ripon college in wisconsin and struggled as an actor and carpenter in southern california. ``star wars'' gave him the success and security to buy the ranch and spend some time there
i wouldn't be able to do it (acting) if i wasn't able to get back when it was over,'' he said
his current project is ``working girls,'' a comedy set in new york about a secretary who fights to retrieve an idea from a boss who has claimed credit for it
one of the pleasures of this comedy is that it's a relatively smaller part,'' said ford, who called the last two pictures ``killers.'' in ``working girls,'' he plays the boyfriend of melanie griffith and sigourney weaver
this fall, production begins on a third ``raiders'' movie. when that's over, ford will head back to his wife, his 10-month-old son, malcolm, and the ranch
and then?
i'm planning to take the next year off,'' he said
actor rob lowe is best known for his ``brat pack'' movie roles and romances with actress melissa gilbert and princess stephanie of monaco
but the heartthrob of the teeny-bopper set also is an active crusader against toxic wastes
he and other young screen actors, such as ally sheedy, judd nelson, daphne zuniga and alexandra paul, are just a few of hollywood's new breed of celebrity political activists
they represent a new generation of artists who have, like athletes, a tremendous effect at being role models for young people,'' said california assemblyman tom hayden
they're taken more seriously with americans than politicians because people know them. ... it's a very healthy tonic for an apathetic generation.''
hayden was a founder of students for a democratic society, one of the most visible student radical organizations of the 1960s, and is the husband of actress jane fonda, another celebrity activist
in 1985, the haydens became curious about the true interests of the so-called brat packers, who had been labeled selfish and self-centered by critics. they invited a few to their santa monica home, including tom cruise, kelly mcgillis, demi moore, emilio estevez, gilbert, nelson and lowe
once the haydens saw an interest was there, they formed network, an educational group that explains political issues to actors and introduces them to politicians
they are incredibly effective at motivating and opening up your minds,'' sheedy said of the couple. ``it's not something where they're trying to brainwash you in any way. there's no pressure at all.''
her involvement in network prompted the young star of ``war games'' and ``the breakfast club'' to throw a mixer with sen. alan cranston (d-calif.) for her actor friends
it was so much fun. it was so exciting,'' sheedy said
another hollywood activist group, young artists united, was formed two years ago by paul, who starred in ``dragnet,'' and filmmaker daniel sladek. yau involves young people in such social issues as teen suicide and drug and alcohol abuse, rather than political issues
some yau members include sarah jessica parker, star of tv's ``a year in the life,'' eric stoltz of ``mask'' and most of the network members
yau plans to put about 30 of the young actors on a bus caravan this april and cruise the southern california beach communities, urging young people to register to vote
i think there's a major transformation going on in the people of this generation from the `me' generation to the `we' generation. they realize they can accomplish a lot united,'' said the 23-year-old sladek
for fear of alienating their fans, actors generally remained aloof from politics until the 1930s, when hollywood threw its support behind president roosevelt and his social policies
hollywood staged massive support for world war ii, with war bond rallies and entertaining the troops abroad. some notables, especially charlie chaplin, supported the soviet cause, and their activities would haunt them later
the postwar period brought mccarthyism, when many careers were harmed or ruined through ``blacklisting'' by association with leftist causes. the reaction caused many actors to eschew support of any issues or candidates, and continued into the 1960s
however, the civil rights movement brought out such actors as marlon brando on marches, sit-ins and rallies. the vietnam war, environmental issues and women's rights also rekindled hollywood's social consciousness
this will be a busy year for network, said spokesman patrick lippert. members will start meeting presidential candidates at private meetings in the spring and will probably become active in the 1988 elections
last september, members of both groups worked against robert bork's confirmation to the u.s. supreme court by staging a post-card writing campaign with their peers
in october, nelson (``billionaire boys club,'' ``the breakfast club''), helen slater (``supergirl''), esai morales (``la bamba'') and mary stuart masterson (``at close range'') traveled to the soviet union to film a documentary for the national committee for a sane nuclear policy
zuniga (``spaceballs'') and paul visited nicaragua, where paul rode in a soviet-made helicopter with sandinistas
everyone was saying two years ago this is the most self-centered, selfish generation in years,'' lippert said. ``but what you see is the most idealistic group of young people. you see them getting involved in so many things, and reaching out to their generation.''
however, not all hollywood observers are jumping with praise for the political meanderings of brat packers
it's striking that not one of these stars has a dissenting view other than what's the norm in hollywood,'' said michael medved of pbs' ``sneak previews.''
it's absolutely nonsensical that alan cranston should follow rob lowe's advice to vote against robert bork for the supreme court,'' he continued. ``rob lowe, daphne zuniga and gregory peck (who did an anti-bork commercial) _ we take their position seriously because they're pretty. it's scary
i think they are sincerely interested in the issues. but part of burnishing your image is not to be written off as a pretty-face airhead. so you become politically involved.''
also dabbling in politics are such hollywood glamour girls as morgan fairchild, donna mills and sally field
field, a two-time academy award winner, was host of a poolside party at her home that featured massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, a presidential contender. mills, the scheming vixen of cbs-tv's ``knots landing,'' talked politics with sen. paul simon (d-ill.), another presidential hopeful, at a gathering at her home
fairchild, who has testified before both the house and senate on environmental issues, has given up needlepoint and instead spends her free time reading such weighty material as ``abu nidal: master terrorist'' or hefty medical reports on the deadly aids virus
i know that going in, a lot of people didn't take me seriously,'' said fairchild, who has no intention of giving up her sexy image. ``but i have a deceptively high i.q. and so when people sat down and started talking to me about some of these things, they started to take me seriously.''
while the stock market has rallied in recent months from its drastic drop last year, some wary analysts caution that it is still following the pattern set in 1929 and 1930
after the great crash in october 1929, the market regained its balance and recovered nearly 50 percent of its losses. but that rise turned out to be a deadly trap
by the time stock prices finally bottomed out in 1932, they were down about 90 percent from their peaks. a drop of the same magnitude today would put the dow jones industrial average at about 275
no market analyst with a wide following on wall street is currently predicting anything close to that. along with the similarities, most observers say, there are many differences in the world of the 1980s from the situation that prevailed nearly 60 years ago
furthermore, they say, if history were prone to repeating itself with any reliability in the market, the pursuit of making money in stocks would be a lot easier than it is
still, a good many people in the business of giving financial advice are very mindful these days of what is now known as the ``sucker rally'' of early 1930
the entire price action of the past few years has tracked the 1928-1930 span like clockwork,'' says martin zweig, a new york investment adviser, in the current issue of his letter the zweig forecast
the odds that this is the start of a new bull market are remote at the moment,'' he argues
eric miller, chief investment officer at donaldson, lufkin &amp; jenrette securities, says stocks at their recent prices reflect some hopes about the economic outlook that may go unfulfilled
we think the probability of a recession, and perhaps a severe one, is fairly high,'' he observes, ``and we also think that the current level of stock prices does not discount a recession.''
optimists on the market outlook, whose numbers have been growing lately, describe the recent behavior of stocks as healthy-looking
one distinct positive, they say, is that many smaller stocks have been rising faster lately than the blue chips that make up the dow jones industrial average, after lagging behind through the latter stages of the 1982-87 bull market. in theory at least, that betokens broad support for stocks
zweig says he is well aware of this view, but questions its validity. in the first three months of 1930, he says, a broad measure of stock prices he calculated rose 24.9 percent, while the dow was up 15.3 percent
`positive' divergence, as most call it, is normal after crashes which lead to continuing bear markets,'' he says
both zweig and miller acknowledge the possibility that they are wrong, and both hold some stocks in their recommended portfolios
as zweig put it: ``if this turns out to be a bull market, which i doubt, then fine. we own stocks now. if it's a bear rally, i'll look for exit signs as we go.''
should the advance turn out to be a ``sucker rally'' like the one in 1930, zweig concedes it will be a tricky mission to pluck the bait out before the trap snaps shut
i suspect that the rally, which looks ok on the tape, will continue to look good. why? to trap the maximum number of people for the next decline.''
japan's latest comic book heros are emperor hirohito and former prime minister yasuhiro nakasone
comic books are widely read in japan by both children and adults and often are used as teaching aids for such topics as history, economics or etiquette and even to explain frictions with the united states over trade
the hirohito comic book, which is in hard cover and is titled ``tenno heika'' (emperor), follows the 86-year-old monarch from childhood through world war ii, including his historic surrender broadcast in 1945, and into his quiet retirement in tokyo's imperial palace
the book on nakasone is called ``yatchan's,'' which was the former prime minister's childhood nickname. it is published quarterly by nakasone's office and sent to supporters and constituents
japanese prime ministers, once they step down, traditionally fade into the political background and take the role of party elder, occasionally seen but seldom heard
but nakasone, whose term in office ended this past november, has stayed in the news through trips abroad and the establishment of a think-tank group. ``yatchan's'' helps keep attention focused on him
the idea for a cartoon newsletter has been gestating for a long time, and it just happens that it was produced after nakasone-san left office,'' said masaki donji, a private secretary to nakasone. ``there was no deliberate timing to keep him in the news.''
while purporting to depict faithfully the characters' lives and careers, the comic books seem overly flattering
hirohito is shown as barrel-chested and cheerful rather than the aged and stooped man he is now
nakasone, now 67, is shown as burly, with round eyes and a uncharacteristic full head of hair
but the comic book presents little-known facets of nakasone's life
an essay by nakasone's wife tsutako says that, in his younger days when he was known as yatchan, nakasone pranced about in his underwear after baths, humming music from swan lake. and on state visits abroad as prime minister, he grudgingly allowed his wife off elevators first, but upon returning to japanese soil, would instantly declare, ``ladies first is over.''
yatchan's'' opens with nakasone's return from the 1987 summit in venice, italy, with photos of the six in-flight meals he was served on his special jet. it then flashes back to the beginning: a fiery-eyed nakasone resigning from tokyo's metropolitan police department in 1946 to work toward japan's postwar reconstruction
he reveals himself as an idealist who patterns himself after sakura sogo, a 17th-century village headman who was executed for seeking reduced taxes for poor peasants
he eats potatoes for lunch _ an expression of humility _ and chooses a white bicycle for his first political campaign because hirohito rode a white horse
subscriptions to ``yatchan's'' are 2,000 yen ($15.50) a year. the booklet also includes reproductions of nakasone's paintings, and samples of his haiku poetry
the hirohito book divulges some imperial trivia: the emperor has no surname, reached adulthood at age 18 (20 for ordinary japanese), and cannot adopt children or vote
it also explains that his duties include opening sessions of the diet (parliament), closing sessions of the house of representatives, receiving foreign ambassadors, and formally approving laws, government decrees, amendments to the constitution and treaties
hirohito, once regarded as a living god, remains a sensitive subject in modern japan, and ribbing of royalty by the press is neither tolerated nor attempted
but the comic book touches on some sensitive points in the emperor's life, including an assassination attempt, the great kanto earthquake of 1923 for which hirohito was later criticized for not doing enough for his people, and a 1936 military rebellion that led to the death of one of his favored ministers
it also touches briefly on his role in world war ii, although it reveals little about his activities or motivations during the conflict, and portrays hirohito's famed speech imploring the nation in august 1945 to bear the unbearable _ surrender
the emperor's trips to europe and the united states are shown, including protesters waving signs saying ``go home'' and ``fascist hirohito.'' it ends with him enjoying his favorite pastimes, walking along the beach and studying marine biology
an official of the imperial household agency, which tends to the imperial family's duties and needs, said the agency had nothing to do with the comic book and extended neither approval or assistance in its production
first el salvador, then nicaragua, now panama. like chain reactions, crises spread through central america. despite protests, despite u.s. pressure, panama's military leader, gen. manuel antonio noriega, the real boss of the country, remains in power, surviving charges of drug dealing, illicit money laundering, election fraud and violations of human rights. here is a look at how it all came about in a country the united states deems vital to its security
many panamanians have lived for years with the belief, if not the sure knowledge, that their government is corrupt, their elections are unfair and their leaders lust for money and power
there were protests from time to time, but they seldom lasted more than a few days. then the nation would sink back into a tropical lethargy abetted by prosperity. the voices of opposition were few
now the lethargy seems to be gone
the country is in turmoil over the military rule of gen. manuel antonio noriega, who has been indicted in the united states on drug charges. prosperity is threatened by a large foreign debt, u.s. economic pressure and the freezing of panamanian funds abroad
in recent years, money poured in from the panama canal, the new offshore banking center, an oil pipeline that helped carry alaskan crude to atlantic coast markets, a thriving re-export industry and a large u.s. military presence
it all helped an economy traditionally based on bananas, sugar and coffee weather the ups and downs of unstable agricultural markets, and made panama by far the wealthiest country on the central american isthmus
they were years of indulgence and indifference,'' says roberto brenes, a panama city investment banker and a leader of the broad new opposition movement that took firm root only nine months ago
the rich were getting richer, the middle class was growing and the lot of the poor was improving,'' said a diplomat with long experience in central america. ``it's always been a tolerant society, and few people saw any need to rock to the boat.''
neither did the united states, which saw in panama enough stability to make a treaty in 1977 that will deliver control of the vital canal between the atlantic and pacific to the panamanian government at the turn of the century
omar torrijos herrera, a charismatic army colonel, seized the government in 1968, broke the traditional rule of wealthy merchants and land barons and began a costly series of reforms
he built schools, schools, hospitals, health clinics, farm-to-market roads and other public works. with fervent nationalism, torrijos brought a new sense of pride and identity to the country, even its wealthiest citizens
much of his popularity came from his ability to tweak uncle sam's nose while maintaining relations with washington. few panamanian leaders had risked the slightest impertinance with the united states
his ideology became known as ``torrijismo'' and survived his death in an airplane crash in 1981, four years after he signed the canal treaty with president jimmy carter and fulfilled one of the fondest dreams of the panamanian people
although the country maintained the fiction of a president, torrijos ruled supreme as ``chief of government'' and commander of the national guard. he had no real opposition and the nation prospered from economic growth and public spending financed with money borrowed abroad
noriega came to power in 1983, four years after torrijos was killed, and the first presidential election since the 1968 coup was held the following year
nicolas ardito barletta, a respected economist, was elected president despite the fact that he had spent years with the world bank in washington and was little known at home
his election, by a margin of fewer than 2,000 votes, was tainted by charges of fraud. opponents held marches and auto caravans, honking horns, waving white banners and banging pots and pans in a traditional panamanian form of protest
like those before them, the demonstrations died within a week
the united states and the rest of the world recognized ardito barletta, as they had six other figurehead presidents installed and removed by the military since 1968. the first vice president was eric arturo delvalle, in his first elective office
less than a year later, in september 1985, it became ardito barletta's turn to go
he was summoned to military headquarters and held for 12 hours after calling for an impartial investigation into the murder of hugo spadafora, one of noriega's chief opponents. ardito barletta announced his resignation and delvalle was sworn in to replace him
once again, government upheaval was greeted largely by public apathy
noriega kept building his power, increasing the size of the military with the help of the united states
washington poured millions of dollars into the general's newly renamed panama defense forces, a single command encompassing 15,000 members of the army, air force, navy, police forces and state security agency in this nation of 2.2 million people
the canal treaty gives panama primary responsibility for the security of the waterway beginning with the year 2000. the carter administration, then president reagan, wanted the defense forces to be up to the task
rumors of military corruption recurred. then col. roberto diaz herrera, one of noriega's top aides, told reporters last june after his forced resignation that his former boss had rigged the 1984 elections, was engaged in the illegal selling of visas and had engineered the spadafora murder
spadafora's headless, mutilated body was found in august 1985, stuffed in a canvas u.s. mail bag just across the border in costa rica. he had threatened to offer proof of noriega's involvement in drug trafficking, and his family and friends insisted the general ordered the brutal murder
until diaz herrera began talking, however, no one in the military's tight inner circle had accused noriega of so much as fixing a traffic ticket
the former aide's frequent press interviews caused a sensation they also spawned the national civic crusade, a movement begun by a few wealthy businessmen whose disgust and anger at the military's increasingly heavy-handed interference in the government and economy had been building for some time
within weeks, the crusade grew to an umbrella organization covering about 200 professional, business, labor and political groups and had gained support from panamanians of the middle and lower classes
the crusade called its first strike june 10. it had little success but was followed by others and a series of mass protests, despite a state of emergency decree that forbade public gatherings and closed opposition newspapers and broadcast stations
by july 10, noriega had enough. he sent soldiers and riot police to break up a mass rally. more than 100 people were injured, many peppered by birdshot, and up to 600 were arrested and detained for four days
the movement appeared to lose heart, but bounced back with a successful strike in late july and a rally aug. 6 that attracted 30,000 anti-noriega demonstrators, despite the threat of repression. leaders of the civic crusade began seeking foreign support
delvalle's government responded with pro-noriega rallies and increasingly virulent attacks on the united states in speeches and government-owned newspapers
it all was done under the cloak of ``torrijismo,'' but the garment did not fit noriega well. in late august, a gallup poll indicated three of four panamanians wanted him to step down
after an attack on the u.s. embassy in june, the reagan administration had suspended all military and economic aid, which would have totaled $21 million this year. that brought howls of ``economic aggression'' from delvalle and other panamanian leaders
loss of the aid was particularly painful because panama faced a fiscal crisis, brought on by years of deficit spending that piled up a $4.5 billion foreign debt and capital flight caused by the civil unrest
early in february, two federal grand juries in florida indicted noriega on charges of drug trafficking, money laundering and racketeering
among other things, he is accused of helping colombia's notorious medellin cartel by providing safe airstrips for its cocaine shipments and safe haven for its hired killers
what he did was utilize his position to sell the country of panama to the traffickers,'' said u.s. atty. leon kellner of miami, who led the investigation for one indictment
events began unfolding rapidly feb. 25 when delvalle, scorned by the opposition as a puppet, decided he had had enough and ordered noriega's dismissal. the united states said it knew of his intentions, and continued to recognize him as president through the ensuing trouble
noriega arranged for the legislative assembly to remove delvalle the next day _ the special session lasted 10 minutes _ and hours later devalle went into hiding
the civic crusade called another strike, its sixth, last monday but acknowledged it would not be enough to drive noriega from office even the country closed down completely
opposition leaders said only the united states, with or without the support of the rest of latin america, had the financial clout to depose him
at week's end, roberto aleman, a lawyer and civic crusade leader, summed up the alliance's hopes:
the government will find itself besieged by economic and diplomatic measures taken in the united states and latin america. the measures will oblige the regime to take extremely unpopular measures such as raising taxes and firing public employees.''
thomas moscardini talks of manet and warhol in the same breath as undercover stings and doing time
for the new york city police detective, the two are as inextricably linked as oil and canvas
moscardini, an art history student and former undercover narcotics agent, works full time on recovering the stolen art of galleries, museums and patrons. his contacts are interpol, the u.s. customs service, art associations and the art underworld, along with an unspecified number of paid informants
he's part of an elite fraternity of full-time art sleuths, who range in number to perhaps a half-dozen, depending on the criteria used to define them
since moving more than four years ago from the dim back alleys of undercover drugs to the grand halls and cozy galleries of the art world, the 42-year-old detective has created something of a name for himself
among the artworks he's recovered was a $500,000 joan miro. ``my best piece was a $1 million renoir,'' he says
he's great,'' says elizabeth hayt-atkins, director of art theft archives at the new york-based international foundation for art research. ``he plays the part of the knowledgeable art person very well. he knows the lingo. he knows the artists. so i imagine when he goes undercover he's perfectly plausible.''
moscardini looks the part: trim, impeccably groomed down to his manicured nails, articulate and art-wise. the only give-away that he's anything but a connoisseur is the 9mm semi-automatic that hangs from his lizard-skin belt
the same gun as james bond used,'' he quips
and he knows the role
a frequent weekend visitor to new york's metropolitan museum of art, because it's ``one of those places you have to go to quite often,'' moscardini himself dabbles in oils and acrylics. he also is studying for an art history degree and has lectured on museum security the last three years at the smithsonian institution
moscardini at one time wanted to be a commercial artist. he went into police work more than 19 years ago, he says, because he needed a job
when the department went looking for a savvy investigator with an art background, the computer search turned up moscardini among the possibilities
the detective is full of tales of mostly all-purpose thieves, sometimes ignorant of the art they steal or the art world, who've been snared in one of his traps, usually set up in an obliging gallery staffed with undercover officers
moscardini's own undercover work is probably over now, he says. ``i am known out there. my photo's been around.''
he estimates only 10 percent to 14 percent of stolen art worldwide is recovered
although he figures he's recovered $8 million worth of works over the years, there are millions, too, in unresolved mysteries. the most recent is the $6 million heist last month from the colnaghi art gallery, new york's biggest art steal
his small office is filled with his work and passion: file cabinets stuffed with artists' and gallery names, folders each for missing oil paintings, water colors, folk art, photography; auction books from sotheby's and christie's. breaking the monotony of the institutional-white walls, he has hung an andy warhol silk-screen print, a claude monet impression and an erte art deco poster. a family heirloom chinese brass vase sits on a file cabinet
i don't consider myself just a cop. i consider myself a part of the art world,'' moscardini said. affiliation to democrat</note>
members of the mormon tabernacle choir and church president and prophet ezra taft benson attended the inauguration of arizona gov. evan mecham, himself a former mormon bishop. mecham's beliefs are closely tied to church doctrine; his ties to church leadership strong. so when a storm of turmoil engulfed the governor, arizona's mormon community found itself at the center
steve benson has been a life-long mormon, active in church affairs. he is the grandson of church president and prophet ezra taft benson. few would question his devotion
few, except impeached gov. evan mecham and some of his supporters
benson happens to be the award-winning cartoonist for the arizona republic _ and a relentless critic of the embattled governor. mecham happens to be arizona's first mormon governor and an unwavering believer in conservative church doctrine
in arizona these days, politics and religion are mixing in the mormon community. mormon critics of mecham have been scorned by other mormons, who say they are not true to their religion. mecham even once told steve benson his salvation was in jeopardy because of the biting cartoons
sides have been taken and swords drawn,'' said the cartoonist. ``there have been instances of shunning. letters have been written questioning one's devotion to the church _ whether one has the moral rectitude to remain in the flock.''
with the turmoil have come fears that the brouhaha will damage the image of mormons, whose roots trace back to the settling of arizona
officially, the church has remained neutral on the governor's plight. some members say the only mentions of mecham from the pulpit have been reminders of neutrality, and the strife is limited to a small group of mormons
is the church worried? i think not. it's a matter that will pass in the next few months,'' said phoenix attorney dave udall, a church leader designated as the official spokesman
still, individuals within the community say passions run deep. some say families have been split by the issues
ed pagan, a mormon who is a history graduate student at the university of arizona and who criticized mecham in a letter to the editor, called the turmoil ``gut-wretching'' for church members
in a sense, his platform and ideology have the veneer of unofficial church position,'' said pagan, whose criticism drew letters questioning his own faith. ``there are those who say if you criticize mecham, you're ultimately criticizing god.''
an unofficial church newspaper, the latter-day sentinel, has supported mecham, and its editor, crismon lewis, is a sharp critic of the republic's benson. ``most of the church is extremely disappointed in him,'' lewis said
one cartoon that rankled mecham's mormon supporters showed an angel atop the mormon temple in salt lake city, utah. at the end of the angel's trumpet was a banner reading, ``resign, ev.''
some remember the controversy that surrounded benson's grandfather during eight years as agriculture secretary under president eisenhower
his grandfather was attacked so much by the press that he offered his resignation, but eisenhower kept him,'' said lewis. ``now, a couple of decades later, you've got the grandson doing the same thing.''
benson says his grandfather, a personal friend of mecham's, has never pressured him to back off. church-related pressure in arizona, he said, comes from an ultra-conservative sect of the church _ not the mainstream
some individuals _ and it's not unique to my religion _ unavoidably mix religion with politics and as a result think any mormon who does not agree with a fellow latter-day saint who happens to be governor is endangering his position in the church,'' benson said
it's intolerant, and it's silly.''
and benson has support among mormons _ even among some who support the governor
he's got his job to do,'' said democratic state rep. jack brown, who voted against mecham's impeachment. ``he can do that and still be a good member of the mormon church.''
mecham, a 63-year-old native of duchesne, utah, was impeached feb. 5 by the arizona house of representatives on allegations of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan, misusing $80,000 from a special fund and attempting to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat involving a state official
trial on the impeachment is under way in the state senate. if convicted, mecham would be removed from office. he also faces a criminal trial on the campaign loan charge march 22, and a recall election set for may 17
the ultra-conservative governor took office 14 months ago and immediately plunged himself into controversy by rescinding the martin luther king holiday for state workers and making statements that have offended women, homosexuals, jews and japanese
mormons believe church leaders receive divine guidance, and some mecham backers have suggested political leaders do as well. mecham himself has occassionally suggested he's received guidance from god
to shirley whitlock, active in the church and state leader of a conservative political group called the eagle forum, mormons who don't support mecham have lost their religion
i feel if there are other members of the church who do not support the governor they either have allowed themselves to be propagandized or are too liberal and don't understand their own teachings,'' mrs. whitlock said
if members of the church can't see this man is trying to do his duty, then there's false belief,'' she said. ``if they don't support the governor when he supports constitutional principles, then they better do more studying.''
passions ran high in the legislature, too, as the impeachment vote neared. rep. brown, a former mormon bishop, said he received letters from followers who tried to intimidate him
rep. mark killian, a conservative republican from mesa, a popular mormon area and site of the church's arizona temple, broke into tears as he blasted the governor's behavior, but voted against the impeachment because he didn't believe the evidence was strong enough
udall, the arizona church spokesman, said he cringes when mecham's religion is brought into the debate
is religion really a factor? i don't think it is,'' he said. ``and we'd prefer not to be getting the attention.''
brown said he worries about possible damage to the church
but i think people basically understand that you have different kinds of people in the church, and some are not reflective of the whole group,'' he said
it's a concern,'' said wayne arnett, an attorney and mormon. ``there will be those who know mecham is a mormon and think less of me because i'm a mormon.''
most mormons, mesa bishop bob goodman said, ``are sorry the church has been involved in it.''
but i can't say it's hurt any of my members,'' goodman said. ``and i can't say it's hurt the church. the church is just too strong for that.''
scott mccartney is the ap southwest regional reporter, based in dallas. guitarist to matt bissonette, reflecting personnel change made by band.</note>
the child in david lee roth is taking plenty of toys on his next trip: a 28-foot flying surfboard; a huge banner featuring bikini-clad women; and a regulation-size, red, white and blue everlast boxing ring
but this is no ordinary summer vaction for the shaggy-haired rock star with the trademark scream. it's a concert tour, and the playthings are meant to wow audiences for the next nine months in arenas from australia to new york
music should look like it sounds, no matter what kind of music it is,'' roth said in a recent interview. ``a lot of times this music sounds like something thundering up out of the floorboards or raining down from the heavens. sometimes it's like rolling waves of sound. and what's a wave without somebody to surf it?''
despite the props and an endless stream of jokes, roth is a shrewd businessman. he knows the gimmicks will bring attention to his craft _ rock 'n' roll
there's a lot of aerial tricks, but it's all built around the music. the band is doing more musical gymnastics than you've ever heard a rock band do,'' he said
roth, 32, is touring to promote his third solo album, ``skyscraper.'' the record, which includes the single, ``just like paradise,'' marks the first time he has tried on the producer's hat. his tour began on march 4 in lakeland, fla
i wanted to try something different,'' roth said. ``always in the back of my mind i had thought about producing. but i wouldn't try a flight like this unless i had the tools and the know-how to do it, and i didn't feel secure with that until fairly recently.''
the comic book-like showman spoke about his tour, with his long, blond hair tied back in a ponytail, wearing camouflage pants and a torn t-shirt, sitting in the second row of his rehearsal hall. he was careful not to reveal too many of the tour's surprises
during the band's moment of patriotism, i climb a ladder to the ceiling of the arena _ jeez, i don't want to give it all away,'' he said, but added, ``it's death-defying stuff.''
roth's hometown is bloomington, ind., but he moved to pasadena, calif., when he was about 12 and has lived there ever since. as a child, he was inspired by television. he said he figured if all these people were entertaining him on television, maybe he could be some kind of entertainer, too
the influences which led him to music ran the gamut of groups and styles
if i say to you deep purple was a big inspiration to me and so were the ohio players, you'd say, `oh, that's where dave got his scream from, deep purple!' no, no, no, i got the scream from the ohio players, i got the haircut from deep purple.''
he began his career after meeting eddie and alex van halen and michael anthony at pasadena city college. the four formed van halen, a band that set the standard for many heavy-metal bands to come, especially because of eddie's innovative guitar playing, and roth's wild-man antics
the group split up in 1985, and roth moved on to a solo career. his new band includes lead guitarist steve vai, bass guitarist matt bissonette, drummer gregg bissonette and keyboardist brett tuggle
roth's international tour will include some of the old van halen standards, in addition to his solo efforts, including a remake of the beach boy's ``california girls'' and the bluesy ``just a gigolo.''
in his spare time, roth climbs mountains, as seen on the ``just like paradise'' video in which he scales a 3,000-foot-high vertical wall of granite. he said he may be reverting to his childhood, because he got the climbing bug when he was a boy scout. climbing is a kind of therapy for him
you know, the most scariest place you can put yourself in has the most calming effect.''
although experienced, he says the hobby has not made him want to conquer mountains such as mount everest
something like that is a hyper-commitment,'' he said. ``i need all of my toes in order to jump around with great abandon. inevitably, you're going to lose a finger or a toe on a trip like that. somebody checks out early. taking that kind of risk is not my interest. the music gives me enough of that kind of adventure. fooling around with my career burns enough calories.''
roth also fools around with martial arts, receiving a black belt in karate about nine years ago. at one point he experimented with kick boxing. these days, he incorporates both disciplines in his stage show
martial arts has a lot of visceral impact. you can feel it _ pow! and combining it with the music, 10,000 people say, `oh, did you feel that?'''
despite his devil-may-care manner, roth is definitely a success. two previous albums have sold more that 1 million copies, certifying them as platinum, and ``skyscraper'' is well on its way. this does not include his revenues from the six van halen lps that share the same honor
a lot of what stands for success in rock 'n' roll or showbiz after a while seems like so many little trophies and prizes along the way,'' he said. ``if there's any real glory to be had it's in legend.''
all kidding aside, he insists the money he's made is not for things, but rather experiences. he said experiences provide better memories
if anything, roth's whole career is built around making a single point, getting across a single message:
there's a very definite message in all of this music. people say, `dave, what's the message?' that's it. imagination. take a chance. not just take your best shot, that's too dependable.''
sales by the nation's largest general retailers were unexpectedly slow in february, prompting worries that year-old sluggishness in the retail sector has yet to run its course
the nation's largest retailer, sears, roebuck and co., said thursday its sales rose 2.5 percent from february 1987. k mart said its overall sales were up 0.8 percent, but sales at stores open at least a year fell 1.6 percent
the results do not bode well for the economy,'' said fred wintzer, a retail industry analyst for the investment firm alex. brown &amp; sons inc
led by industry-leader general motors corp., automakers sold 25 percent more domestic cars and light trucks in late february than a year ago, the car companies have reported
gm said thursday its sales during the last third of february were the highest for late february since 1972
in the seven selling days from feb. 21-29, gm sold 127,549 domestic cars, up 33.4 percent from a year ago, and 59,709 domestic light trucks, up 46.2 percent from a year ago
chrysler motors corp. has decided not to sell its acustar inc. parts-making subsidiary but says it will close or sell four plants within the next 18 months
the no. 3 automaker said thursday that the four plants _ amplex van wert in van wert, ohio, trenton chemical in suburban detroit, detroit forge and detroit trim _ employ about 2,000 workers
the united auto workers union said it was pleased by the decision but urged chrysler to find ways not to close the four plants
improvements in the nation's efficiency in churning out goods and services slowed by almost half last year despite revised figures showing higher output in the the fourth quarter, the government said
the labor department said thursday that productivity among non-farm businesses responsible for three-fourths of the nation's economic activity rose at an annual rate of 0.3 percent in the fourth quarter in contrast to a deterioration of 0.2 percent reported in preliminary figures last month
the revisions raised the productivity improvement for the entire year from 0.8 percent to 0.9 percent, slightly more than half the 1.6 percent gain of 1986, despite the lowest hourly labor cost increases in more than four decades
the democratic-controlled house labor standards subcommittee has voted along party lines to increase the minimum wage from $3.35 to $4.65 an hour over the next three years
the 6-3 vote thursday came on a measure to raise the minimum wage 50 cents an hour on jan. 1, 1989 and 40 cents an hour each of the following years
president reagan's sanctions against japanese electronics imports have halted computer chip ``dumping'' but have failed to boost sales of u.s. chips in japan, according to an industry group
the semiconductor industry association said thursday that by the end of 1987, the u.s. share of the japanese chip market was 10 percent, up only slightly from the 9 percent share that existed when the sanctions were announced last april
batus inc. has raised its hostile bid for controlling interest in farmers group inc., coming up with a $4.5 billion offer for the nation's seventh largest insurer
the $63-per-share proposal was made thursday as a tender offer to farmers' shareholders instead of to the board of directors because the board ``has regrettably refused to talk to us so far,'' said batus chairman patrick sheehy
the los angeles-based insurance concern had rejected the louisville company's initially proposed $60-a-share, or $4.2 billion, buyout offer on jan. 20
a group led by a british construction firm has launched an unsolicited tender offer for koppers co. inc. that values the construction and chemicals company at about $1.3 billion
the pittsburgh-based koppers declined to comment on thursday's offer, but traders on wall street speculated the bidding might go higher by sending the price of koppers' stock well above the $45 a share offer to $51.75 a share
the bid was made by a concern called bns inc., whose biggest shareholder is beazer plc, a london-based general construction company that owns 49 percent
major airlines have raised fares for the second time in about two weeks, reflecting unexpected strength in passenger traffic despite the usually slow winter season
the latest move was initiated thursday by continental airlines, which boosted one-way regular coach fares in amounts ranging from $7 for short flights to $45 for longer trips
american, united and northwest airlines immediately announced they would match continental's regular coach-fare increases in markets where they compete
the transportation department has proposed a wide range of drug tests for more than a half million airline employees from pilots to mechanics, although officials said they have no clear evidence of a drug problem in the industry
thursday's announcement of the drug testing program, which would go into effect after what may be a lengthy rulemaking process, came amid conflicting court cases on whether such tests are legal. a federal judge earlier this week declared random drug tests of civilian army employees as unconstitutional
usair says it has agreed to buy 50 boeing 737 jetliners with options for 30 additional aircraft, a deal worth $2.4 billion if all the options are exercised
delivery of the new jets will begin in april 1989 and continue through december 1991, the airline said thursday
the twin-engine, short-to-medium range aircraft is the most popular jet ever sold by seattle-based boeing co. the deal with usair brings to 2,001 boeing 737s on order
stock prices were mixed thursday in an inconclusive session marked by intense takeover speculation and some selling of blue chips. the dow jones average of 30 big-name industrials slipped 7.80 to 2,063.49
bond prices barely budged in lethargic trading
the dollar ended mixed against most key currencies, while gold prices fell. some cattle futures prices plunged the 1{-cent limit allowed for daily trading, and grain and soybean futures and energy futures also fell
bearish sentiment has sparked a selloff that sent oil and gasoline futures prices skidding lower
on the new york mercantile exchange thursday, contracts for april delivery of west intermediate crude oil settled at $15.50 per 42-gallon barrel, down 17 cents. the april contract also declined in wednesday's trading
among refined products traded on the exchange, april contracts for wholesale no. 2 heating oil also fell, dropping 1.04 cent to 42.89 cents a gallon, and wholesale unleaded regular gasoline slipped .50 cent to 44.40 cents a gallon
the market rallied during morning trading but was unable to sustain the advance, said madison galbraith, senior energy specialist with merrill lynch energy futures
there was no news to support the rally, and profit-taking amid the market's continuing bearish sentiment eroded the advance and caused prices to continue to fall, galbraith said
lending some support to the market was trader nervousness about continuing the selloff below the level of $15.50 for crude, galbraith said
the government's planned sale of the electricity industry in england and wales is by far the biggest and most controversial venture so far in prime minister margaret thatcher's huge privatization program
critics predict poorer service and higher prices, and question the wisdom of putting nuclear power stations in private hands
supporters insist it will produce better service, with safeguards built on the lessons of past privatizations
but investors weighing this debate also harbor big financial concerns. in the wake of october's stock market crash, britons burned by the sell-offs of british gas plc and british telecommunications plc shares understandably are wary of buying into another public utility
the stock offering of the electric company _ now a state body run by the central electricity generating board _ is to be debated march 7 in parliament, and the energy department already is taking steps to fend off criticism
privatizing the electricity industry has been likened to trying to grasp a porcupine,'' the sunday times commented
the complex sale will take two to three years and could raise more money than the entire 16.5 billion pounds, or about $29 billion, raised from all the other state-owned companies sold since mrs. thatcher's conservatives were elected in 1979 promising to roll back socialism in britain
the city, london's financial district, expects the electricity sale to raise from $26 billion to $47 billion
less controversial have been the sales of non-utility companies, such as british airways plc and rolls-royce plc, the airplane engine maker
mrs. thatcher's goal has been to make these companies more competitive and to get more britons to become shareholders. the share-owning public has tripled to 8.5 million in 10 years, the government says
the objections have been to the privatization of monopolies intact without the intention of introducing competition,'' said dieter helm, a research fellow at the london business school
critics also complain that british gas and british telecom were insufficiently regulated when they went private in 1986 and 1984 respectively. consequently, they claim, gas and telephone prices have risen while service has deteriorated
some britons also say they feel less secure without government control over such vital public services. in the electricity sale, critics fear higher prices, deteriorating service and poor security for nuclear stations. labor unions fear job losses
helm said there also were questions over whether the capital markets could absorb all the stock to be sold
moreover, he said, nuclear disasters in recent years at three mile island in the united states and at the chernobyl plant in the soviet union ``increase uncertainty about whether people really want to hold shares in this kind of firm.''
the sale is opposed by lord marshall, chairman of the central electricity generating board, who says the plan is unlikely to serve the consumer's interests
lawmaker john prescott of the opposition labor party attacked the plan as ``a triumph of ideology over common sense,'' and accused the government of selling off assets to finance tax cuts
the government structured the sale defensively, addressing some of the issues raised by the gas and phone selloffs. it set up two competing generating companies and promised to implement regulation that will protect britain's security and consumers' rights
for example, energy secretary cecil parkinson plans rebates for dissatisfied consumers _ a privilege not granted to british telecom users
tony boorman, deputy director of the watchdog electricity consumers' council, called regulatory safeguards ``a welcome change.''
we've always believed that at least in the short term, the structure of the industry has less relevance to the customer than the regulation,'' he said
more than 30 years ago, life magazine took a look at the burgeoning little desert town of las vegas and wondered if it wasn't overbuilt
the year was 1955 and five new resort hotels had just opened, prompting the magazine to question where they would get people to fill them
has las vegas pushed its luck too far?'' life asked
history has proven doubters to be wrong. las vegas has grown from a dusty town of a few resorts into a booming metropolis of more than 600,000 people, with nearly 60,000 hotel and motel rooms to accomodate tourists
now, as las vegas undergoes one of the most ambitious of its periodic building booms, there are few who believe that overbuilding is a problem. tourism is growing and the gaming and resort industries are attempting to capitalize on the trend
there is still a tremendous amount of demand out there that hasn't been satisified,'' said rossi ralenkotter, director of marketing for the las vegas convention and visitors authority. ``we're in a very strong growth pattern and all indications are that it will continue.''
nearly 20,000 new hotel rooms either are under construction or awaiting groundbreaking, as resorts compete to add rooms they hope will bring in even more tourists and gamblers in the near future
part of that optimism is based on figures showing hotels averaged 90.2 percent occupancy during 1987. such extremely high rates meant potential guests often were turned away by a lack of rooms: on weekends, it is nearly impossible to get a room and on three-day holiday weekends it's even worse
visitor volume nearly has doubled in the last 12 years, with an estimated 17 million tourists each expected to spend an average of 2-3 days in las vegas during 1988
gaming revenues kept pace, growing 14 percent in 1987 to a record $2.74 billion in southern nevada
we're penetrating markets we've never penetrated before,'' said dave verbon, publicity director at the riviera hotel. ``there are vast numbers of people out there we never tried to reach before and now we're going after them and getting them.''
already boasting the world's two largest resort hotels, las vegas soon will have five hotel-casinos with more than 3,000 rooms apiece. two resorts _ the riviera and the flamingo hilton _ are about to begin work on expansions that will bring them to more than 4,000 rooms apiece
the riviera opened a new 1,000-room highrise march 1 and plans to begin construction of a 1,700-room tower in the fall
you have to build towers to have a very high volume of business to drive a large casino with a large number of slot machines and blackjack tables,'' said verbon. ``we think there are enough potential customers to support these huge hotels.''
the centerpiece of the new construction is the golden nugget, a massive resort rising from a desert parcel adjacent to caesars palace. when finished sometime late next year, the $550 million resort will have 3,200 guest rooms set in a watery tropical setting that hotel officials claim will be like nothing las vegas has ever seen
it's really on a completely different plane in terms of what we presently have,'' said nugget president bobby baldwin. ``it's very difficult to compare the new nugget to anything.''
baldwin says he has few worries that the nugget will be able to fill its rooms with gamblers and tourists. the company's downtown resort regularly sells out its rooms
we're very bullish,'' he said. ``tour and travel continues to grow and the individual traveler market continues to expand, particularly from southern california. international business has also expanded in the last few months and we hope to see that continue.''
the tourism economy has been helped by the growth in three-day weekends and a national trend toward mini-vacations of 2-3 days. las vegas has also been very successful in landing conventions, which attracted 1.6 million people to the city in 1987
part of the las vegas lure also comes from room rates that average $45 a night, far below the $100 or more charged by non-gaming hotels in other cities
it's the bargain aspect, the ability to have a very enjoyable convention or vacation visit at far less expense than any other destination,'' said ralenkotter
the city's hotels in the past four to five years have begun exploiting the vast middle-class and tourism markets they once eschewed in favor of attracting a handful of high-rolling gamblers
the expanded customer base, hotel operators believe, gives them protection against a recession or sudden rise in fuel prices that could have a negative impact on tourism levels
in the early 1980s, a national recession combined with high fuel prices and the legalization of gambling in atlantic city stopped the las vegas growth rate in its tracks
in good times everybody does pretty well and the better operators do even better,'' said baldwin. ``in bad times good operators don't do quite as well but they still do well. the best operators do great in both times.'' 1987</head>
the best-liked commercials of 1987 included some starring performances from animated characters such as dancing clay raisins, a hamburger chain's moonman and a pizza company's dreaded foil called a noid
few of the commercials mentioned most often by consumers polled by video storyboard tests inc. featured traditional show business celebrities, the head of the consumer research firm said thursday
we seem to heading into a period when we see more created celebrities, not necessarily human beings, in commercials,'' said david vadehra, president of video storyboard, in relasing the results of the firm's 10th annual survey
he said that may be partly due to growing dissatisfaction with the costs and risks associated with using celebrities. the trend occurs even as admakers for some cars, office phone systems, computers and insurance products have tried to replicate realistic situations and dialogue in their commercials
video storyboard, which is based in new york, interviewed more than 25,000 people about what commercials they liked best last year
leading the list was the campaign for california raisins, which used clay models of raisins dancing to the sounds of motown music in a construction worker's lunchbox and across the kitchen counter
the ads took top billing despite relatively modest spending of $5.4 million to put them on television. the survey said makers of other well-liked ads spent as much as $344 million (mcdonald's corp.) on television placements
second was bud light beer commercials, many of which featured the english bull terrier spuds mackenzie while others offered numerous variations of what can go wrong if you simply order a ``light'' without specifying the brand
the ad campaign for pepsi soft drinks placed third, and miller lite beer commercials were fourth
ads for mcdonald's restaurants came in fifth. the campaign included some commercials that featured a piano-playing character shaped like a moon crescent who extolled dinner at mcdonald's to the tune from ``mac the knife.''
the stars of sixth-ranked bartles &amp; jaymes wine cooler ads are a pair of non-actors who were persuaded to pose as the brand's owners
ads for coca-cola soft drinks, which placed seventh, include some with the computer-generated character max headroom
rounding out the top 10 were ads for isuzu automobiles, dupont carpeting and domino's pizza, which features an animated clay character called the noid
consumers didn't turn completely sour on celebrity-filled ads. jell-o dessert ads with actor bill cosby placed 11th. but cosby couldn't keep kodak film from dropping off the list of the 25 most popular campaigns
another casualty in 1987 was burger king advertising, which fell out of the top 25 for the first time in five years with advertising billing it as ``the best food for fast times.'' the chain recently dumped the theme, changed ad agencies and is pitching the taste of its flame-broiled hamburgers in new ads
another hamburger chain, wendy's, placed 12th with an ad campaign that spoofed taste tests by having customers pick a pre-cooked hamburger over a freshly cooked wendy's burger for some very strange reasons
next were campaigns for levi's jeans, kibbles 'n bits dog food, seagrams wine coolers, michelob beer and oscar meyer meats
the partnership for drug-free america, a campaign aimed at discouraging illegal drug use, was the first public service campaign to place in the top 25, finishing 18th
rounding out the top 25 were ads for chevrolet cars, lucky dog dog food, angel soft tissue, energizer batteries, sprite soft drinks, tender chops dog food and long john silver restaurants
koppers co. inc., a huge construction and chemicals concern, has offered no reply to an unsolicited $1.3 billion takeover bid from a group led by a major british contruction company and a u.s. investment firm
but traders on wall street seem to think the bidding might go higher, and sent the price of koppers' stock well above the $45 a share offer
koppers rose $6.62{ a share to close at $51.75 on thursday on the new york stock exchange. it was the sixth most-actively traded stock with 3.1 million shares changing hands
the tender offer for koppers was launched thursday by a concern called bns inc., whose biggest shareholder is beazer plc, a london-based general construction company that owns 49 percent of bns
other participants in bns are subsidiaries of shearson lehman hutton inc., a new york-based investment firm that reportedly owns about 46 percent of bns, and natwest investment bank ltd., a british investment bank
affiliates of bns already own nearly 2.1 million shares, or about 7.45 percent of koppers' outstanding common stock, the company said
based on koppers' nearly 28.6 million common shares outstanding, the tender offer would be worth a total of about $1.29 billion
several securities analysts said koppers, which recently completed a restructuring that shed several engineering and metals products businesses over the past three years, was worth more than the offered price
its main businesses now are construction materials and services, which mainly involve road construction, and chemical and allied products
bns indicated that it planned to sell the chemicals and allied products business if its tender offer is successful
robert kanters, senior vice president for the stock brokerage legg mason masten in pittsburgh, said koppers holds ``a commanding position in aggregates and the coal-based chemicals businesses'' and may be worth $55- to $60-a-share
aggregates are the rock mixtures used in road and bridge construction. among koppers' coal-based chemicals products are substances used to treat lumber
fred siemer, who follows the chemicals business for the firm chemical research, said beazer probably is attracted to koppers' quarries, which are essential to roadbuilding. koppers said it operates about 150 quarries in 20 states
beazer has been expanding rapidly in recent years. it bought gifford-hill &amp; co., a cement-maker based in dallas, in 1986; and also operates phillips builders in nashville, tenn., tidewater construction co. in norfolk, va., and cohn communities in atlanta
the bid is conditioned on, among other things, koppers stockholders tendering a majority of the company's common shares, approval by the non-management directors of koppers, approval by beazer's shareholders and the bidding group's satisfaction that certain elements of delaware antitakeover laws are invalid
the offer expires at midnight march 30 unless extended
brian c. beazer, chairman of beazer plc, told koppers' chairman, charles r. pullin, in a letter, ``we plan to operate koppers as an independent autonomous business and we have no plans to move the headquarters from pittsburgh.''
bns said shearson had agreed to provide $465 million in financing for the offer and that citibank had indicated to arrange additional financing
koppers reported its profit for 1987 fell to $10.2 million, or 36 cents share, from $74.1 million, or $2.59 a share, a year earlier. the results included a charge of $59.4 million in 1987 due to settlement of a lawsuit
revenue rose to $1.52 billion from $1.4 billion in 1986
beazer said it earned $82.8 million on sales of $1.7 billion in its latest fiscal year, which ended last june 30
here are the overall sales reported thursday by the nation's nine largest retailers, for february, the first month of the fiscal year
the 10th largest, r.h. macy &amp; co., is privately held and does not report monthly sales figures
