otis spunkmeyer inc. is wagering a few million cookies that it has goodyear out-blimped when it comes to midair advertising
the gourmet baking company embarks today on a sky tours business featuring a vintage 1945 dc-3, hoping to capture the romance of aviation's golden era along with the hearts and wallets of well-heeled customers
kenneth rawlings, chairman and chief executive officer of otis spunkmeyer, sees the tour business as a can't-miss proposition: even if planefuls of customers don't line up for hour-long flights at $75 a pop _ or $1,200 to charter the entire 18-seat aircraft _ the promotional value is high
we look at it as our goodyear blimp,'' rawlings said, noting that a 95-foot-long sign bearing the company's name under the wing should grab the attention of ground-bound consumers
we're just trying to find a way of flying it full at the same time we're promoting our product.''
the company inaugurated its ``sentimental journeys'' venture on thursday, whisking press and invited guests on half-hour trips around san francisco bay in the two-propeller airplane, complete with champagne and crew in 1940s style uniforms
otis spunkmeyer, which expects $30 million in sales over the next 12 months, bought the dc-3 for $165,000 two months ago
rawlings took his first airplane ride on a dc-3 as a child and says he's been mulling over the sky tours idea for some time. last summer he decided to go ahead with it after his wife linda _ the company president and a white-knuckle flier _ accompanied him on a commercial dc-3 flight from cape cod to boston and was lulled to sleep by its comfort
victory lap inc., the spunkmeyer subsidiary that operates the tours, has spiffed up the inside of its dc-3 and offers deluxe limousine service as well
inside the plane, crew members wear 1940s-style uniforms, the in-flight music features doris day and glenn miller, and stewardesses distribute champagne, gourmet hors d'oeuvres and _ of course _ cookies as the slow but steady aircraft flies past the golden gate bridge at 1,500 feet
the dc-3 revolutionized air travel in comfort and safety, and accounted for 90 percent of the world's airline traffic in 1939. rawlings estimates there are more than 1,000 of them still operating, mostly flying cargo in other countries
aviation historian ed davies of nearby millbrae, calif., said he believed the dc-3 venture was the first of its kind
if the tours venture is successful, rawlings envisions a fleet of refurbished dc-3s serving the nation's major metropolitan areas, starting with seattle, san diego or los angeles
such a move would mark a new chapter for san leandro-based otis spunkmeyer, founded by rawlings in 1977 as a california chain of fresh-baked cookie stores. the company moved into selling frozen gourmet cookie dough wholesale in 1983 and now employs 250 people
only about a quarter of mexico's creditor banks submitted bids in a unique debt-for-securities swap aimed at reducing the nation's $105 billion foreign debt, according to the treasury department
the government said thursday it had accepted 55 percent of the $6.7 billion in bids that 139 creditor banks submittd under the swap plan, which has been hailed by some as a major new initiative in dealing with troubled third world debtors
under the plan, the government will issue over $2.5 billion in new, 20-year bonds to its creditor banks to replace $3.66 billion in old bank debt, a swap that will save mexico over $2.6 billion over 20 years
mexico had invited its international bank creditors to trade their mexican loans at a discount for the 20-year bonds, which are backed by u.s. treasury securities
the plan unveiled last december was seen as a way of reducing the banks' exposures to troubled mexican loans while minimizing the impact on the banks' ledgers from having to write down the value of those loans
but there were indications when the plan was announced that a number of major foreign lenders would not participate. citibank, for example, indicated it was satisfied with its loan portfolio and viewed the swaps instead as a way for banks to get out of third world lending
mexico's approximately 560 creditor banks had until feb. 25 to submit their sealed bids to morgan guaranty trust co., which acted as exchange agent for the plan
of the $6.7 billion in bids received from 139 creditor banks, mexico accepted bids representing $3.66 billion in old loans at an average discount exchange rate of just over 69 cents on the dollar, the treasury department said
the remaining 45 percent of the bids were rejected because they sought a price for the old debt that was higher than that sought by the government, the department said
by agreeing to issue the $2.557 billion in new bonds, mexico will reduce its debt principal by $1.108 billion. it also will save $1.537 billion in interest over the 20-year term of the bonds, for a total savings of $2.645 billion
the government will back the bond issue by buying $520 million in zero-coupon u.s. treasury bonds. it had been prepared to invest up to $2 billion to purchase up to $10 billion of the u.s. securities
the department did not identify the banks which had bids accepted or detail the amounts
it did state that the government would continue ``to actively explore new mechanisms to reduce its external debt.''
it is hoped that in the future...international financial organizations can play a more active role in designing and assisting other solutions to alleviate the weight of the debt,'' the department stated
robert j. birnbaum is stepping down as president and chief operating officer of the new york stock exchange when his contract expires at the end of may and will be succeeded by executive vice president richard a. grasso
birnbaum, 60, who became nyse president in 1985 after eight years as president of the american stock exchange, said in a statement thursday that he is ``interested in pursuing other interests and opportunities,'' including membership on corporate boards and possibly an association with a major law firm
his successor, grasso, 41, is a 20-year veteran of the nyse who has served as its executive vice president for capital markets since 1986 and is a member of the exchange's management committee
there was no indication that birnbaum's departure was related to the oct. 19 stock market collapse, when the nyse was strained to the breaking point by the plunge in prices and an unprecedented volume of trading
nyse chairman john j. phelan jr. stated that ``bob birnbaum has been a valuable asset to the new york stock exchange during one of the most turbulent periods in its history
his many years of experience in operations and extensive knowledge of securities industry issues contributed significantly to the nyse's ability to operate smoothly and efficiently during the market crisis,'' phelan said
grasso is known for his expertise with the exchange's computers and communications systems, which are becoming increasingly critical. he is responsible for upgrades of the systems that will allow the nyse to manage volume of 600 million shares a day by june as efficiently as it manages 225 million shares currently
in an interview, grasso said the exchange is working with member firms to remove bottlenecks so that the whole trading system will be able to handle 600 million shares a day _ the record volume of last oct. 19 and 20
i can't give you the categorical statement that all 600 member firms will be at the point where we will be by june, but progress is being made,'' grasso said
phelan said in a statement that ``it is imperative that the president and chief operating officer of the nyse be thoroughly familiar with these systems.''
the nyse said grasso was designated by the board of directors on thursday and would be formally elected on june 2
southland corp. announced the sale of its reddy ice operation to the investment firm kaminski-engles capital corp. for an undisclosed amount of cash
reddy ice is the world's largest producer of fragmentary ice and operates seven plants in texas, florida and nevada
most reddy ice employees will be retained after the sale, said officials with dallas-based kaminski-engles
southland also said it plans to divest its snack foods and chemical-food labs divisions and other retail operations
southland, the parent company of 7-eleven convenience stores, plans major asset sales to help pay off debt incurred in its $4.9 billion leveraged buyout. the company on tuesday announced the sale of 473 7-eleven stores in 10 states to circle k corp., its chief competitor, 
unexpected strength in passenger traffic during a typically weak travel season has prompted major airlines to raise fares twice in recent weeks
continental airlines initiated the latest move on thursday, boosting one-way regular coach fares in amounts ranging from $7 for short flights to $45 for longer trips
continental also tightened restrictions on some of its discount fares used by business travelers, effective march 15. they will have to book tickets four to seven days in advance and pay a 25 percent cancellation or change penalty
american, united and northwest airlines immediately announced they would match continental's regular coach-fare increases in markets where they compete. other carriers were expected to do likewise
under the revised fare structure, for example, a one-way regular coach ticket from new york to denver rose from $350 to $395. a one-way coach ticket from newark, n.j., to rochester, n.y rose from $118 to $125
last month, airlines raised their deepest discount fares by about $10 per round trip, partly because of surprisingly higher passenger traffic. in january airline traffic rose about 4 percent, more than most industry analysts had expected. february traffic also appeared to be strong
american, for example, reported a 25.7 percent jump in passenger traffic for the month over a year earlier and said it flew a record 4.61 billion revenue passenger miles. a revenue passenger mile represents one paying passenger flown one mile, an important measurement of an airline's business. continental said february traffic increased 8.8 percent over a year earlier
airline traffic ordinarily slows in the winter, which prompts carriers to woo travelers with fare-cuts. concern about a winter slump intensified after the october stock market crash, which raised fears that leisure and business travel would decline
industry analysts have attributed the surprisingly strong growth in airline traffic to eased concern about the impact of the stock crash. they also say the dollar's lower value has attracted thousands of europeans to the united states, where they can exploit the buying power of their stronger currencies
the fare increases announced thursday helped boost airline stocks on wall street, reflecting an investor belief that earnings would benefit if greater numbers of passengers are paying more money to fly
delta air lines rose 87{ cents to $48.87{; amr, parent of american, rose $2.12{ to $42.12{; nwa, parent of northwest, rose $1.12{ to $44.75, and allegis, parent of united, rose $1.25 to $77
batus inc. said it launched a $4.5 billion hostile tender offer for farmers group inc. because the insurance giant's board of directors declined to negotiate over batus' earlier $4.2 billion proposal
batus began the $63 a share offer on thursday, sweetening its initial unsolicited $60 a share proposal that farmers had rejected on jan. 20 as inadequate
a spokesman for los angeles-based farmers, the nation's seventh-largest insurer, said that while the farmers board would consider the higher price, ``this highly conditional offer changes very little.''
wall street reacted to the latest development by sending the price of farmers' stock up 75 cents _ to $62.75 per share _ on the over-the-counter market
in a statement, batus chairman patrick sheehy said the tender offer ``represents a pemium of 47 percent over the $43 price at which farmers' shares closed on the day before our initial proposal.''
he said batus would be willing to meet farmers' directors at any time to discuss all terms of the proposal
one new york analyst, who has followed the maneuvering, said batus' latest attempt ``may be a ploy to get some action out of farmers. they have been sitting there ignoring everything that is done.''
i wouldn't be surprised to see a further offer down the line,'' said d. gordon luce, of brown brothers harriman
other analysts had said previously that batus needed to sweeten its offer by $5 to $20 a share before farmers would consider it
the tender offer was conditioned upon batus obtaining at least 51 percent of farmers' 69 million outstanding shares and on batus gaining required state regulatory approval. the offer expires march 30
batus is a subsidiary of british-based bat industries plc, a tobacco, retailing and insurance conglomerate
batus announced last month that it had lined up a $3.2 billion revolving line of credit from an international group of banks for use in its takeover bid
after rejecting batus's $60 a share offer, farmers chairman leo denlea jr. said his shareholders would be best served if the company remained independent
farmers has about $11 billion in assets, mostly in insurance. it ranks third in the united states in home and auto insurance behind state farm and allstate and is the seventh-largest property and casualty insurance company. chairman</head>
five directors of kaisertech ltd. have filed suit against alan clore, the company's chairman, to keep him from turning over control of the board to houston financier charles hurwitz
the lawsuit, filed thursday in alameda county superior court, was the second against clore involving kaisertech in three days. on tuesday, the world's fifth-largest aluminum maker sued the british investor for illegal insider stock trading
among the minority group of directors that sued clore on thursday was retired kaiser chairman cornell maier. the suit said that clore's resignation ``is in order'' because of an alleged breach of contract
clore agreed earlier this week to sell his 32.1 percent stake in kaisertech for up to $234 million to hurwitz, who acquired pacific lumber co. in 1986
the five directors wanted clore to sell his shares more broadly. they also are concerned that all board positions expire in may
the minority directors claim clore has breached the so-called clore agreement, which gave clore the right to nominate a majority of the board in exchange for a $140 million investment last year
they said in the lawsuit that ``driven by his financial desperation and (in) violation of delaware law and his agreement with kaisertech, clore has entered into agreements with hurwitz under which clore will pretend to nominate his own (slate of directors), but in fact will nominate only those hurwitz selects.''
in plain english,'' the suit continued, ``the foregoing agreements and schemes are a sham designed to enable hurwitz to obtain board control, all without stockholder approval.''
clore and his lawyers could not be reached for comment on the suit. a representative for hurwitz, not a defendant in the complaint, said the suit is ``without merit.''
besides maier, those suing include stephen hutchcraft, corporate president under maier and now president of kaisertech's only operating subsidiary, kaiser aluminum; john beckett, retired transamerica corp. chairman and the bankamerica corp. director who helped persuade tom clausen to return as chairman of the san francisco-based bank corporation; charles lynch, chairman of dhl worldwide express in redwood city; and john merow, kaiser's former vice chairman. all but lynch were directors under maier
bond corp. holdings ltd., the australian company that bought the g. heileman brewing co. last fall, has decided to sell the brewer's bakery division, according to a letter sent to employees
michael d. moon, president of the heileman baking co., said in the letter sent thursday that the division was being offered to sale ``to a wide variety of american and international companies and investors.''
about 4,700 people are employed nationwide at the division's 12 bakeries, which have annual sales of about $350 million
moon said management had made an offer two weeks ago to buy the bakeries. ``our goal is continuity of the company and jobs for all of its people,'' he said
a federal judge has ruled that trans world airlines did not bargain in bad faith to precipitate and prolong a 1986 strike by flight attendants, a decision that could save the airline $300 million
the ruling thursday went against the independent federation of flight attendants, which represents about 5,000 twa flight attendants who were seeking reinstatement with back pay to the jobs they lost in the strike
u.s. district judge howard f. sachs rejected contentions by the union that twa and its largest shareholder, carl icahn, bargained in bad faith in violation of federal labor laws to precipitate the bitter 72-day walkout. the union demanded its jobs back with back pay at prestrike wage rates
union president vicki frankovich said she was disappointed by the judge's ruling but was ``confident we will win on appeal.''
if sachs' order is upheld upon appeal, it will lift from the airline a potential financial liability that has been accumulating at the rate of $8 million to $15 million a month since the strike began march 7, 1986
we are very pleased the court made this decision,'' icahn said. ``we try to be fair to our employees. we tried to negotiate with iffa. we are happy the court vindicated us.''
icahn said the decision would not alter twa's financial plans because ``we never put any reserves aside because we always thought we could win it.''
the walkout began after icahn bargained unsuccessfully for cost-saving concessions from the union. freed from the supervision of a federal mediator who could not resolve the differences, icahn cut flight attendant wages by 22 percent, increased working hours and changed work rules. the union struck
twa hired 2,700 new flight attendants to replace the strikers. about 1,300 attendants resigned from the union, crossed its picket lines and continued to work
on may 17, 1986, the union offered unconditionally to return to work without a contract
in one of several lawsuits it filed, the union alleged that the airline had bargained in bad faith to bring about and prolong the strike
while chastising both sides for their sometimes angry and abrasive conduct in negotiations _ particularly icahn for allegedly sexist comments _ sachs found that the actions of the airline were legal responses to economic conditions
i cannot conclude from the evidence presented that twa's bargaining was in bad faith,'' the judge wrote in his 78-page opinion
sachs said case law permitted an aggressive union to bargain for benefits that will increase an employer's costs. an aggressive employer can lawfully bargain for reductions in total expenses of a group thought to be considerably overpaid and much less productive than is feasible, he said
sachs went on to say that ``it is not a function of the court to insist that an employer cheerfully accept strike losses or show generosity in victory.'' fact. a version moving on general news wires.</note>
a flight attendants' union official said today that transportation department plans to test airline crews and ground workers for drug use would be unfair and unnecessary
but transportation secretary james burnley defended the proposal announced thursday, saying he did not want to wait until hundreds of people are killed before taking action to stop any potential problem
vicky francovich, president of the independent federation of flight attendants, said that in the 50-year history of the industry, there have been no accidents blamed on employee drug use
ms. francovich, interviewed with burnley on abc-tv's ``good morning america,'' said the department should be looking for ways to combat fatigue among overworked airline personnel and to tighten certification procedures
i think there are more responsible ways to deal with the problems,'' she said, adding that false positive drug tests could lead to an unfair stigma against an employee
while the government is not dealing with problems in the deregulated industry ... it is attacking a problem here that doesn't really exist,'' she said. ``this is not a necessary approach.''
burnley acknowledged that no airline accidents have been traced to drug use, but he cited a pittsburgh press survey showing that six hospital emergency rooms had treated 23 cockpit crew members or flight attendants for drug overdoses
burnley, who was also interviewed on ``cbs this morning,'' said one airline reported that 16 percent of job applicants for mechanics jobs were found to be using drugs and, at another airline, 6 percent of flight attendant applicants were drug users. he did not name the airlines
there is nothing beyond that anecdotal evidence that would indicate that the airline industry is somehow exempt from this problem that is plaguing all of american society, so i think it's pretty clear that we need to move in this area,'' he said
burnley said he expects a final rule to be implemented before the end of the year, despite several pending court challenges to mandatory drug testing
testing would cover the more than half a million commercial aviation employees who hold safety-senstive jobs: from pilots and flight attendants to mechanics and security workers at airport checkpoints
a fact sheet provided by the department suggested as many as 7.5 percent of the 511,000 workers who would be subject to the tests might show evidence of drug use. but burnley sought to distance himself from the estimate, saying it was included only as a means of roughly estimating the possible cost of such a program and not meant to indicate the extent of drug use in the industry
the pilots and otherairline unions promised to challenge any random drug testing rule in court once it is made final. drug testing already is the subject of numerous lawsuits and several federal courts of appeal have either upheld testing or knocked it down
we can't wait for weeks and months while these (drug testing) cases wind themselves through the courts,'' burnley said
in addition to pilots and flight attendants, the testing requirements would cover aircraft mechanics, other cockpit crew member such as flight engineers and navigators, aircraft dispatchers and security personnel who work at screening checkpoints at airports
under the proposal, employees would be subject to a pre-employment test, periodic testing whenever a person is taking a physical, post-accident testing and random testing as well as test for reasonable cause. an employee would be subject to an initial test on a sample of urine and a more sophisticated test if the first test shows the presence of drugs
japan posted an unadjusted current account surplus of $3.52 billion in january, down 27.4 percent from $4.84 billion a year earlier, the finance ministry said friday
january's surplus in the broadest measure of trade was also down from $9.44 billion in december, said finance ministry official toshio naito. the current account includes services and investment income as well as merchandise trade
when adjusted for seasonal fluctuations, the current account surplus for january stood at $8.03 billion, down from $8.71 billion a year earlier but up from an adjusted $7.47 billion in december
japan's seasonally adjusted trade surplus in january fell 19.6 percent from its level a year earlier, marking the seventh consecutive monthly decline, naito
the seasonally adjusted surplus in merchandise trade, a narrower measure, came to $4.58 billion, down from $5.70 billion last january and $10.06 billion in december, naito said. it was the seventh straight monthly decline in the trade surplus compared to its year-earlier level
imports of aluminum, platinum, textiles, food and crude oil increased, apparently because of the yen's continued rise against the u.s. dollar and stronger domestic demand, naito said. the higher yen has raised prices of japanese exports overseas and made imports cheaper, encouraging japanese to buy more foreign goods
in 1987's january-march quarter, the current account surplus rose 65.5 percent from a year earlier. on the other hand, it declined 1.5 percent in the april-june quarter year-on-year, 13.2 percent in the july-september quarter and 15.2 percent in the october-december quarter
exports rose 16.1 percent in january from a year earlier to $17.0 billion, compared to $14.6 billion a year earlier, but down from the holiday-impacted $22.8 billion in december
imports rose 38.8 percent to $12.4 billion from $8.94 billion a year earlier
toshiaki kakimoto, chief economist for sumitomo bank ltd., said january's unadjusted 16.1 percent surge in exports was ``somewhat disturbing.''
kakimoto said japanese exporters, in part, had boosted their shipments in december and january on fears the yen would rise against the dollar and make their products less competitive
in a separate report, the japan automobile importers' association said imported cars sold in japan reached 8,212 autos in february, up 39.4 percent from the 5,890 sold in the same month last year
the number of imported autos sold in japan has increased every month since january 1984, said kunihiko ono of the association. recommendation to open bargaining early and include analyst comment.</note>
a massive protest and other strong opposition from the united auto workers union influenced chrysler corp.'s decision not to sell its acustar inc. parts-making subsidiary, the automaker says
chrysler said thursday it would keep acustar, but would close or sell four plants within the next 18 months because of their ``competitive position.''
the uaw had threatened plant-by-plant strikes if chrysler sold the subsidiary, which employs 28,000 in the united states, canada and mexico and had $3 billion in sales last year
last thursday, more than 1,000 sign-waving workers protested the proposed sale outside chrysler's highland park headquarters
furthermore, workers at chrysler plants throughout the no. 3 automaker also had stopped attending management-union meetings and participating in other joint activities since the automaker disclosed the possible sale
that played a role,'' chrysler spokesman john guiniven said of the company's decision. ``(workers) stated very strongly that they wanted to remain a part of chrysler.''
chrysler had said it was considering selling the subsidiary, which represents a fifth of its worldwide operations, because it didn't want to invest in the research needed to upgrade some operations. chrysler already buys about 70 percent of its parts from outside sources
the uaw had opposed the sale of acustar on the grounds that it would threaten the job security of all chrysler workers
we looked at all the offers, took into account the feelings of our employees and decided not to sell,'' guiniven said
we certainly welcome this announcement, since we have maintained all along that chrysler is a stronger company with its own internal parts-making capacity,'' uaw president owen bieber and uaw vice president marc stepp said in joint statement
chrysler said the four plants it plans to close or sell _ amplex van wert in van wert, ohio, trenton chemical in suburban detroit, detroit forge and detroit trim _ employ about 2,000 workers
the largest of the four plants is detroit trim, which employs 1,177 workers and makes trim for automobiles
trenton chemical employs 189 and makes chemicals used in auto paints, amplex van vert employs 333 and makes powered metal products and detroit forge employs 419 and makes forged parts
we are going to sell all four and if not, they will be closed,'' guiniven said. ``but we feel strongly that ampex and trenton chemical will be sold.''
the union would not have been able to call a national strike over the sale of acustar, but union locals were given permission to authorize strikes on a plant-by-plant basis over unresolved issues such as health and safety grievances
at least seven locals had voted to ask for strike authorization, including workers at trenton chemical. workers also had stopped participating in union-management meetings at plants throughout chrysler in protest
chrysler said it expected the company-union joint activities suspended last month would resume in the wake of its decision
bieber and stepp said they believed workers who had stayed away from the meetings probably would begin cooperating as a result of the decision
the company also said it was ready to open negotiations for a national contract to replace the agreement that expires sept. 14
stepp said thursday he would recommend to the union's 140-member chrysler council that negotiations, which normally begin in midsummer, be started early this year
it surprised me a bit that they offered to open talks early, but i'm, very interested in getting a new agreement like ford and gm that covers workers being laid off by plant closings,'' stepp said thursday night
harley shaiken, a professor and labor relations expert at the university of california at san diego, said chrysler misjudged its workers when it said acustar was up for sale
chrysler miscalculated, thinking that they might only have problems with acustar workers,'' he said. ``instead acustar became a lightning rod for union discontent throughout the corporation.''
the upjohn co. and a tokyo-based pharmaceutical company have announced a joint venture to bring japanese health products to the united states
upjohn and chugai pharmaceutical co. ltd. will form a third company, which will be named later. chugai will own 55 percent and upjohn will own the rest. the new company will be based in the united states, the companies said friday
the agreement announced today calls for chugai to license products to the new company and for upjohn to be the exclusive distributor for seven years. among the products heading for the united states are erythropoietin, which stimulates production of red blood cells, and granulocyte-colony stimulating factor, which stimulates white blood cells
they can be used to treat anemia associated with kidney dialysis and in transfusions and cancer chemotherapy
upjohn and chugai have had an excellent business relationship since 1982,'' said lawrence c. hoff, upjohn president and chief operating officer
kimio uyeno, chairman of chugai, said, ``we intend to establish our capability to develop chugai's new products and technologies through the joint venture. ..
with upjohn's help, the corporation is expected to become a fully integrated pharmaceutical company through gradual transitions in the future,'' he said
upjohn spokesman robert d. larue said the location of the new company's headquarters and its employment level haven't been decided. he declined to speculate about the new company's sales level
here are some facts about chrysler corp.'s acustar parts subsidiary. chrysler announced thursday it would not sell the subsidiary, but would close four plants in ohio and michigan instead
headquarters: warren, mich
chairman: robert a. lutz
employees: 28,000
plants: 31
products: automotive trim, heating and cooling systems, chassis systems
1987 sales: $2.9 billion
a michigan congressman is urging unionized flight attendants at northwest airlines to strike the company, saying a cooling off period has ended
rep. william ford, a democrat from taylor in suburban detroit, said thursday the teamsters union should strike the airline since talks between the two sides have reached an impasse
the demands the company are making now would provoke a strike in any factory in my district,'' said ford, whose district includes detroit metropolitan airport, one of northwest's three major hubs. the others are in minneapolis and memphis, tenn
teamsters airline division leader william genoese sr. said he met thursday with ford and michigan sen. donald riegle, also a democrat, and was pleased with their support for his union
a teamsters strike deadline passed nearly a week ago as negotiations between the minnesotat-based company and the union representing its 6,700 flight attendants continued. since then, talks have broken off and no new negotiations have been scheduled
the union has said there will be a strike, but has not said when or to what extent
the stock market declined slightly today as interest rates jumped following a stronger-than-expected report on employment
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, up more than 6 points in early trading, was down 4.47 at 2,059.02 by 11 a.m. on wall street
losers outnumbered gainers by about 6 to 5 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 544 up, 657 down and 527 unchanged
volume on the big board came to 83.35 million shares at midmorning
before the opening the labor department reported that the civilian unemployment rate dropped a tenth of a percentage point last month to an 8{-year low of 5.7 percent
nonfarm payroll employment increased by 531,000, considerably more than most advance estimates on wall street
the news was seen as an emphatic signal that the economy remains strong several months after the stock market crash last october. but it was not well received in the credit markets, where traders interpreted is as a likely portent of upward pressure on interest rates
prices of long-term government bonds fell about $15 for each $1,000 in face value, raising their yields to the 8.4-8.5 percent range
american cyanamid rose } to 54 in active trading. the stock is one of many that have been caught up in takeover rumors and speculation this week
the nyse's composite index of all its listed common stocks dropped .37 to 150.33. at the american stock exchange, the market value index was up .15 at 292.66
usair officials have agreed to buy 50 boeing 737 jetliners with options for 30 additional aircraft in a deal worth $2.4 billion
edwin colodny, usair chairman and president, said thursday the order ``is indicative of the health and vitality'' of the airline, which is headquartered at washington national airport
the 50 aircraft on order will include some of the smaller series 500 models that will be introduced by boeing in early 1989. the boeing 737s have a seating capacity ranging from 108 seats for the series 500 model to 150 seats in the series 400 jet
delivery of the new jets will begin in april 1989 and continue through december 1991
the twin-engine, short-to-medium range aircraft is the most popular jet ever sold by seattle-based boeing co. the deal with usair brings to 2,001 boeing 737s on order
usair, which traditionally has concentrated its flights in the northeast, became the fifth largest airline company last year with the acquisition of psa and piedmont. while the three airlines still operate as separate carriers there are plans to merge them into a single carrier in the future
wheat futures opened higher while other grains and soybeans opened lower today on the chicago board of trade
wheat prices advanced in reaction to the agriculture department's announcement thursday afternoon that it had sold just 1.4 million bushels of surplus wheat wednesday in the second of three auctions slated for this week, analysts said
the usda had set a target of 10 million bushels for each of the auctions, which are designed to meet increased demand by selling government-owned stocks of the grain
the agency hit its target on tuesday, but fell far short on wednesday, easing fears among traders that the increased availability of wheat could depress cash prices. another auction was scheduled for this afternoon
the usda also announced thursday that american and soviet negotiators would meet next week to start work on a new, long-term grain agreement. the announcement prompted further confidence in the wheat market, said richard loewy, an analyst in new york for prudential-bache securities inc
he said prices for future delivery of soybeans fell on technical factors while corn was nearly unchanged
in early trading, wheat was 2 cents to 2{ cents higher with the contract for delivery in march at $3.06{ a bushel; corn was unchanged to { cent lower with march at $2.00{ a bushel; oats were unchanged to 1 cent lower with march at $1.86 a bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents to 3{ cents lower with march at $6.19{ a bushel
livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading on the chicago mercantile exchange
live cattle were .10 cent lower to .18 cent higher with april at 70.52 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .35 cent higher with march at 79.25 cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to .50 cent higher with april at 42.70 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .75 cent to .88 cent higher with march at 53.05 cents a pound
cattle futures settled sharply lower on thursday. pork futures finished slightly lower
bonds prices tumbled in heavy trading and interest rates jumped sharply this morning in reaction to the government's surprisingly strong february employment report
the treasury's key 30-year issue fell more than 1{ points or $15 per $1,000 in face amount. its yield, which moves inversely to price and is a barometer of interest rate trends, surged to 8.44 percent from 8.31 percent late thursday
the deterioration is quite obviously a response to the employment situation,'' said william sullivan, director of money market research at the investment firm of dean witter reynolds inc
the labor department said the economy created half a million jobs last month, dropping the civilian unemployment rate to 5.7 percent, its lowest since the summer of 1979. the january rate had been 5.8 percent
credit-market analysts said the job-creation figure was more than twice the general estimate and suggested there would be heightening demand for credit and rising inflation, which depresses bond prices
nevertheless, some saw elements of weakness in the labor department report, particularly a slowdown in the creation of manufacturing jobs, suggesting future inventory buildups and production cutbacks
after a detailed analysis of the report filtered through the bond market, prices were likely to stabilize or recover somewhat, some analysts speculated
in the secondary market for treasury bonds, prices of short-term governments fell { point, intermediate maturities fell one point and long-term issues fell more than 1{ points, the financial information service telerate inc. reported
the movement of a point equals a change of $10 in the price of a bond with a $1,000 face value
the merrill lynch daily treasury index, which measures price movements on all outstanding treasury issues with maturities of a year or longer, fell 0.76 to 113.25. the shearson lehman daily treasury bond index, which makes a similar measurement, dropped 8.05 to 1,184.34
among corporate bonds, industrials and utilities fell between } to 1 point in heavy trading
moody's investment grade corporate bond index, which measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, fell 1.07 to 285.09
yields on three-month treasury bills jumped 13 basis points to 5.73 percent. a basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. six-month bills rose 12 basis points to 5.98 percent and year bills rose 13 basis points to 6.16 percent
the federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, traded at 6{ percent, up from 67-16 percent late thursday
tektronix inc. will lay off about 1,000 employees by may 28 to cut the growth of expenses, which has outpaced sales growth, the electronics manufacturer announced
there's just no question that we must reverse that trend to get tek back on the track to growth and profitability,'' said david p. friedley, president and chief executive officer, on friday
tektronix employs about 16,900 workers, with about 11,000 in oregon and southwest washington. most of the layoffs will affect managerial and professional workers in the portland area, the company said in a news release
the first phase of the layoffs will affect about 300 employees in the company's information display group. they were notified of the layoffs friday. employees in other divisions will be notified of their job status in the next few weeks, the company said
the layoffs follow a recent companywide review by a new management team
the reductions cause us to lose some very fine people,'' friedley said. ``their talents will be missed. but the fact is, we've been operating at less-than-maximum efficiency and our appetite for many projects and programs is greater than our pocketbook can adequately fund.''
friedley was chosen to succeed earl wantland on nov. 1. friedley's new management team was announced jan. 12
we have a number of growing, profitable businesses which are performing well, including portable oscilloscopes, television-related units, and the graphics printer and terminal division,'' friedley said. ``we are also aggressively pursuing other growth opportunities, such as telecommunications equipment, workstations and measurement systems.''
the company said it expects to record a loss for the third quarter, which ends march 5. the layoffs will result in significant expenses for severance pay and restructuring during the quarter
employees will be offered one week's severance pay for each year with the company, with a minimum of two weeks' pay
the company's sales in 1987 totaled $1.39 billion
ten employees have purchased standard chemical manufacturing co. of omaha, a 102-year-old livestock feed firm, from a group of new york and st. louis investors
the price of the leveraged buyout was not disclosed
after 98 years of profitability, the company was unprofitable the last couple of years,'' executive vice president bill dyer said
dyer and greg kluck, who becomes the seventh president in standard chemical's history, are the firm's majority owners
james m. paxson will remain as chairman, dyer said. paxson joined the company in 1953 as assistant to the president and became president in 1961
in october 1983, paxson, the majority stockholder in the employee-owned company, sold to a buying group headed by tom m. reese of st. louis, who became president, and r.b. halaby, president of ibec agri-finance co. of new york, who became chairman of the finance committee
dyer said standard chemical, which sells its feed items via the standard quality feeds label, would remain intact
standard chemical, has plants in malvern, iowa, and marshall, minn. it sells livestock feed in nebraska, iowa, wisconsin, south dakota, minnesota and montana
the company was founded in 1886 as the standard stock food co. by f.e. sanborn, a veterinarian. the company adopted its present name in 1912
