japan's toshiba corp. sold machines for making computer parts to czechoslovakia and east germany but broke off a third deal last summer after it was discovered by u.s. officials, according to congressional sources
a pentagon spokesman denied that the deals had occurred, but several members of congress said intelligence analysts have prepared reports that the illegal technology transfers did take place
toshiba has been involved over the last seven years in enhancing the microchip capability of the warsaw pact nations,'' said an aide to rep. duncan hunter, r-calif
the aide, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he had no direct knowledge of classified reports from the central intelligence agency and the military defense intelligence agency
those reports were described in today's editions of the washington times. another congressional source, also speaking on condition of anonymity, confirmed those allegations, which come six months after toshiba admitted that a subsidiary had sold the soviet union machine tools for making quiet submarine propellers, thereby neutralizing a portion of u.s. anti-submarine defenses
according to congressional sources, toshiba sold czechoslovakia a complete factory in 1979 to make computer chips, sold east germany a similar but more advanced computer-chip assembly line in 1986, and negotiated a deal for a second assembly line in east germany in 1987
the deals have become known as toshiba 2, toshiba 3 and toshiba 4. toshiba 1 is the submarine case
a pentagon spokesman, col, arnold williams, said that ``the information that we have is that we feel these actions, toshiba 2, 3 and 4, have not occurred.''
williams said he was unable to discuss the cia and dia reports
officials in the office of stephen bryen, the deputy undersecretary of defense for trade security, also declined to discuss the allegations
according to congressional sources, the czechoslovak deal was of questionable legality, and the 1986 east germany deal was illegal under western export laws
defenders say the first deal was legal, the second never happened and in the third instance, toshiba voluntarily acted out of public-relations concerns to halt what would have been a legal sale
toshiba attorney david houlihan called the allegations the result of a ''vendetta'' by a group of cia analysts against toshiba and japan, according to the published report
as a result of the sale to the soviet bloc, house and senate conferees are working on a bill that could ban toshiba sales in the united states for two to five years, said duncan's aide
the congressman has organized classified briefings for about 30 lawmakers by cia and dia analysts who are convinced that the transactions did occur, said the aide
intelligence officials have confirmed them to our satisfaction,'' said the aide
there has been a lot of pressure from the administration'' not to damage trade relations with japan, said the aide. ``the strength of the conflict between the congress and the administration is intense.''
american standard inc. today intensified a struggle to escape a hostile $2.1 billion takeover from black &amp; decker corp. by sweetening a rival recapitalization plan that analysts valued at about $2.3 billion
the move disclosed by the new york-based plumbing and air conditioning giant would add $5 cash to the payment of cash and securities that american standard has offered shareholders to woo them away from the $68-a-share cash payment black &amp; decker has offered for each of the target's 31 million shares
wall street analysts figured the sweetened american standard offer of $64 in cash, $5 in debt securities and one share of stock in the recapitalized company was worth about $74 a share. the company's stock surged $1.50 a share to $70.12{ on the new york stock exchange by early afternoon
black &amp; decker, a tool and appliance maker based in towson, md., said it was studying the sweetened american standard offer but had no other comment
american standard's move came a few days after it disclosed discussions with unidentified parties regarding the possible sale of debt securities to sweeten the cash portion of its recapitalization
under the revised proposal, american standard will sell $160 million worth of debt securities to emerson electric co. as part of the transaction, american standard also will purchase some unidentified products from emerson, a st. louis-based maker of electronics, tools and cooling and heating systems
a recapitalization, in which a company restructures its amount of debt and equity, is used often to thwart unwelcome takeovers. the strategy usually plunges a company into debt, making it less attractive as an acquisition
american standard's revised plan, which would raise the company's long-term debt from $412 million to about $2.46 billion, would pay shareholders about $2.06 billion plus give them a stake in the recapitalized company
black &amp; decker has been attempting since late january to acquire american standard. 110,000 to 10,000. also moving on general news wires</note>
the nation's economy created half a million jobs last month, dropping the civilian unemployment rate to 5.7 percent, its lowest since the summer of 1979, the government said today
total employment grew by 280,000, the labor department's monthly household survey said, with the number of jobless americans falling by 108,000 to 6.9 million
january's civilian jobless rate had been 5.8 percent
presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater applauded the news, saying that ``these strong employment gains confirm that the longest peacetime expansion in u.s. history continued into its 63rd month. jobs are the best indicator of a sound economy.''
a separate survey of business payrolls showed a net increase of 531,000 jobs in february, 40 percent of which were in service industries. health services added 60,000 workers while business services added 55,000
retail trade employment, adjusted for seasonal variations, climbed by 110,000 despite evidence of declines in consumer spending
the commissioner of labor statistics, janet l. norwood, said the gains in retail-trade employment reflect ``post-christmas cutbacks this year that have been much smaller than usual.''
the only service industries that did not show job gains were finance, insurance and real estate. in fiance, which includes banks; savings and loans, and investment houses, employment actually fell by 10,000 after several months of minimal increases
this probably resulted from the employment retrenchment following last october's financial market upheavels,'' ms. norwood told the congressional joint economic committee
meanwhile, factory job growth, which had been averaging 50,000 jobs a month, moderated in february, with a gain of just 20,000. employment in the furniture and electronic equipment industries fell by 3,000 while automobile industry employment held steady at 822,000
construction jobs jumped by 105,000 after a drop of 60,000 in the preceding month
the percentage of the nation's adult population with jobs rose to a record 62.2 percent in february. the labor department said recent job growth has been particularly strong in the administrative and management areas, accounting for more than one-third of the growth of 3 million jobs in total civilian employment over the last year
the biggest beneficiary of that trend and the recent rebound in manufacturing and construction has been adult men, whose jobless rate has dropped from 5.8 percent in february 1987 to 4.9 percent last month
the jobless rate for women, also at 5.8 percent a year ago, was 5.2 percent in february
jobless rates for minority groups remained high despite the fact that blacks and hispanics have obtained one of every three new jobs over the last year
black unemployment, at 12.6 percent last month, was more than double the 4.8 percent for whites. hispanic unemployment, after declining to 7.2 percent in january, bounced back to 8.3 percent last month to return to the level that generally prevailed through most of the last half of 1987
teenage unemployment fell from 16.0 percent to 15.4 percent last month. among white teenagers, the rate fell from 14.0 percent to 12.4 percent; among black teens, the rate rose from 35.0 percent to 38.3 percent
an alternate jobless rate, including the 1.7 million members of the uniformed armed services stationed in the united states, also dropped 0.1 percentage point last month, to 5.6 percent
all the calculations are adjusted to discount for predictable, periodic influences
with more than a half-million new jobs last month, the nation's civilian unemployment rate dropped to 5.7 percent, the government said friday, indicating a much stronger u.s. economy than most analysts had thought
only once since 1974 _ in may 1979 when the rate was 5.6 percent _ has the percentage of jobless americans been lower. with a one-tenth percentage point drop from december's and january's jobless rates of 5.8 percent, the rolls of the unemployed declined by 108,000 in february to just over 6.9 million, the lowest jobless number since early 1980
the bureau of labor statistics said its survey of households showed 280,000 more americans going to work last month, with an all-time record 62.2 percent of the nation's working-age population _ age 16 and over _ now holding jobs
business and other employers reported in a separate survey increasing their payrolls by a net 531,000 new jobs _ 115,000 of them in business and health services, 110,000 in retail trade, 105,000 in construction, 68,000 in government and 20,000 in manufacturing
these numbers have killed all discussion about no growth this quarter,'' said james cochran, chief economist for texas bancshares in houston
the economy is doing pretty well,'' cochran said. ``and to everyone's surprise, the strength is coming from basic domestic activity rather than companies hiring people to produce things to sell overseas.''
donald straszheim, chief economist for merrill lynch, said the february job numbers were the most surprising economic statistics he has ever seen
there's 400,000 more people working now than we had thought,'' he said. ``the housing market is weak, construction is weak and, except for automobiles, consumers don't seem to be buying anything. some of it just doesn't make any sense.''
nonetheless, straszheim joined a chorus of other economists in saying that the unemployment report effectively negates their earlier predictions of little or no economic growth this year
this report makes it clear there is no recession in the cards,'' said allen sinai, chief economist for the boston co., a new york-based financial consultant. ``the real question is how much steam the economy will gather. as incomes start flowing from this surge in jobs, the future looks pretty bright.''
the jobless report shines brightest on republican presidential candidates seeking to retain gop control of the white house, the economic gurus agreed
the economic statistic that has more political import than any other is unemployment,'' said straszheim, ``and this is a very strong report.''
george bush ought to be running over to kiss the people at the bureau of labor statistics,'' said david wyss, chief financial economist of data resources inc. of lexington, mass. ``people vote their pocketbooks, and right now their pocketbooks look pretty full.''
at the white house, reagan administration officials also basked in the numbers
both the february increase in employment and the decline in unemployment exceeded the expectations of private forecasters,'' white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said. ``jobs are the best indicator of a sound economy.''
sinai said the unemployment rate, down from a full percentage point from 12 months ago, can only be a ``big plus for republicans.''
it certainly doesn't argue that we need protectionism to help our job market,'' said wyss, referring to rep. richard gephardt's campaign theme for winning the democratic presidential nomination
democrats, however, could utilize some of the figures in the report. despite inflation running at an annual rate of 4.2 percent so far this year, average wages dropped by 2 cents last month to $9.12 an hour, the bls said
that's both bad and good news,'' straszheim said. ``if you're working, it means your wages aren't keeping you up. but if you're fearful about inflation, don't be.''
the figures also indicate that 199,000 of the 280,000 increase in the number of americans holding jobs were people working part-time only because they could not find full-time employment
however, the labor department said recent employment growth has been strongest in high-wage administrative and management occupations, accounting for more than one-third of the 3 million new jobs in the past year
the biggest beneficiaries of that trend and the recent rebound in manufacturing and construction employment have been adult men, whose jobless rate has dropped from 5.8 percent in february 1987 to 4.9 percent last month
the jobless rate for women, also at 5.8 percent a year ago, was 5.2 percent in february
jobless rates for minority groups remained high despite the fact that blacks and hispanics have obtained one of every three new jobs over the last year, the government said
black unemployment, at 12.6 percent last month, was more than double the 4.8 percent for whites. hispanic unemployment, after declining to 7.2 percent in january, rose to 8.3 percent last month
an alternate jobless rate, including the 1.7 million members of the uniformed armed services stationed in the united states, also dropped 0.1 percentage point last month, to 5.6 percent. venture</head>
government and construction industry officials friday expressed regret over a u.s. refusal to award a contract to a joint venture between japanese and american construction firms for a subway extension project in the united states
it is indeed regrettable that a concerned japanese firm was excluded'' from an american public works project at a time when japanese and u.s. officials in washington are discussing opening some of japan's large-scale construction projects to u.s. firms, said chief cabinet secretary keizo obuchi in a nationally televised news conference
the washington metropolitan area transit authority thursday rejected a bid from kajima corp., a major japanese contractor, together with peter kiewit and sons corp. of the united states, to construct a 1,200-meter subway tunnel and station in washington d.c., officials said
according to the japan broadcasting corp. (nhk), it was the first time a japanese construction firm involved in bidding for an american public works project was rejected since the u.s. congress last year passed legislation calling for reciprocity in awarding such contracts
local reports said the bid by the two companies totaled 6.3 billion yen, or $48.8 million, the lowest offer among an unspecified number of international bidders
hajime sako, chairman of the japan federation of construction contractors inc., said in a statement that ``...the fact that the japanese firm's tender was actually canceled is extremely regrettable.''
sako, also chairman of taisei corp., a major japanese construction firm, said the local construction industry ``strongly hopes the latest u.s. measure will be retracted as soon as possible, and that such a measure, which will adversely affect friendly japan-u.s. relations, will not be taken again.''
kishio nagayama, president of kajima engineering and construction inc., a wholly owned u.s. subsidiary based in los angeles, california, that handled the latest bidding, also expressed regret over the decision
in a statement issued by the company's head office in tokyo, nagayama said his company will decide how to respond by consulting with its u.s. partner
japanese and u.s. officials resumed working-level talks in washington thursday to discuss access to japan's large-scale construction projects. both sides failed to reach agreement in a previous meeting held in tokyo last month
access to the japanese construction market has been a major trade issue in recent years between the two countries. to date, u.s. firms have had access to only two semi-public projects in japan _ the tokyo bay bridge and the multi-billion dollar kansai international airport project
japanese firms won about $2.3 billion worth of contracts in the united states in 1986, while u.s. companies did about $500 million dollars worth of business in japan, according to construction officials
the stock market declined broadly today as interest rates jumped following a stronger-than-expected report on employment
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, up more than 6 points in early trading, was down 17.90 at 2,045.59 by 2 p.m. on wall street
losers outnumbered gainers by nearly 2 to 1 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 495 up, 943 down and 466 unchanged
before the opening the labor department reported that the civilian unemployment rate dropped a tenth of a percentage point last month to an 8{-year low of 5.7 percent
nonfarm payroll employment increased by 531,000, considerably more than most advance estimates on wall street
the news was seen as an emphatic signal that the economy remains strong several months after the stock market crash last october. but it was not well received in the credit markets, where traders interpreted is as a likely portent of upward pressure on interest rates
prices of long-term government bonds fell more than $15 for each $1,000 in face value, raising their yields to the 8.4-8.5 percent range
among actively traded blue-chip industrials, american telephone &amp; telegraph fell [ to 28}; eastman kodak ] to 43[; ford motor ] to 45|, and general electric ~ to 43~
the nyse's composite index of all its listed common stocks dropped 1.21 to 149.49. at the american stock exchange, the market value index was down .81 at 291.70
volume on the big board came to 151.84 million shares with two hours to go
