the century-old wente bros. winery has completed its first shipment of wine for japan's bullet train, the winery reported on friday
the delivery to japan railways marks the first order of american wine by the toyota motor co., according to debra sanchez, spokeswoman for toyota motor sales, u.s.a
it's just the beginning,'' she said. ``the japanese are falling in love with california wines.''
the first order was for 29,000 mini-bottles of chablis, blanc de blancs, and white zinfandel, chosen after exhaustive taste tests of the livermore winery's 14 wines, said toyota motor sales u.s.a. vice president robert best
exporting california wines to japan is another example of toyota's commitment to increase japanese purchases of u.s. products,'' said best
i'm excited, not only for wente brothers but the entire california wine industry,'' said wente spokeswoman carolyn wente. her ancestor, carl wente, acquired his first vineyards in livermore in 1883, growing sauvignon blanc and semillon grapes. wente whites have been sold in the united states for 100 years
the wines for japan were chosen for their expected popularity on the trains. the choices virtually parallel american popular tastes. the blanc de blancs is a light, sweet blend that includes chenin blanc. chablis is regarded around the world as the typical dry white table wine
wente has been exporting small amounts of wine to japan for 20 years but thwarted by extremely high tariffs that found a bottle of wine that sold for $4 in califoria selling for $18-20 in japan. the taxes were lowered a couple of years ago, and the retail price in japan is now reported to be about double the california price
the united states today already is the second largest exporter of wine to japan, behind france, with germany in third
best said toyota acted in this instance as a broker ordering the wine, exporting it and selling it to the railway in japan
the 6.3-ounce bottles will be sold on the 120 mph trains that travel from tokyo. the wines will go for about $2.50 each, he said
toyota established a u.s. exports office in 1985 to search out american products appropriate for the japanese market and to reduce the u.s. deficit in the balance of payments, best said. wente is the first u.s. wine taken on by toyota, he said
there has been a doubling in japanese consumption of wine over the last several years, and wine sales have grown over 400 percent in the last five years,'' said best
the u.s. dollar fell against most major currencies in european trading friday. gold prices rose nearly $10 an ounce in london and $3 in zurich
merrill lynch metals specialist ted arnold said gold bullion climbed to $437.50 bid per troy ounce because of a short-covering rally and a dip in monthly u.s. unemployment figures. gold closed at 427.80 an ounce late thursday
he said the figures, which showed that the february rate fell to 5.7 percent from 5.8 percent in january, rekindled fears of inflation
in zurich, gold rose less sharply, to $432 bid an ounce, from $429 dollars, on short-covering prompted by gains in silver and platinum, dealers said
in a short sale, traders sell borrowed gold in expectation of ``covering'' those sales by replacing the gold with new lots bought at cheaper prices
foreign exchange dealers said u.s. unemployment figures briefly pushed up the u.s. currency but the improvement in the rate was not enough to have a lasting effect on the dollar
in tokyo, the dollar inched lower to a closing 129.22 japanese yen from 129.30 yen. in london, it fell further to 128.95 yen
other late dollar rates in europe, compared with late thursday, were: 1.6940 west german marks, down from 1.6955; 1.4030 swiss francs, down from 1.4035; 5.7300 french francs, down from 5.7355; 1.9010 dutch guilders, down from 1.9025; 1,248.00 italian lire, down from 1,249.25, and 1.2547 canadian dollars, up from 1.2535
in london, the british pound rose to $1.7740 from $1.7680 late thursday
earlier, in hong kong, gold fell $1.67 to a closing bid of $431.27
silver bullion rose in london to a bid price of $6.41 a troy ounce, up from $6.22 bid late thursday
the biggest investment-grade corporate bond issue ever sold in the united states _ $1.1 billion in 10-year notes _ went off with picture-perfect ease this past week
and experts say they weren't surprised since the seller was eastman kodak co., which priced the issue generously to compensate for a recent drop in its credit rating
a lot of people love to own the name ...,'' explained anthony naylor, a senior vice president in fixed-income securities for rodman &amp; renshaw inc. ``but they've always had to pay through the nose before.''
the record issue _ undertaken partly to help finance kodak's recent $5.1 billion acquisition of sterling drug inc. _ was priced at par to yield 9.125 percent, a percentage point more than comparable treasury securities
the 10-year notes are noncallable for seven years and rated a-2 by moody's investors service and a-minus by standard &amp; poor's corp
both wall street rating services lowered kodak's senior debt rating in response to the sterling deal and legal problems with polaroid corp. over an instant photography patent
but analysts say that probably added to the allure of the $1.1 billion issue because the lower the rating a company receives, the higher the interest it must pay to compensate for the increased credit risk
it was very generously priced,'' said naylor of the notes, noting that previous issues by the blue-chip company have had a much narrower yield spread
for instance, kodak's $300 million in four-year notes issued in october yielded 60 basis points above treasury securities with similar maturities, and $125 million in five-year notes from last spring had only a 25-basis point spread, he said. a basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point
naylor said the fact that the issue was so large also contributed to its success since ``everyone can get in and play, giving it plenty of liquidity,'' or the ability to sell at any time without depressing the market price
kodak also came out ahead by the fact that the bonds were sold at par, or the full face amount. in less successful deals, bonds are sold at a discount to increase their attractiveness
the rochester, n.y., company originally had planned to sell only $750 million in 10-year notes, but increased the size by $350 million because of the strong demand by domestic institutions, explained richard w. swift, a principal at morgan stanley &amp; co., underwriters of the issue
i think it was one of the hottest deals i ever experienced,'' he said, adding that one institution snapped up $75 million of the notes. ``there's magic to the kodak name.''
some analysts said the popularity of the issue could be read as a vote of confidence in kodak's management and its ability to digest the sterling deal, which had been criticized as overly ambitious by some who follow the company
before this past week's issue, the single largest issue by a u.s. corporation with investment-grade ratings came from occidental petroleum corp., which sold $1 billion of debentures in march 1986, swift said. about two years earlier, chevron corp. sold $1 billion in three-year notes, he said
kodak filed a shelf registration dec. 30 with the securities and exchange commission for $1.5 billion worth of bonds. the company has $400 million left from that registration
when new postage rates go into effect, americans will be using special ``e'' stamps on an interim basis to mail first-class letters
the stamps were printed with the letter e on them, instead of the amount of postage, because the new first-class rate was not known
the postal rate commission on friday suggested postage rate increases that included a 25-cent first-class stamp, but those recommendations still must be accepted by the postal service board of governors. the new rates could go into effect in 10 days to two weeks after a decision is made, perhaps as early as next week
a similar procedure has been used four times in the past, although the basic design of the undenominated stamp has changed
the a, b, c and d stamps all showed the head of an eagle, each in a different color
the e stamp carries a multicolored, space-based image of the plant with the word earth printed beneath
the stamp also carries the notation ``domestic'' since it can be used only for mail within the country. mail traveling to other nations requires stamps that show their demoninations
international business machines corp. confirmed friday it has discussed a deal involving its new personal computer line with siemens ag of west germany, but said the executive who made the talks public ``feels his comment on siemens was premature and inappropriate.''
ibm's unusual statement was in reaction to an article friday in the wall street journal that quoted william c. lowe, the vice president in charge of personal computers, on ibm's plans for its personal system-2 line
siemens executives ``were very disturbed by what appeared in the journal,'' but the statement friday will probably help matters, said martin weitzner, a spokesman for siemens' u.s. operations
according to the journal, lowe said that if a pact was reached, siemens would either license or buy from ibm the crucial parts of ibm's ps-2 line and incorporate them into its own computers. lowe said it was even possible that some companies might buy ps-2 computers whole and sell them under their own labels
the journal said ibm was in similar talks with ing. c. olivetti &amp; co. of italy, but ibm said that lowe had only mentioned olivetti as an example of a company that could be considered
such deals would be a major departure for ibm, which traditionally keeps a tight grip on its own technology. but they might benefit the company by helping establish the personal system-2 as an industry standard
irving bank corp., the target of a hostile $1.08 billion takeover bid, said friday it plans to appeal the federal reserve board's recent decision to allow a proposed merger with bank of new york co
irving filed a notice of appeal in the u.s. court of appeals for the district of the columbia earlier this week, saying it would ask the court to reviw the central bank's decision, irving spokesman don phelps said
he said irving also asked the fed to delay the effect of its ruling until the appeals court can review it
irving has rejected takeover efforts by bank of new york, which has offered $60 a share in cash and securities for irving's 18.1 million common shares
the takeover fight, launched last fall, has attracted attention because hostile acquisitions are unusual in banking. some analysts speculate that if it succeeds, it may encourage other unsolicited takeovers in the banking industry
the fed and the new york state banking board concluded last month that a merger of the two new york banks wouldn't hurt competition in the nation's biggest financial center
the central bank said federal law ``does not draw any distinction between acquisitions that are agreed to between the parties and those where, as here, there is no agreement.''
a merger would create the nation's 12th largest banking company with assets of nearly $12 billion
the stock market retreated today as interest rates jumped following a stronger-than-expected report on employment
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, up more than 6 points in early trading, was down 15.08 at 2,048.41 by 3 p.m. on wall street
losers outnumbered gainers by about 8 to 5 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 559 up, 897 down and 481 unchanged
before the opening the labor department reported that the civilian unemployment rate dropped a tenth of a percentage point last month to an 8{-year low of 5.7 percent
nonfarm payroll employment increased by 531,000, considerably more than most advance estimates on wall street
the news was seen as an emphatic signal that the economy remains strong several months after the stock market crash last october. but it was not well received in the credit markets, where traders interpreted is as a likely portent of upward pressure on interest rates
prices of long-term government bonds fell more than $15 for each $1,000 in face value, raising their yields to the 8.4-8.5 percent range
among actively traded blue-chip industrials, exxon fell | to 41|; eastman kodak | to 42~; ford motor \ to 45}, and general electric 1 to 43}
